<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Babes in the Wood, Magnum Centre, Irvine</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mary Brennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766082</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SADLY, the real pantomime has been happening off stage here. A precipitate
parting of ways between the company and its artistic director - our news hounds
have been reporting on this - meant Borderline found themselves caught with
their panto down . . . and the curtain ready to go up. Ofpants, the official
panto watchdog, does not intend to comment on the background situation - which
seems as thorny as Carabosse's wicked wood - since his province is essentially
what appears before the public. So what did the checklist look like after an
afternoon with Babes in the Wood?
Definitely checkered. A rash of black spots, a bristle of question marks, and a
smattering of ticks, occasionally followed by the letters BTCOD. ``Beyond The
Call Of Duty,'' explained Ofpants tersely.
Most folk look and behave as if they'd accidentally tried on a costume and then
found themselves on stage, but Deborah Young and Jane McCarry actually manage
to make the sudden plunges into Scotch myths and music bearable, while Billy
Riddoch (BTCOD with !*) walked on at a few hours' notice and made Silly Billy
the absolute touchstone of merriment and warm humanity in a piece that
desperately needed both. The audience, mainly schoolchildren, were remarkably
amenable. ``I suppose it's better than doing quadratic equations,'' I
volunteered. ``Oh no it's not,'' said Ofpants, opening his Herald at the
Situations Vacant . . .
P
</TEXT>
