<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Three killed in yard blast</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766083</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THREE workmen were killed when an explosion rocked an engineering yard on
Tyneside.
Four other workers were injured in the blast at the Howdon yard of engineering
firm Amec.
The firm is understood to make plant for the offshore oil industry, near the
northern end of the River Tyne tunnel.
The explosion is thought to have occurred during a pressure-testing operation
at the plant.
A spokeswoman for the Northumbria police said: ``Three persons have
subsequently died and the other four are being treated for minor injuries and
shock.
``No names are being released as we are informing relatives at the moment.''
An ambulance spokesman said the casualties were taken to North Tyneside general
hospital for treatment.
Nine fire appliances were called to the yard.
The explosion took place in a pressurised container at the oil rig construction
complex.
The cause of the explosion was not known but it was not thought to be
suspicious.
Factory inspectors have been notified.
</TEXT>
