<HEADLINE>Cinderella, Perth Theatre, Perth</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sara Villiers</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766084</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TTHEY'RE all charming, not just the Prince. Andrew McKinnon has firmly opted
for traditional family fun in his theatre's version of the tale of the insipid
kitchen wench. Accordingly there's a welcome lack of the kind of smutty double
entendre which is increasingly plaguing some of the glossier productions.
As usual, the soppy stuff is boring but the comic turns are tremendous, with
fabulous performances from Ian Greive and John Ramage as the Ugly Sisters,
Bianca and Samantha. That EastEnders reference aside, there isn't a lot of
contemporaneous comedy, although a boisterous Gladiators-themed work-out class
from the aesthetically challenged siblings certainly got the audience roaring.
Young Philip Carroll and Lewis Christie provide further knock-about humour as
the double act Dun and Dee - together they're Dundee United, groan, groan.
They're more Tweedledee and Tweedledum than a Dumb and Dumber duo.
Paul Nivinson plays Buttons with winsome cuteness and the right smattering of
pathos, immediately winning our sympathies with the admission that when they
played doctors and nurses at school he was always the ambulance driver. With
credentials like that he'll clearly never get the girl.
All the panto staples are there, from fuzzy animals whizzing across the stage
to the skulking skeleton, the sing-along with actions, and the wedding finale.
The cast generate enough exuberance to ensure that everyone joins in - and the
only reason that this critic didn't participate in the ``wriggling song'' was
because of a phobia about a certain animal. That was the only alarming moment
in a fun-packed entertaining show which ably proved that sometimes old jokes
really are the best.
</TEXT>
