<HEADLINE>Clock change `will save lives'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766085</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PUTTING the clocks forward by one hour permanently would have saved 110 lives
lost on the roads last year, according to new Government estimates.
A total of 2080 road casualties would have been avoided including 590 serious
injuries, say figures given by junior Transport Minister Steven     Norris.
The news was hailed by supporters of a Commons Bill to change the clocks and
intro- duce so-called ``double summer time''.
Campaigners for the idea say it would produce an extra usable hour in the
summer, cut road accidents and bring Britain into line with its European
partners.
Tory MP John Butterfill is to introduce his Private Member's British Time
(Extra Daylight) Bill to the Commons on January 19.
However, the Scots, who would be plunged into darkness for most of the morning
in the winter, oppose the scheme and it has been reported that the Cabinet has
decided not to support the back-bench measure. Mr Norris published the new
figures in a Commons written reply to Labour MP Keith Hill.
He said the estimates were produced by the Transport Research Laboratory and
were based on a test conducted in 1968-71 when summer time continued throughout
the year.
He said the figures covered the whole of Britain and could not show what might
happen in any particular region of the country where special circumstances may
exist.
</TEXT>
