<HEADLINE>`Christmas miracle' after Colombia suffers its worst aviation tragedy 17 survive airliner crash</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GILLES CASTONGUAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766086</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Buga, Colombia, Thursday
AS many as 17 people, including a family of four, were rescued from the
wreckage of an American Airlines jet that crashed into a mountain in southwest
Colombia, Caracol radio said today.
It did not give an exact breakdown of the survivors amid the many conflicting
reports from the remote crash site in the guerrilla-infested region of Valle
del Cauca province. The aircraft was en route from Miami to Cali in Colombia.
In what one commentator described as a true ``Christmas miracle,'' Caracol
quoted hospital officials as saying the survivors included a husband and wife,
identified as Gonzalo and Nancy Dussan Delgado, and their two young children.
One of the survivors, 19-year-old student Mauricio Reyes, was rescued by his
older brother Juan Carlos, who rushed to the site on the slopes of the 12,000ft
San Jose mountain last night.
Overcome by emotion, Juan Carlos praised the Virgin Mary for what he told
reporters was a ``miracle.''
As rescue teams searched the remote mountainside crash site, emergency workers
said local residents who reached the wreck first had gone through luggage and
stripped valuables off corpses. Three looters were reported arrested.
Caracol said the survivors also included a girl about seven years old who had
been found trapped in the wreckage of the Boeing 757 jet.
A dense fog and driving rain forced the suspension of rescue operations late
this afternoon amid protests from grieving family members.
The accident was the most deadly involving a US carrier since the 1988 bombing
of PanAm flight 103 over Lockerbie that killed 270 people.
It was also the worst in Colombian history and took place within hours of the
December 21, 1988, anniversary of the Lockerbie crash.
Alvaro Cala, head of Colombia's Civil Aviation department, said he could not
rule out sabotage. He also stressed that aircraft navigation radio beacons in
the area had all been in good working order last night.
The plane was flying at 9000 ft when the crash occurred, Cala said, adding the
flight recorder had still not been located more than 15 hours after the
accident.
In Forth Worth, Texas, American Airlines chairman Robert Crandall told
reporters the crash site was ``somewhat to the east of the course line''
normally set for approaches to Cali, Colombia's third largest city about four
minutes flying time from the crash site.
The plane was carrying 156 passengers, including four infants, and a crew of
eight. It went down in an area dominated by leftist guerrillas, who have
targeted radio beacons for sabotage attacks in the past. The beacons, usually
located on towers or mountaintops, emit radio signals that help pilots map
their location.
Radio reports said at least 10 American citizens were believed to have been
aboard the fatal flight, including its pilot and co-pilot and Francisco Ferre,
a son of former Miami Mayor Mauricio Ferre.
Boeing officials in Seattle, who sent a team of investigators to Colombia, said
the crash was the first ever involving the twin-engine 757, which entered
commercial service in January 1983.
Just last month, the US Federal Aviation Authority downgraded its assessment of
Colombia's civil air authority to a conditional safety rating after it found
shortcomings in its international safety standards. -- Reuter.
</TEXT>
