<HEADLINE>Education funding `crisis'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766087</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE leader of Scotland's biggest teachers' union, the EIS, has called for a
meeting with Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth to discuss what he describes as
a growing crisis in education funding.
Mr Forsyth's announcement of a standstill education budget would only add to
the problems which were about to confront the new unitary authorities, said Mr
Ronnie Smith.
``There exists now an unprecedented threat to the level of educational
provision which com- munities in Scotland have come to expect and deserve,'' he
said.
Private Funding Initiatives for capital building programmes were an unknown
quantity for parents, pupils, students, and local authorities, which merited
proper funding, he continued.
Mr Smith contrasted the standstill budget with the recent announcement by
Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke of additional resources.
Also, he criticised the planned expansion of the assisted places scheme for
private schools which could eventually cost #9m a year, on top of the existing
annual allocation of more than #10m.
He said it served to indicate ``that the Government priority is not one which
the overwhelming number of parents would endorse''.
In a letter to Mr Forsyth, Mr Smith wrote: ``I am sure that you will recognise
the urgency of the matter.'' That was why he wanted to discuss the impact of a
cut in real terms on schools, universities, and colleges, he said.
</TEXT>
