<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cock's crow on after Christmas reprieve</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766088</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COUPLE who were ordered to silence their noisy cockerels have won a partial
Christmas reprieve.
Ken and Julie Ayres were told by a court to get rid of three of their four
birds - and build an 8ft high fence around their farm-style property following
complaints from neighbours.
Dumbarton District Court JP Richard Dickson had originally insisted that the
Ayres comply with the demands before December 25.
However, he didn't realise that any fence over 6ft 6ins required special
planning permission from the local council.
Yesterday, he deferred the order for four months to give the Ayres until
mid-April next year to erect the enclosure - providing the council permission
is granted.
The Ayres have been told that their planning application must be lodged with
Dumbarton District Council by next Friday.
However, Mrs Ayres, of Strone House, Glen Fruin, Dunbartonshire, said: ``We are
supposed to include three builders' quotes for the work. We have written to
three but each one has been too busy to give us one.''
She added: ``The whole business with the fence is quite ludicrous anyway.
``How can a wire-mesh fence possibly affect the amount of noise which travels
through the air?''
</TEXT>
