<DOCNO>GH951222-000008</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000008</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lang urged to resign over HCI `failings'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DUNCAN BLACK, STEPHEN McGREGOR, Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766089</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OPPOSITION parties yesterday demanded that former Scottish Secretary Ian Lang
resign from his current Cabinet post after the Public Accounts Committee
published a scathing report on the handling of the Health Care International
private hospital project at Clydebank.
The committee found that #37m of public money had been spent in support of a
scheme where the company had gone into receivership just a few months after the
hospital was officially opened.
It added there had been insufficient evaluation of the major risks involved and
inadequate monitoring of the worsening financial problems; there had been an
outright loss of #8.4m to the taxpayer; and the hospital was still operating at
a level far below that originally envisaged.
The founders of the #180m hospital complex hoped it would attract several
thousand overseas patients a year and employ as many as 1800 staff. However,
the scheme had to be saved from collapse early this year when it was bought by
the Abu Dhabi Investment Company, a shareholder in the original project.
Both the Scottish Office Industry Department and the Scottish Enterprise agency
were severely criticised in yesterday's Public Accounts Committee (PAC) report,
which stated: ``We consider that all concerned should have taken a tighter grip
on this project.''
Labour responded to the report by calling for the resignation of Mr Lang, now
President of the Board of Trade and Industry.
Scottish health spokesman John McAllion said: ``Ministers must not attempt to
hide behind criticisms of their departments or agencies. They are directly
accountable for the failings identified by the committee.
``Ian Lang was the Minister most closely identified with the HCI project. He
initially sought to take the credit for it and then tried to make excuses for
it when it went wrong.
``This damning report is a direct condemnation of his role as a Minister. He is
the Cabinet Minister now directly responsible for Regional Selective Assistance
which was so wantonly wasted on this project. He has to go, there is no other
honourable way out.''
The resignation call was echoed by the Scottish National Party, whose
parliamentary health spokesperson, Mrs Margaret Ewing, said: ``The Government
stands condemned of wasting vast sums of taxpayers' money on an unsustainable
and unwanted ideological experiment.
``Ministers allowed themselves to be blinded by their bankrupt ideology and
must face up to the consequences. As the Minister most closely associated with
the HCI fiasco, Ian Lang should now tender his resignation.
``If he does not, then it will simply confirm that the Tories are incapable of
governing in the public interest but are thirled to a narrow, and failed,
anti-Scottish agenda.''
For the Scottish Liberal Democrats, Mr Robert Maclennan, a senior member of the
PAC, said: ``This costly episode was a triumph of dogmatism over prudence. The
Scottish Office threw millions of pounds of taxpayers' money at an unsound
private medical initiative. This is the kind of
Government enterprise Scotland can well do without.''
PAC chairman Robert Sheldon said there should have been much more thorough
market research internationally before the project went ahead on the scale
envisaged. He was also critical of the lack of adequate monitoring as the
hospital's financial problems worsened, adding: ``The board only met a few
times a year. With the level of crisis we saw, there was a case for meeting a
few times a week.''
Scottish Office Industry Minister George Kynoch said the PAC report made a
number of recommendations which the Government would review carefully ``to see
what lessons can be learned from this case''. The formal response would be
issued in due course in the form of a Treasury minute.
``However, this one project has to be viewed in the context of the Government's
policy of seeking to attract to the UK investment in a range of projects which
will broaden and strengthen our economic base, thereby creating and
safeguarding jobs.
``Clearly such a policy carries risks but these have to be considered as part
of its overall impact, which when viewed as a whole, is clearly very
successful.''
He added: ``The HCI story is of course not concluded, as the PAC report
acknowledges. The hospital remains in business, employing over 450 staff at
Clydebank, has benefited from major investment by its new operators, and
continues to pursue its target markets. Indeed, it only recently announced the
signing of a major contract for the treatment of Algerian patients.''
A Scottish Enterprise spokesman said yesterday that the agency was considering
the recommendations in the report and would advise the Scottish Office of its
response.
Clydebank and Milngavie Labour MP Tony Worthington said: ``The report makes it
clear that the Government did no work of its own to evaluate the market. It
simply took the word of others who were seeking public money. The PAC said
there should have been a tighter grip. That is putting it mildly. There was no
grip at all.''
Public service union Unison said the report vindicated all the union's earlier
warnings about the HCI project.
Mr John Lambie, the union's Scottish head of health, said: ``What is especially
galling is that the really guilty men - Malcolm Rifkind and Ian Lang (both
former Scottish Secretaries) - have been rewarded with promotion to national
level, and Michael Forsyth, who was Scottish Minister for Health at the time,
is now Scottish Secretary.''
He added that the HCI hospital was now competing with NHS hospitals for NHS
contracts. The management at the HCI hospital refused to make any comment on
the report on the grounds that it related to management prior to receivership.
A company spokesman said the hospital's new owner, the Abu Dhabi Investment
Company, was happy with the current situation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
