<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Egyptian train disaster kills at least 75</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766090</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN the worst disaster on the accident-prone Egyptian railways for more than 15
years, 75 people were killed and 76 injured today when a crowded train ran into
the back of another in thick fog.
Eyewitnesses in the town of Badrasheen, 17 miles south of the capital Cairo,
said an early-morning train taking about 120 workers south to the town of Beni
Suef rammed a train to Assiut city from behind at high speed.
One carriage rode up on top of the others and two derailed, one of them onto
wooden stalls by the side of the track.
The driver of the second train, Mahmoud Ali, said the first train should not
have been there and he saw no red signal as he came to the last level crossing
before the crash.
Ali has had his right leg amputated from the knee down in Badrasheen hospital
and could hardly speak.
``I saw fog all around,'' he mumbled. ``I am not meant to stop at this place. I
was astounded by what happened.''
Another survivor, Mohamed Zaki Abdallah, ended up crushed under three other men
in one of the derailed carriages. He was badly bruised, scratched and bloodied.
Sobhi Abdelbaqi, a heavy plant operator who saw the crash and took part in the
rescue operations, said he had tried to pull two dead people out from under the
Beni Suef train.
``There was a man hugging his daughter - a girl about nine years old. We got
the girl, except for one of her legs, but the man is still there,'' he said.
``There are still lots of people under the cloth shops that were destroyed. We
pulled out two dead women from there. And there was this one man stuck up on
the carriage there and we cut his legs off and pulled him down.
``The crash squeezed bodies into the wood of the shops so we had to cut them
away,'' he added.
Hassan Nigm, the local police chief, told Reuters the latest death toll was 75
dead and 76 injured. The figure could rise when rescue workers lift the
derailed carriages.
Abdelfattah Abu Zeid, a municipal worker, said he had counted 50 corpses going
to Badrasheen central hospital. His colleague, Fathi Wahdan, counted 65 going
to Hawamdia hospital.
But the Interior Ministry in Cairo said its latest casualty toll was 60 killed
and 150 injured.
Police said the first train, the one travelling to Assiut city, had about 220
people aboard. The trains should have been about five minutes apart but the
Assiut train had slowed down because of the fog, police Colonel Mohamed Ibrahim
said.
Residents said the stretch of track around Badrasheen was notoriously
dangerous, with 43 people killed in a head-on collision near the local station
in 1992 and 18 killed in 1993 at a collision two stations away.
The disaster reinforces the poor safety record of the Egyptian railway and
level crossing systems.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
