<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Long lunch followed by no breakfast</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766091</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RADIO One DJ Chris Evans appeared to forget all about his early morning show
yesterday. He failed to turn up the day after his Christmas party.
In fact, apart from one woman, all his breakfast show team failed to arrive at
Radio One. A stand-in DJ was called in at the last minute after frantic
attempts to reach the station's highest-paid performer failed.
Radio One said their star DJ was ``unwell due to a throat infection''.
However, the station said later that Evans, who has a #1m contract, was facing
a showdown with station controller Matthew Bannister for missing his show.
Spokeswoman Polly Ravenscroft said: `I am sure he will be reprimanded. He has
been burning the candle at both ends for some time now. He has been getting up
at 4.30am and going to bed late. He obviously went out and had a good time at
his Christmas party.''
A spokeswoman for Evans said: ``Chris took everybody from the programme out for
Christmas lunch and it developed into a bit of a session. He'll get a ticking
off when he's located but he's not answering his phone.
``How many people go to office parties at this time of year and don't make it
to work the next day? Chris will be back tomorrow and will probably explain
everything on the programme.''
The only member of his team to arrive, a woman called Holly, turned up at the
studio at 8.45am, 15 minutes before the programme was due to end. She told
listeners: ``I really can't remember too much at all about last night.''
Another one of his team revealed that, after the breakfast show on Wednesday,
the DJ went shopping and bought Christmas presents for all his production
staff. He added: ``When he came back mid-morning the drinking started pretty
much immediately. Then everyone went for lunch at a restaurant at the Hilton
Hotel on Park Lane. After lunch, which was a pretty raucous affair, Chris went
awol.
"He has not been seen since. He phoned in to Radio One this morning and said he
had a throat infection. However, it has not gone down well with BBC bosses,
some of whom managed to get in with sore heads from their own Christmas
parties.''
A Radio One spokeswoman said: ``Chris will be getting a ticking off when he
comes back.''
Since joining the station, Evans has annoyed BBC chiefs by flying the flag of
his company, Ginger, from radio masts at Broadcasting House, and he was
reprimanded for ``smut'' after listeners' complaints. BBC governors also
censured him for urging listeners to boycott Shell petrol stations during the
Brent Spar controversy, and the Broadcasting Standards Authority accused him of
overstepping the boundaries of acceptable taste.
However, the carrot-haired DJ has boosted Radio One's audience by more than
600,000 since he was brought in to reverse a slump in listening frigures.
</TEXT>
