<TEXT>
Doomsday cult
members missing
GENEVA: Eighteen remaining members of a doomsday sect at the centre of a mass
suicide-murder last year have gone missing, police said yesterday. Police in
Switzerland, France and Canada are involved in the hunt for the members of the
Order of the Solar Temple, so far without success, said Geneva police spokesman
Alexandre Baeriswyl.
Fifty-three members of the sect were found dead in Switzerland and Canada in
October 1994. Leading members committed suicide while the others were murdered,
investigations found. The reasons for the tragedy were never uncovered.
Nazi claim
VIENNA: Austrian public prosecutors said yesterday they were investigating the
possibility of criminal charges against far-right Freedom Party leader Joerg
Haider after an amateur video showed him making a speech praising the Nazi SS.
The video of Haider addressing and mingling with a group of former SS officers
in September has sent shockwaves through Austrian politics and society since it
was screened on television on Tuesday.
Smoking ban
BEIJING: A public smoking ban was ordered yesterday in Beijing, capital of the
world's largest producer and consumer of tobacco. The standing committee of the
People's Congress passed the no-smoking law, which will go into effect next
May. Violators will be fined 10 yuan (80p). China has over 350 million smokers
among its 1.2 billion population. In Beijing, more than 50% of the population
smokes.
Santa protest
STOCKHOLM: A man chosen to portray Father Christmas on a Swedish televsion show
has been exposed as a convicted child molester, sparking a storm of protest. A
pay channel TV Christmas gala will feature Hans Scheike, sentenced to six
years' imprisonment in 1988 for grievous bodily harm and sexual assault
involving children. Scheike led a notorious sex sect in which young teenagers
were held as sex slaves.
Election joy
PORT LOUIS: Mauritians celebrated yesterday when Prime Minister Sir Anerood
Jugnauth, 65, lost his parliamentary seat in an opposition rout of the ruling
coalition. The results were sweet revenge for Navin Ramgoolam after his father,
Sir Seewoosagur Ramgoolam, was beaten in 1982 following 14 years of rule.
</TEXT>
