<HEADLINE>Formality before friendship is Glasgow's priority in the world-wide search for city link Freebie fear in Spanish twin bid</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766096</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALL Glaswegians may have a sombrero or a straw donkey tucked away in the
wardrobe from that holiday on the Costas but it seems such connections are not
enough for the city to twin with the Spanish resort of Benidorm.
The twinning was proposed last month by the Mayor of Benidorm, Mr Vicente
Perez-Devesa, at a private meeting with Glasgow Lord Provost Tommy Dingwall.
Mr Perez-Devesa was in the city on the first leg of a glad-handing visit round
the UK to bang the drum for what is already Spain's number one holiday
destination.
However, Glasgow will not be joining in the chorus of Viva Espana. Council
leader Pat Lally has written to the Spaniards to tell them the idea is a
non-starter.
Mr Lally fully agrees in a letter to the Spaniards ``that Benidorm is a city in
which many Glaswegians enjoy wonderful holidays. I am sure that the obvious
friendship that exists between the people of Glasgow and Benidorm, and which
was clearly cemented by the Lord Provost and the mayor, can be maintained
without any formal links.''
However, he adds: ``It is council policy to limit the number of our twinning
relationships and to focus on developing links with cities which offer the
opportunity to develop substantial trading and economic links as well as
friendship and cultural links.
``Glasgow is twinned with Nuremberg in Germany, Dalian in China, and
Rostov-on-Don in Russia, while our agreed priority is to explore the
possibility of establishing links with a city in North America and Japan.''
Mr Lally goes on to say that with local government reorganisation in the wings
it would be inappropriate for the council to commit its successor to a new
twinning relationship.
Unofficially, The Herald also understands that twinning with Benidorm would put
councillors at a disadvantage because any time they jetted off to the town they
would leave themselves open to the allegation that they had gone off on a
``freebie''.
When it was first mooted that he should meet the Lord Provost, Mr Perez-Devesa
was told that a full diary precluded such an encounter. However, a meeting
subsequently scheduled at the City Chambers for 15 minutes ran over to 90 and
saw the Lord Provost tie a tartan tie round the mayor's neck.
The Lord Provost said yesterday: ``The idea of twinning was never a goer. It
never got off the ground. I was being polite with the mayor as I would be with
anyone who came to my home.''
Despite the setback - which will leave Benidorm with three twins, Bad Ems in
Germany, Vina del Mar in Chile, and Le Cannet in France - the town is confident
it will maintain its market share and attract about 100,000 visitors from
Scotland despite the fact that the industry is predicting that next year will
be difficult.
Last night, Mr Perez-Devesa said: ``Although obviously disappointed that
Glasgow is not able to take the twinning idea further I'm delighted to continue
to welcome Glaswegians to Benidorm.''
To maintain its number one position, the resort has spent more than #20m
improving facilities and upgrading hotels rather than allowing new ones to be
built. With the completion of the 52-storey Hotel Bali in 1997 (which will
become Spain's tallest building) no new hotels are being built.
</TEXT>
