<HEADLINE>Scots lines frozen out</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAIN WILSON Chief Reporter and CHRIS STARRS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766097</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RAILTRACK'S investment plans for the next 10 years exclude the long-awaited
electrification of three major lines in Scotland, including the busiest
commuter route, Glasgow-Edinburgh.
The ``upgrading freeze'' was condemned last night by Labour's transport
spokesman Brian Wilson as an appalling step backwards.
He added that Railtrack's failure to mention nine major electrification schemes
throughout the UK in investment plans over a decade will be greeted with fury
and dismay in the areas ``which have been written off''.
Mr Wilson said of Labour's analysis of Railtrack's #1000m-a-year investment
programme, published earlier this week: ``It represents no more than a wish
list, dependent on taxpayers' money - and they do not even wish to include the
extension of electrification over a full decade.''
However, Railtrack insisted the #10bn programme was not prescriptive. A
spokesman argued it covered schemes to be completed within the decade. ``In no
sense does it exclude any other developments. It does not mean other projects
have been thrown out. It is possible the Scottish electrification schemes could
start within the next 10 years.''
Mr Wilson said later: ``Oh, come on. They are not included in the programme
because they are not to be.''
Excluded from the programme are Glasgow-Edinburgh;
Edinburgh-Glasgow-Stirling-Dunblane-Perth, and Edinburgh-Dundee-Aberdeen.
All have been the subject of strong, sustained campaigns for upgrading, with
the latter the only non-electrified section of the East Coast main line to
London.
Save Our Railway campaigners believe money spent on the privatisation process
should go to upgradings and electrifications. However, some experts believe
electrification of the Edinburgh-Glasgow line, estimated at #89m, would not be
cost effective, with travel time benefits negligible.
Aberdeen-Glasgow electrification could cost #400m.
q Rail services will run down on Christmas Eve, with no trains on Christmas Day
and limited services on Boxing Day, ScotRail said last night.
</TEXT>
