<HEADLINE>All gigs great and small</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>David Belcher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>boss grooves</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766098</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Big Country have a lot to live up to at Edinburgh's Hogmanay bash. But, as
Stuart Adamson tells David Belcher, the size of the date isn't everything
I'm not keen on being seen as a rock'n'roll soap-box evangelist
STUART Adamson's 1995 has been a year of contrasts. During its course there
have been some very big Big Country gigs, and some rather more intimate ones,
too. Being a down-to-earth Dunfermline laddie, of course, Stuart keeps it all
in perspective.
Having earlier this year, for instance, supported such rock behemoths as the
Rolling Stones and Jimmy Page and Robert Plant, Stuart and his cohorts will not
be rattled next weekend by playing al fresco before 100,000-plus revellers at
the grand civic bash which is Edinburgh's Hogmanay on an all-tartan bill beside
Edwyn Collins, Aly Bain, and the Scottish Fiddle Orchestra.
Big gigs, small gigs: Big Country do their bit. On the same day that Big
Country skirled on Hampden's turf alongside 130 pipers as part of the pre-match
warm-up for the Dundee-Aberdeen Coca Cola Cup final, they helped Glasgow's Lord
Provost switch on the city's Christmas lights in George Square.
Shortly afterwards, the band were interfacing with politicians in less amicable
style: handing over an anti-nuclear-testing petition on the steps of the French
consulate in Edinburgh, their current single, Nosn (Stop The Tests), having
been designed to act as a consciousness-raiser for Greenpeace's Pacific protest
campaign.
And just one week after that, Stuart and his long-time Big Country guitar-foil,
Bruce Watson, were playing as a douce acoustic duo, the Neverly Brothers, in
the venerable environs of Dunfermline abbey's abbot's house in a fund-raiser
for the local council's heritage scheme.
Naturally, when we meet, Stuart is fulfilling yet another role: laughing-eyed
mine host of Tappie Toories, his recently-acquired, tastefully-renovated,
eighteenth-century pub in Dunfermline's city centre. No, that's wrong.
Actually, what Stuart is doing when we meet is expertly wiring up the payphone
on Tappie Toories' bar and joking couthily amid a platoon of dust-covered
workies. ``My overalls are upstairs, stained and grubby,'' Stuart says with
lantern-jawed pride, his eyes crinkling into their trademark smiley crinkle.
His chest swelling, Stuart points to a gleaming stained-glass sign on display
in the pub's window. Stemming from the pub's previous 100-year lifespan as the
Star Tavern, the sign was rescued by Stuart and his wife, Sandra, from stoorie
oblivion. But what are tappie toories?
Tappie toories: old Scots for high spires, fittingly enough for a pub located
on Dunfermline's heritage trail midway between its city chambers and the abbey.
Like Stuart Adamson, if it's not too fanciful to say it: aiming star-wards, but
rooted in Fife.
``I hate to come out with the old `keeping-my-feet-on-the-ground' phrase, but
that's it really. I love being a songwriter, but in order to write about
people, you need to be among them. I enjoy being among the people I grew up
with.
``In the same way, I'm not keen on being seen as a rock'n'roll
soapbox-evangelist. It's more to do with having been on tour in Europe through
the summer and having seen everyone protesting about the French nuclear tests.
``But back in Britain, nothing - maybe because John Major's got his hand in
French pockets. So the single was intended to alleviate my frustrations and
give Greenpeace some support.''
Pop and politics: one can easily scupper the other. Speaking of which, I'll
never forget accompanying Big Country to Moscow in 1988 on a hugely-expensive
48-hour publicity stunt intended to promote the band's then-current Peace In
Our Time album by linking it to the emergent Soviet-dismantling process of
glasnost.
A plane-load of hacks, radio DJs, media-drunks, PR toadies, magazine weasels,
and rockbiz dimwits flew over for a less-than-triumphant gig, disrupted by
mysterious power-failures, in a municipal sports hall. Final result? Big
Country appearing the victims of their own rock-star hubris, entangled in
events beyond their control - and minus some of the expensive stage-gear that
they'd brought into the Soviet Union.
``I went in with my eyes open, and it was the best and worst experience of my
life,'' says Stuart. ``You hear about these legendary music industry disasters
from the seventies, and it was great to be on the end of one of a real one.''
Best bits?
``Doing the Soviet Union's first non-Government-run gig for which people simply
turned up at kiosks and bought tickets, and where the first 10 rows weren't
Government friends and relations.''
Worst bits?
``In the West, we'd been told for years how grim life in the Soviet Union was,
and as with all propaganda, there's an element of truth. I saw the queues for
food. You felt people's suspicion . . . suspicion of us, of each other . . .
everyone was so guarded.
``I think I learnt that if you take peoples' ambition away, you take people's
fire away. And that extremes of anything never work.''
Paradoxically, in the seven years since the extremes of that Iron Curtain trip,
Big Country's career seems not to have reached the commercial heights it did
previously. How true were tabloid horror stories about the Moscow lig-of-ligs
having incurred large-scale financial losses?
``There are newspaper stories and there are newspaper stories,'' Stuart says.
``It wasn't commercially great, but what mattered was that the whole thing was
a blast! It's not about taking the money and scuttling off to stuff it under
your pillow.''
It is true, though, that Big Country have been laying low for the past couple
of years, not least because Stuart and his family spent 18 months in their
Florida des res. From there, in a detached way, Stuart could observe the
vagaries of British pop fashion.
``In the US you hear lots of guitar music on the radio, the new punky stuff.
Not so much Green Day - too cartoonish - but Offspring, Cracker, the Flaming
Lips.
``But our singles don't get daytime radio air-play in Britain. It's especially
annoying when your record reaches the UK top 40 and you're told that you're not
getting play-listed on Radio 1 because no-one wants to hear it.
``Then again, unlike a lot of current British chart pop, Big Country's music
has an expressive, ethnic, Scottish and Irish folk base with a different tonal
nature and a different set of values... after all, Scottish folk is the roots
of country and western. There aren't the same obvious connections with English
bands.
``I mean, you can trace the current Britpop thing back in an obvious chain from
Blur to the Sex Pistols, to the Kinks; from the sixties to the fifties, to
Tommy Steele, to the forties, to music hall.''
Not that you'll find Stuart Adamson going mindlessly nationalistic and uttering
disapproving cries of Jings and Crivvens in the face of Blur's gorblimey
trahzers. He has too well-developed a sense of humour for that.
</TEXT>
