<HEADLINE>Hepatitis B doctor recovers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766099</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DOCTOR who was infected with hepatitis B is said to have recovered and
returned to work in the Ayrshire and Arran area.
Ayrshire and Arran Health Board stressed that there was no risk of patients
being infected by the GP.
However, a Labour MP is to ask the health board what is being done to tackle
similar incidents in the future. Two years ago, a Staffordshire doctor was
diagnosed as having hepatitis B after working in Ayrshire and Arran and the MP
also wants confirmation that the cases are not linked.
Public health consultant Dr Cameron Stark said blood tests on the un-named
doctor in the latest case showed that he or she was clear of infection.
Dr Stark said: ``We would like to stress that there was absolutely no risk to
patients because the GP was not involved in invasive work.''
Dr Stark added that any infected patients would have come to light by now and
there were no plans to name the doctor or issue a warning to patients.
Meanwhile, Cunninghame South MP Brian Donohoe said yesterday: ``I will be
contacting the health board for assurances that the health of local patients
has not been put at risk.''
</TEXT>
