<HEADLINE>Warning to the terrorists over killings as Dublin delays release of IRA prisoners Ulster peace impetus renewed</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From JOHN COONEY in Dublin</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766100</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister and his Irish counterpart, Mr John Bruton, gave renewed
impetus to the peace process at a summit meeting in Dublin last night, but
there was a warning later for the men of violence.
The Irish Government dropped a plan for the pre-Christmas early release of IRA
prisoners, a move understood to be related to this week's Belfast murders of
two men in shootings linked to the IRA by some Northern Ireland security
sources.
Up to 10 men had been expected to be set free permanently as part of Dublin's
continuing response to the Northern Ireland peace process. One of the group was
thought to be Thomas McMahon, who has served 16 years for the 1979 IRA murder
of Lord Mountbatten and three other people in a fishing boat explosion.
At a joint news conference after the summit, Mr Major insisted he was not at
odds with the Irish government on the desirability of an elected assembly for
Northern Ireland.
Mr Major also insisted that the Irish government was committed to finding a
formula for the decommissioning of terrorist weapons as a prelude to the
holding of all-party talks.
In a similarly positive vein, Mr Bruton said that they were both very pleased
with the speed and the application of the international body in proceeding with
its task on the arms issue.
Mr Bruton said the two leaders believed that everyone engaged in the political
side of the ``twin-track process'' was showing a commitment to making it work.
Both leaders were determined to prolong ``the feel-good factor'' engendered by
US President Bill Clinton's visit, and to play down reports of differences
between London and Dublin on the details of the arms issue and the Ulster
Unionist proposal for an assembly in Belfast.
Placing strong emphasis on the importance of the assembly as a catalyst for the
political talks, Mr Major said that Irish government criticisms related to
details about its functions - and ``not as a forum from which negotiators might
emerge''.
The Prime Minister said that the assembly proposal had to be examined by all
parties.
``People who do not examine it would perhaps be closing off an option for
proceeding that an increasing number of people find to be attractive.''
Mr Major said he recognised that the whole assembly could not negotiate a
political settlement. But after the election of such an assembly representing
all strands of political opinion in Northern Ireland, ``other options may be
delivered''.
Mr Major said he very much hoped that this would be the case.
Asked if these options might include an electoral college from within the
assembly or a mandated smaller negotiating group, he said this would spring
from the will of the assembly.
Equally emphatic on the decommissioning of paramilitary weapons, Mr Major said
that the key point for both governments was that without decommissioning it
would be difficult to see how the objective of getting all the parties around
the negotiating table could succeed.
The two Premiers called on the murder gangs in Northern Ireland to stop their
``appalling barbarities'', in a condemnation of the Belfast killings.
Earlier, in Northern Ireland, Mr Major told the IRA and Sinn Fein to stop
trying to maintain the laughable fiction that they were two separate
organisations.
He condemned the recent killings in Belfast and said that if the speculation
about their responsibility was correct, ``is that not the clearest indication
of why it is necessary for all weapons to be decommissioned?
Mr Major, who visited Ballymena, County Antrim, Belfast, and Downpatrick,
County Down, said it was not just the Government that wanted the guns
decommissioned but the vast majority of the people of Ireland, north and south.
In a direct message he said: ``If those talking about peace for 18 months or so
are genuine in what they say, then they can prove that very clearly, by proving
that they really wish to take the gun out of politics, by doing it - I hope
they will.''
The summit was given the go-ahead 24 hours earlier after the settlement of an
unrelated dispute between the British and Irish governments.
The dispute centred on Britain's opposition to a European Union plan to aid the
takeover by an Indian buyer of the troubled, state-backed Irish Steel company
because of fears it could have consequences for the UK steel industry.
It was felt the row might sour UK-Irish relations to an extent that the summit
would be counter-productive. But the differences were overcome after telephone
contact between the two Premiers on Wednesday - and their meeting plan was
confirmed.
Mr Major will return to London today after staying overnight at the British
Ambassador's residence in the outskirts of the city.
</TEXT>
