<DOCNO>GH951222-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>News Digest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974766102</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Good response to
police appeal
WITNESSES to the road accident which killed a Glasgow woman and her unborn
child have been traced by police. Mrs Helen Howe, 32, of Bilsland Drive,
Ruchill, was a passenger in a car which crashed head-on into another vehicle on
Blackhill Road, Summerston, Glasgow, on Tuesday.
Mrs Howe died from multiple injuries, the almost full-term baby was still-born.
Police said last night that two women who passed the accident scene in a Ford
Fiesta had contacted them following a media appeal. Two teenagers from the
other crash car have been traced but a third occupant has not been found.
No-one has been charged.
Open all hours
A LOCH Lomond tourist centre on the A82 - gateway to the Highlands - which
served 69,000 visitors in its first year, will open year round, it was
announced yesterday.
Hospital review
LOTHIAN Health has asked West Lothian NHS Trust to carry out a feasibility
study on the future care of elderly people at Tippethill Hospital in Whitburn.
Proposals include refurbishment of the hospital or the building of a
purpose-built unit.
Impostors chased
TWO bogus workmen were chased from a doorstep by an 86-year-old woman waving a
walking stick, police revealed yesterday. The two posing as water board
officials tried to gain entry to her house in Killin Street, Glasgow, on
Wednesday. One of the men is about 20years old, 5ft 7in, and was wearing dark
blue overalls. The other man is between 25 and 32, of broad build, and was
wearing dark clothing.
Guppy loses
OLD Etonian Darius Guppy, the disgraced friend of Earl Spencer, lost his bid to
overturn a three-year sentence imposed for non-payment of a #227,000
compensation order at the High Court yesterday. He was given a five-year prison
sentence for falsely claiming insurance on jewellery ``stolen'' in New York.
Youth custody
A TEENAGER who helped stab the husband of Director of Public Prosecutions
Barbara Mills during an attempted robbery, was given six years' youth custody
at Inner London Crown Court yesterday. Bernard Enerio, 17, was convicted
earlier this month of unlawfully wounding and robbing Mr Mills, while acting
with others unknown, for supplying a Ninja knife used in the attack.
Gas fire death
A 75-YEAR-OLD woman has died in a fire at her Ayrshire home. Mrs Alice Lawson
was found at her Ochiltree house by brother George Robertson yesterday. It is
thought she may have fallen against a gas fire. A report will be sent to the
procurator-fiscal.
Gunmen jailed
THREE men were each jailed for seven years at the High Court in Glasgow
yesterday for separate offences involving guns. William Freeman, 34, of Duke
Street, Dennistoun, Glasgow, admitted threatening a kebab shop owner with a
plastic gun. William Wilson, 36, of no fixed address, admitted tying up staff
of a music shop in the city's St Vincent Street and robbing them at gunpoint of
#750. Robert McDade, 31, of Millerfield Place, Dalmarnock, Glasgow, robbed a
bookmakers of #1600 at gunpoint.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000022</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000022</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>News Digest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974766103</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Navy clears
Solway bombs
MORE than 200 bombs were cleared from a Solway beaches during a month-long
operation by a naval disposal team.
The 10lb Second World War devices were uncovered by tides at Southerness beach
but are not thought to be linked to phosphorous incendiary bombs washed up on
the west coast during gasline work near Beaufort's Dyke - the sight of a
wartime arms dump. Further searches will take place in the new year.
Man in custody
A MAN is in police custody in connection with an early morning incident after
which an elderly woman was taken to Raigmore Hospital, Inverness. The incident
happened in a house in the Drakies area of the city. A report has been sent to
the procurator-fiscal.
Gloucester dig
CROMWELL Street pathologist Professor Bernard Knight, who examined 12 victims
in the West case, was helping police exhume the body of Ukrainian Iwan
Romanowskyj in Gloucester's Coney Hill cemetery yesterday. The professor was
called in after police took a 36-year-old man into custody and charged him with
murder. An inquest had returned an open verdict on Mr Romanowskyj, who died of
stab wounds in October 1985.
Missing woman
POLICE are searching for a 31-year-old woman who has been missing since
December 13. Ms Jennifer Bain was last seen at her home in Brechin, Angus, as
she left for an appointment at the bank, which she did not keep. She is
described as 5ft 6in tall, very slim, and has collar-length dark hair, green
eyes, and a pale complexion.
Sentence on hold
A TEENAGER who took a steamroller which wrecked gardens in the Argyll village
of Kilcreggan, had sentence deferred for six months yesterday at Dumbarton
Sheriff Court. Derek Brydon, 16, of Stanmore Road, Mount Florida, Glasgow,
admitted taking the vehicle with another boy on July 1. A 13-year-old
co-accused failed to appear and a warrant was issued for his arrest.
Factory closes
THE closure of Monax Glass Limited in Perth was announced yesterday. The St
Catherine's Road factory employs 55 people, 40 of whom will be made redundant
immediately.
Santa Caster
SCHOOLGIRL Yvette Caster, 14, has decided to help other children by giving up
all her Christmas presents. Yvette, from Newbury in Berkshire, has asked all
her friends and relatives to give the money intended for her presents to the
National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children, hoping to raise
#170.
Safety breach
MFI (Furniture Centres Ltd) was fined #500 at Aberdeen Sheriff Court yesterday
after the company admitted contravening Health and Safety regulations at its
Denmore Road, Bridge of Don, warehouse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NHS trust heads bid to run hospital</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766104</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GRAMPIAN Healthcare revealed yesterday that its partners in the bid to win the
contract to run hospital services in Grampian will include an English-based
company which runs private nursing homes around the UK.
There is thought to be significant interest in the contract.
The Government caused controversy earlier this year when it rejected Grampian
Health Board's proposal, reached after wide consultation, that Woodcot Hospital
in Stonehaven should be disposed of and a new hospital built on the site of
Arduthie Hospital.
The Scottish Office NHS Management Executive told the board to invite open
competition and while some welcome the move as an opportunity for Stonehaven to
gain a hospital service tailored to the needs of the community others see it as
a major step towards privatisation of the NHS.
Grampian Healthcare is determined to win the contract and is heading a
consortium which includes CHS (Community Health Services), which runs a number
of private nursing homes, Miller Construction of Scotland, and the British
Linen Bank, which will finance the project.
``The trust is satisfied that a partnership arrangement will enhance our
prospects of winning the contract because the bid will have to meet the
criteria of the Government's private finance initiative,'' said Mr Jack Stuart,
who heads the trust's project team.
``All these companies have expertise in one form or another in the health
provision and with their support I am sure we can put together a body which has
a realistic chance of winning.''
The details of the project have still to be fully developed but the proposal
will include the construction of a hospital and 30-bed nursing home complex on
the Arduthie site.
The NHS services would continue to be under the control of Grampian Healthcare
while the nursing home would be the responsibility of CHS.
Expressions of interest were due to be submitted by 5pm last night. Details are
expected to be given this afternoon and a small number of providers will be
short listed in January.
Tenders will have to be returned by April 16 and the contract is expected to be
awarded in May with the new hospital operational a year later.
Grampian Healthcare staff and trade unions were being briefed on the plan
yesterday..
Mr Ken Macmillan, Grampian officer for the health service union Unison, said:
``Right now the trust is the body being led and it will continue to be led by
these private organisations who are only there for the cash. The trust is
merely the straw available to them to suck the public pot dry.
``Banks are not renowned for foregoing their pound of flesh and construction
companies' expertise in health-care provision is more than questionable.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jack and the Beanstalk, The Eden Court Theatre, Inverness</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mark Fisher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766105</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE ailing official from Ofpants, the panto watchdog, had seconded his deputy,
a junior clerk from a local government quango who didn't know much about it but
knew what he liked, to monitor possible seasonal entertainment violations in
Inverness.
At the interval he was looking concerned. ``I know the audience is in full
voice,'' he said, pointing to his standard issue rule book, ``but it's
infringing the As-Seen-On-TV regulations.''
Indeed, the more amateurish moments in this traditional production are thanks
not to the show's well-drilled amateurs, but to the curious mix-and-match
casting that lands a Scottish Dame (Jackie Farrell) with one Australian son
(Matthew Lilley of Home and Away), and one southern English son (Sacha Pitimson
from The Biz). The anomalies wouldn't matter if these actors demonstrated a
feel for the subtleties of the broad art of panto, but they seem to think it
enough to jump around a lot and flap their arms at the audience. It isn't.
To be fair, they're not helped by a script that lacks flair - it tells the
story cleanly enough but many of the gags fall flat and the characterisation
isn't strong enough to support it. Several sequences ramble so much it's as if
they've been improvised.
Director Sheridan Nicol's strength is in her choreography - which is, after
all, what she is known for - and the dance sequences look far more polished
than the story proper. The music too is strong (director, Irvin Duguid) and
unsentimental even in the romantic numbers.
The man from Ofpants draws my attention to the fulsome yell of approval from
the matinee audience, and we grumble off into the winter dusk.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pastoral Art in East Lothian, City Art Centre, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766106</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE East Lothian school of painting, centred on East Linton, flourished
throughout the nineteenth century, attracting those interested in landscape and
those inspired by the new realism - the art of the French Barbizon painters and
of the realist Bastien Lepage, who also influenced the early work of the
Glasgow Boys. For a brief time they themselves set up temporary lodgings at
nearby Cockburnspath and explored peasant painting, earning the nickname of the
Cabbage School.
Interestingly, the exhibition does not consider the Glasgow Boys' work but
concentrates instead on East Linton painters such as Robert Noble and Darling
MacKay. Noble's lush oils are an evocation of the time and full of the richness
and colour of the land; but they are also, it has to be said, rather
sentimental. Even Darling MacKay's pieces, which sometimes have the sincerity
of a Bastien Lepage, don't have his bite. There is no sense of social comment
or even historical description in these paintings - they are objective and
self-conscious, waiting to be enjoyed for their own sake.
There are touches of brilliance by acknowledged masters: a wonderful study of
dusk in East Linton by James Paterson, a startling early John Bellany, Preston
Tower, a blackness against a yellow sky, and Arthur Melville's Cabbage Garden,
setting the ground at an inspired angle and heavy with the influence of
Japanese art; but these artists were not members of the school.
The exhibition organisers should be congratulated on publicising this
long-neglected school, but the show lacks cohesiveness; the accompanying text,
which outlines changes in farming methods and life, doesn't balance with the
romantic, almost idyllic, paintings. In the end we get only a glimpse which
doesn't do the Scottish Barbizon painters justice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Patient becomes top nurse</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766107</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A YEAR after being treated successfully for breast cancer at Glasgow's Western
Infirmary, Miss Eleanor Martin is going back as director of nursing.
Her remarkable career move follows a 33-year association with the city's Royal
Hospital for Sick Children, where today is her last day as director of nursing
and patient services for Yorkhill NHS Trust.
The equivalent post in the West Glasgow Hospitals Trust covers the Beatson
Oncology Centre where Miss Martin, 55, was a patient last year.
``I am absolutely fine now. I was very lucky - I was caught very early on as a
result of screening,'' she said yesterday.
``The fact I had come through this alive made me think that maybe it was time
for a new direction.''
After her first stint at Yorkhill, starting from nursing school in 1962, Miss
Martin went to the Stoke Mandeville Hospital. Since returning to Yorkhill, she
has worked in neonatal surgery and obtained a Master of Business Administration
degree at Strathclyde University.
``It will be hard to walk out of here tomorrow,'' she said. ``I will really
miss the children but I am looking forward to the fresh challenge.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Attack on Scrooge firms</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766108</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday attacked employers who fail to give more than two million of
the workforce paid time off at Christmas.
Employment spokesman Ian McCartney said: ``It is a disgrace that many families
will be unable to spend Christmas together simply because their breadwinner is
not entitled to paid time off.''
He added: ``Tory Scrooge employment policies have created a country where two
million people cannot even get a paid day off for Christmas. These figures
should make Ministers choke on their turkey with shame.''
Labour findings, based on Government figures, show that 10.6% of all employees
have no entitlement, including 3.8% of all full-timers. The proportion of male
part-timers with no paid holiday is, at 54.6%, almost double that of women,
28.1%.
Mr McCartney said such people were forced to work not just anti-social hours
but on holidays as well, simply to make ends meet. The best Christmas present
for many of them would be the introduction of minimum standards of protection
at work.
Shadow Employment Secretary Michael Meacher had more gloomy news for unemployed
people. He said more than half (52%) of the vacancies registered with job
centres are now for part-time or temporary work.
He said that even when an unemployed person found a job, the odds were against
it being a regular full-time one. ``Without a major programme to end job
insecurity, Britain will be stuck in economic gloom throughout the new year,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Heaviest snow in Shetland for 15 years</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766109</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE heaviest snow falls in the Shetland Islands for 15 years led police there
to appeal to all motorists not to drive unless their journeys were essential.
Snowploughs guided ambulances through the worst of the drifts and tonnes of
snow cleared from the centre of Lerwick had to be dumped in the town's harbour,
creating a mini iceberg.
Elsewhere, the first snow of the winter in the South-west caused traffic
problems on the main A75 Euro-route between Stranraer and Gretna for much of
yesterday and there was a spate of accidents along the road with several people
slightly injured.
Several inches of snow fell on higher areas of the region and conditions on
most roads were reported as extremely dangerous for several hours.
Strathclyde Police said only good fortune prevented a multi-vehicle accident on
the M8 in the Glasgow area yesterday afternoon when many drivers apparently
ignored the adverse weather conditions.
In the Highlands, all 300 snowploughs and gritters took to the roads last night
and kept most routes open. The Benefits Agency announced cold weather payments
were being sent out to several hundred people living in the Aviemore, Braemar,
and Tulloch Bridge area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Toll-free Christmas for Skye</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766110</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE operators of the controversial Skye bridge yesterday unwrapped the present
they will give the people of the island on Christmas Day, 24 hours toll-free .
. . which seems to have left many decidedly underwhelmed.
Mr Russell Thomson, the bridge manager, said yesterday: ``This is the first
time that it has been possible to make the crossing as the ferry did not
operate on Christmas Day. We are delighted therefore to be able to offer our
customers a toll-free day with our best wishes for the season.''
Skye Bridge Ltd director Bob Wilson, meanwhile, said: ``In view of the
encouraging use of the bridge, we have managed to secure a concession from our
financiers to allow the bridge operators Miller/Dywidag to make the bridge
toll-free from midnight on Christmas Eve to midnight on Christmas Day.''
Some, however, seemed to sense humbug. Mrs Kathleen MacRae, treasurer of the
Skye Bridge Appeal Group said: ``It is not even being mentioned, so I think it
is fair to say the people here are not particularly impressed by this
announcement today.
``What is of greater interest is that they admit they have had to go to their
financiers, the Bank of America, to ask permission to make this gesture. It is
the Bank of America which calls ths shots even down to holiday arrangements.''
Tolls for the Tay, Erskine, and Forth road bridges will remain in force over
Christmas and New Year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000030</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000030</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Police call for caution after heavy snow falls</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766111</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOTORISTS who ignored hazardous road conditions and warnings to drive carefully
after heavy snow showers in some parts of Scotland were accused of
``disgraceful'' driving by the police yesterday.
Strathclyde Police said only good fortune prevented a multi-vehicle accident on
the M8 in the Glasgow area yesterday afternoon.
Some motorists were reported to have been driving ``erratically'' by weaving in
and out of the traffic, while others failed to keep a safe distance between
their vehicles and those ahead.
Superintendent Fred McManus, of Strathclyde Police's traffic department, said
last night: ``Regrettably, it is all too common an experience that, when
adverse weather conditions prevail, drivers do not adapt their driving
accordingly.''
Strathclyde Police said that, although road conditions were very poor in the
Newton Mearns area in the south of Glasgow, Kilmarnock, and the A77 at
Eaglesham Moor, there were no serious road accidents.
Snow and ice also played havoc with air services in the east of Scotland last
night. Aberdeen was not badly affected but Edinburgh airport had to shut for
more than an hour, having previously taken diverted flights from Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SNP pushes for fuel bonus</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766112</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SNP leaders yesterday challenged Labour councillors to follow their lead in
giving special help to pensioners to combat the problem of keeping warm during
the winter months.
They claimed the fuel poverty amid energy plenty which existed in Scotland -
affecting 800,000 households - was ``a scandal of immense proportions''.
At a press conference in Edinburgh, the SNP vice-convener for local government,
Councillor Maureen Watt, said her party had a record second to none in
providing practical assistance over heating costs.
Councils controlled by the nationalists had developed a range of packages worth
#1.4m to help people, particularly the elderly, get through the cold winter
months safely and in comfort.
As an example, she displayed some of the hundreds of letters the party says it
has received from 19,000 pensioners in West Lothian who are each getting a #30
bonus from the district council.
West Lothian Councillor John Richardson said: ``The SNP have been inundated
with letters of support from pensioners who are grateful for the help which the
council has been able to provide. The #30 payment which we make represents
three week's fuel costs for pensioners, which means that West Lothian's elderly
are better able to fend off winter's chill.''
It is believed that regional councils are not legally allowed to give such
one-off payments and the position of the new unitary councils on the issue is
still uncertain.
However, Councillor Watt said the three new SNP-run councils of Angus, Perth
and Kinross, and Moray were determined to continue to give special help in some
form to the elderly during the winter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Blair raps `spank' card</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766113</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR leader Tony Blair last night ordered the scrapping of a Labour Party
Christmas card which contained an illustration of a condom and a topless woman
saying ``Spank me''.
The Labour leader said the card showed a lapse in good taste.
He has told party officials, and Labour's ad agency which designed it, that
nothing similar should happen again.
The card was intended to poke fun at various Conservative scandals, and
contained a spoof version of the Twelve Days of Christmas.
To illustrate the scandals, the card, unveiled at a Labour function at
Westminster, showed a bra, underwear, a whip, and hotel bills as well as the
condom and the naked woman.
Ms Tessa Jowell, Labour's women's spokesperson, said: ``It was a parody on the
12 days of Christmas.''
The card was designed by Labour's advertising agency, BMP.
A spokesman for Mr Blair's office said: ``This was meant to be a light-hearted
Christmas joke.
``The script of the card was agreed and cleared but the illustrations on the
card were not.
``Mr Blair has been shown the material and believed it showed a lapse in good
taste. He does not want this card to be used in any way by the party, and the
agency and party officials have been instructed that nothing similar should
happen again.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Polish premier denies he was spy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From ANTHONY YARKER Warsaw, Thursday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766114</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLISH Prime Minister Jozef Oleksy today denied in parliament accusations by
the interior minister that he had been a long-term informer for foreign
intelligence services.
``I was never anyone's agent,'' Oleksy, formerly a senior figure in Poland's
pre-1989 communist system, told a special session to hear details of reports by
President Lech Walesa of a threat to state security.
He admitted he had known Russian and Soviet diplomats but said he had severed
ties with one when he learned he was a KGB agent. Asked by journalists later
whether he thought he should resign, Oleksy replied: ``I don't.''
The prime minister was responding to a statement by Interior Minister Andrzej
Milczanowski which accused him of acting as an intelligence informer until
recently.
``In 1995 intelligence was obtained indicating Mr Jozef Oleksy as an informer
of foreign intelligence,'' Milczanowski told parliament.
He did not name the foreign country but from Oleksy's denial it was clear the
issue concerned Moscow.
``Information emerges that in 1990-95 Mr Jozef Oleksy had many meetings with
officers of foreign intelligence during which he knowingly conveyed
information, some of which was classified,'' Milczanowski said.
He said Polish security knew that even in the 1980s foreign agents had a spy
among Poland's then-ruling communist party, but his identity had only emerged
this year, after Oleksy became prime minister in March.
Milczanowski rejected Oleksy's claim that he had severed links with people he
had been warned were foreign spies.
Oleksy said he had numbered Russian and Soviet diplomats among his close
contacts.
``The moment that the head of (Polish security) informed me that one of these
acquaintances was a KGB officer.......I stopped all contacts with him,'' Oleksy
said.
Russia's intelligence service yesterday denied that Oleksy has co-operated with
it and denounced the charges as a political provocation launched before Walesa
yields the presidency to ex-communist Aleksander Kwasniewski on Saturday.
Walesa, defeated by Oleksy's close colleague Kwasniewski in presidential
elections last month, claims there is a threat to state security.
The prosecutors office is due to decide tomorrow whether to proceed with a
formal inquiry into Oleksy.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Taylor-made delivery is seventh heaven</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766115</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WOMAN has beaten the odds to become a mother for the first time, after seven
Christmases of despair.
Six of Angela Dickson's babies died before birth, two of them from cardiac
failure in the womb and the others early in pregnancy.
Now she and husband, George, are in seventh heaven after getting their best
Christmas present yet.
Mrs Dickson, 29, cuddled daughter Taylor and said: ``She's just perfect. I
could not ask for more. It is what we have dreamed of after almost eight years
of pregnancies.''
Ten weeks after Taylor arrived at the couple's home in Glasgow, Mrs Dickson
still wakes in the morning and finds it hard to believe that she is a mother.
It is all George, 27, can do to tear himself away from her cot to go to his job
as a mechanic. Even being wakened through the night is no chore.
Mrs Dickson said: ``When people, who did not know us well, asked if we were
going to start a family, I would just smile and tell them `some day'.
``Inside, my heart was breaking because I thought that we just were not
destined to become parents. Getting pregnant was not a problem. Keeping the
babies till they were ready to come into the world seemed impossible.''
Doctors could offer no medical explanation as to why her babies died before
birth.
``They carried out a myriad tests but there was no obvious answer,'' said Mrs
Dickson.
The obstetric team at Glasgow Royal Maternity explored every avenue of
treatment and by the last pregnancy Mrs Dickson was on a combined course of
folic acid to reduce the chance of foetal handicap, hormone treatment to lessen
miscarriage, and aspirin to make sure that the blood supply to the baby through
the placenta was not interrupted by blood clots.
She was also monitored by weekly scans. Both Mr and Mrs Dickson were on a
course of multi-vitamin tablets.
Baby Taylor was looked after in pregnancy and delivered by Dr Alan Mathers,
foetal medicine specialist at Glasgow Royal Maternity.
Dr Mathers described the unsuccessful pregnancies as ones which beat medical
science.
``We carried out every available investigation but they failed to provide an
answer to the cause.
``However, we were delighted to help Mrs Dickson achieve a healthy baby against
tremendous odds.
``These are the patients which make you realise the immense joy attached to
obstetrics.''
Mrs Dickson said: ``What Dr Mathers did was give us a healthy baby and we owe
him a great debt.
``He also gave me the encouragement and confidence to keep trying. Believe me,
I despaired of it ever happening.
``However, when I told him we were determined to have a baby he assured me they
would offer all maternity care and support possible.''
Mrs Dickson described how she is still adjusting to motherhood. ``I have yet to
accept that this has really happened. I keep thinking that I am looking after
someone else's baby and that it's all too good to be true.
``If I have to go into the kitchen, I keep checking the living-room to make
sure Taylor is still there. I realise those feelings will settle with time.
``George is so delighted that he's reluctant to leave her and go to work in the
morning and when he returns home he goes straight to the cot.''
Although she is just 10 weeks old, the infant is alert and frequently wide
awake. ``Taylor does not want to go to sleep at night but that is partly
because she is getting so much attention from our families,'' Mrs Dickson said.
``And to be honest I don't really care whether she keeps us up at night because
she is just such a joy to have around.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sheriff urges medical review after ulcer death</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766116</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SHERIFF has called for a review of medical procedures involving junior
doctors after a man was twice misdiagnosed and died of a perforated ulcer.
The sheriff urged that junior doctors should be given better training to rule
out further ``possible errors of judgment''.
Mr Billy Muir, 51, who had a history of stomach ulcer complaints, was detained
for observation at Royal Alexandra Hospital, Paisley, after complaining of
vomiting blood. He was discharged by doctors who said there was no cause for
concern.
Mr Muir, of Ben Lui Drive, Hawkhead, Paisley, returned to the hospital the
following day with severe stomach pains but, after being kept in for two hours,
was diagnosed by a junior doctor as having a blocked bowel, given suppositories
and sent home.
He died on February 20 - a day later - from peritonitis caused by a perforated
duodenal ulcer.
A pathologist who carried out a post-mortem examination told a fatal accident
inquiry at Paisley Sheriff Court earlier this year that Mr Muir's ulcer had
burst two to three days before he died.
The junior doctor who discharged him had worked in the casualty unit of the RAH
for just over two weeks after spending six months in the accident and emergency
unit at Stobhill Hospital, Glasgow.
Sheriff Neil Douglas, delivering his written judgment on Mr Muir's death
yesterday, urged that inexperienced young doctors should refer similar cases to
more experienced colleagues.
He said trainees had little chance of identifying vital warning signs because
advances in medical science had resulted in serious stomach complaints -
including perforated ulcers - becoming rarer.
Mr Muir's mother Mary, 75, told the inquiry she believed medical staff had been
negligent and that her son might still be alive if he had received proper
attention.
Dr Joris Van Der Horst, a senior house officer at the RAH, examined Mr Muir
when he was admitted to the ward from casualty. He said he had not been in pain
or showing any signs which would have alarmed him.
However, he conceded that he may have been more concerned, or at least
suspected the patient's condition had deteriorated, if he had made the same
observations made later by a colleague.
Consultant surgeon John Anderson of Southern General Hospital, Glasgow, said Mr
Muir might not have died if he had had been admitted to hospital after his
second visit and kept under observation.
He said a more experienced doctor might have admitted him and added: ``That is
one of the classic errors of judgment that junior doctors can make.''
A statement issued yesterday by the RAH said: ``We will be studying the report
and cannot comment until we have had the opportunity to do so.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000036</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000036</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cries of foul from Fair City</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAHAM OGILVY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766117</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PERTH City Hall, one of the fixtures and fittings of Scottish political life,
may be demolished to make way for a piazza and a three-storey shopping mall
centred around a ``Golden Tower'' tourism attraction.
Perth and Kinross District Council has a plan to obliterate the B-listed hall
where Ted Heath made his famous declaration of Perth in 1968, promising
devolution for the Scots; and where Margaret Thatcher made her post-election
pledge of a war on ``Marxism''.
The council's #25m ``Putting a New Heart in Perth'' initiative envisages a
large piazza-style open space leading up to a redeveloped Kirkgate Centre
hosting quality shops. A new conference hall would be constructed at Horse
Cross and linked to the city's existing museum and art gallery.
But the normally douce citizens of the tweedy county town are up in arms over
the plan to tear down the hall and replace it with a new civic square. Two
thousand people have signed a petition and opponents accuse council planners of
destroying the city's heritage.
Opened in 1911 and constructed at a cost of #30,000, Perth City Hall was to
``remain for centuries'', according to the then Lord Provost.
Yet, if all goes to plan, the Edwardian neo-baroque hall by noted architect
Henry Clifford will have survived less than 100 years.
With the Scottish Conservatives already having turned their backs on what was a
traditional venue for their annual gathering, council officials insist the hall
is not suitable for the needs of the modern conference market.
THE council also estimates that #1m would have to be spent on essential repairs
to its interior over the next few years, while any major refurbishment would
cost between #3m and #7m.
But the proposals for a radically altered city centre have gone too far for
some of the inhabitants of Scotland's ancient capital.
Mr Dennis Gray, who runs a city-centre kilt shop, is one of the most vociferous
opponents. ``We don't want a piazza, we want to keep our city hall.
``They will replace it with seats, flowers, and winos and all I could say to my
grandchildren will be `that's where our city hall used to be'.
``The main thing is Perth's heritage. Once it's knocked down the hall cannot be
rebuilt again.
``In my opinion the money would be better spent on flood protection measures to
help the people of Perth. If you were to walk through Perth today I think you
would struggle to find people in favour of the plan.
``The city hall should be saved - that's what the majority of people want. It
is too important a part of our heritage to destroy.''
Perth Provost Jean McCormack is backing the demolition plan. ``The city hall
was always regarded by Margaret Thatcher as one of her favourite venues but
John Major has voted it down during my term of office.
``I have had the benefit of the presentations on the new scheme and I am very
much sold on the idea. There is a lot of sentiment attached to the city hall
and it is a radical suggestion to knock the hall down. But we have to move with
the times and the hall is just not suitable for modern political conferences.
``Perth lacks a city square and knocking down the hall would give us a
good-sized square and open up a vista on the beautiful St John's Kirk.''
Proposals will go before the district council early next year and the plans
would also have to be considered by the new unitary Perthshire and Kinross
Council.
The plans have already received the blessing of at least one of the city's
blue-blooded citizens.
Lord Perth, president of Perth Civic Trust, but speaking in a personal
capacity, said: ``I think it is a most imaginative and exciting thing. To open
up the whole of the square where the city hall currently stands would create a
tremendously interesting open space.
``Although I can understand the sentiment about not taking down the existing
city hall, I think it is in every way right.
``Perth would benefit enormously from it and it takes the city into the
twenty-first century.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Revenue raiser or road safety manoeuvre? John Linklater looks at a rise in impounded cars Kind of uplift that gets you down</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN LINKLATER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766118</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT IS a miserable scene played out with increasing frequency during these
Christmas shopping weeks. Dawn Fulton arrives at the austere perspex window of
the car pound off the High Street in Glasgow to negotiate the return of her
Mini Metro. It was uplifted from Midland Street 20 minutes before. The signs
displaying credit cards accepted for the #105 charge are an added irony. If
Dawn held a credit card she would not be in this predicament.
Her costly ten-minute illegal parking manoeuvre, on a single yellow line, was
to allow her to withdraw a special #250 grant. Dawn, a final year student
taking a primary education degree to qualify next year as a teacher, had been
awarded the money by the Child Care Fund of Strathclyde University's student
association. A single parent, the grant was to allow her to give her children
Barry, 10, and Nikki, 9, a decent Christmas.
Her plan was to collect the money and return to East Kilbride to shop for toys
and food. The risk she took, parking close by the bank, halved that Christmas
cheer. An unanticipated queue at the bank was all it needed. By the time she
got back to her vehicle it had gone. The privately contracted hoisters had
responded to a police request to remove it. The operation was as speedy as it
was sickening. It left Dawn facing the #105 charge, which she paid with money
literally marked for her children, and the #20 fixed penalty parking ticket. A
double bind.
Dawn can hardly hold back the tears. Her predicament is desolate enough, but
snow begins to fall towards the ugly iron gates of the pound, and it gives an
added pathos. ``There was no notice,'' she says. ``I thought a single yellow
line just meant limited parking time. The car wasn't causing any obstruction,
causing a risk of an accident or an emergency.'' She looks bewildered, and
fights conflicting feelings of foolishness and anger. The level of the charge
has clearly shocked her. She never fully understood the risk she was taking.
``I am being penalised at the same rate as an executive in some large company
who can put this down on their expenses,'' she blurts finally, seizing on the
significance of the credit card display. ``I would like to know who is
benefitting from this? The police are a public service, but a private
contractor making a profit out of this is a disgrace.''
The name of Bells of Richmond appears on the six hoisters, vehicles with their
apparatus that look strangely like instruments of medieval torture, as they
hunt their prey through the city centre streets. The contract is due for
renewal next year. Bells have operated for the first three years of the scheme,
raking in #486,000, the successful tender accepted by Strathclyde Regional
Council over eight rival firms. Bells are experienced hands in this ugly game.
They also contract in London and Edinburgh.
Unlucky drivers are refused a company telephone number, and are given only a
London post office box address if they have complaints. This is to discourage
``cranks'' and ``angry people'', it is explained politely. Indeed, no number
for a Bells of Richmond is listed. The company actually operates as Whitrad
Ltd, Middlesex. They are unlikely to ever feature in a Beatles song, unlike
Lovely Rita the meter maid, who had some compensating presence. The
contractors, in their quasi-uniformed navy pullovers with emblems on the chest,
act defensively. They refused to be interviewed.
The company's successful tender represents some 30% of every vehicle lifted.
Since 1993 more than 16,000 vehicles have suffered the ignomony. It has raised
#1.7 million credited against the police budget within the overall Strathclyde
Regional Council budget. The cost of the service is assessed annually net of
income. The increased activity of the Contractual Removal of Vehicles, as it is
somberly termed, has provoked the AA and RAC to talk about a ``purge'' and to
raise questions of a ``revenue-raising exercise''.
``Not at all,'' denies Chief Inspector Jim Neill, of Strathclyde Police's
traffic department. ``Of course the contractors have to make a profit to
survive. But the charge is set by Government, nationally across the board. Any
private enterprise - if they don't make a profit they don't survive, and we
wouldn't have any contracters available, capable of paying their employees and
updating their vehicle fleet.
``This whole scheme is not about making money, nor is it about numbers of
vehicles. We are not interested one iota. Bells of Richmond are not either. The
whole ethos and thrust is road safety.''
NEITHER does Mr Neill accept that the scheme operates in an apparently
arbitrary fashion, singling out particular streets for intensive activity, on a
basis that appears to maximise numbers of cars to be swiftly removed rather
than over-riding traffic-flow criteria. Midland, Howard, and Shuttle Streets
are perceived as current targets, precisely because they are convenient.
``That's not true at all,'' counters Mr Neill. ``It's about regulation. It's
about people who will park illegally and by doing so avoid the cost of parking
and ignoring traffic regulation orders. A minority of the motoring public are
absolutely selfish and bloody minded. They are dogmatic and want to drive from
door to door, regardless of the inconvenience they cause. Some do it selfishly.
Some do it with a lack of thought.''
A quota system is denied. ``The quota we would like to achieve is no vehicles
removed at all,'' says Mr Neill. Even so, since 1993 the removal rate has been
steady from Glasgow city centre, with a slight increase that appears to deny
the success of the scheme and which runs counter to the expectations of
regional councillors when it was adopted. The figures are: 5123 cars (1993),
5416 (1994) and 5048 so far this year, with a final figure of 5600 anticipated.
In Edinburgh, 10,185 cars have been lifted already this year, according to
Lothian and Borders Police. The daily rate there is currently running at 25
vehicles.
Despite the deep unpopularity of the scheme among victims, Mr Neill insists
that it has been applauded by taxi associations, passenger transport
associations and bus companies who have appreciated the ease on congestion. He
claims people in bus queues have stood cheering as a vehicle is removed because
it was causing a safety hazard. He also maintains that it is a discretionary
system, willing to recognise cases where disabled drivers have been unfairly
penalised, where errors have been made, and where penalties have been applied
outwith restriction times. After ``sympathetic consideration'' full fees have
been refunded. He cannot give numbers.
It is useless to suggest anything of this to Dawn Fulton as she reflects on her
children's money she has just had to hand over. As she speaks, we are joined by
another woman who has had her battered X-registration Ford Sierra impounded.
Barbara Orton, an independent television producer, is furious. This is the
second time she has had to retrieve her vehicle in a fortnight. ``It is
completely arbitrary,'' she insists. ``That's what infuriates me. On the way
over here I have seen literally hundreds of illegally parked cars. This is what
I get for parking on a single, innocuous yellow line.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A step in the  right direction</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DONNY OROURKE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766119</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CEILIDHS have been increasing in popularity throughout the nineties. Most of us
have done a bit of birling and twirling, even if it's taken some coaxing to get
those tapping toes on to the dance floor. It's good-natured. It's Scottish.
Anyone can do it.
But next time the band strikes up at a party or a wedding, why lumber bemusedly
like a buffalo playing tig, when, with a wee bit of practice, you could get the
steps right? There are experts who can help anyone who wants to make a New
Year's resolution to add finesse to enthusiasm.
Freeland Barbour and Karin Ingram have been sharing their expertise and
enthusiasm with a growing number of regulars and newcomers at Glasgow's
Riverside Club where the ceilidh revival really got going and where people
still pack the floor on Saturday nights.
Monday evening is when dancers of all ages and proficiency gather. Freeland
plays the accordion. Karen calls out the steps. They banter, they cajole, they
encourage. This is hands (and feet) on learning. It's fun. The only difference
between the Monday ``class'' and the weekend ceilidh, is that everybody knows
(or is taught) what they're doing. It's dancing by numbers.
You advance, you retire, set, cast off, visit your corner, learn what to do
with ``man one'' and ``lady four'' and because everyone is there to dance, you
don't have to sit around looking cool and detached. Being a wallflower isn't an
option.
``This is social dance rather than country dancing,'' says Freeland Barbour.
``Country dancing is courtly dancing. It's a bit more intricate and formal.
This is basically `round the room dancing.' Anyone can get up there and do it.''
It's not every box player however who can play sympathetically for dancing and
Freeland's skill and tact in matters of rhythm and tempo add enormously to the
pleasure of the experience. A founder member of Silly Wizard, an innovative and
influential music producer at BBC Radio Scotland in the eighties and mainstay
of the Wallachmor Ceilidh Band, Barbour, a Blair Atholl man originally, is also
one of Scotland's leading composers. He even wrote the theme tune for The
Beechgrove Garden. Music takes him all over the world but the Monday sessions
are a fixture. He sees them as a means of preserving and promoting the
tradition he is steeped in.
Karin Ingram does the calling with Freeland's other band The Occasionals and is
dance artist in residence for Dumfries and Galloway. Her instructions are a
model of witty lucidity.
We tend to think of calling as a North American feature at square and barn
dances. But as Freeland points out, there have always been callers in British
dance too. ``I was impressed by what some of the English callers were doing and
people like Bob Blair of Stramash began trying out these techniques up here.
It's not at all instructive. It helps things flow. A good caller adds to the
enjoyment of the dance.''
As class clod, I was taken graciously in hand by several energetically
accomplished regulars, most of whom have been going along for years, polishing
up the familiar dances and learning new ones.
The selection of dances is beautifully paced and varied. Houlihan's Jig was
like sumo wrestling on speed. Finding the direct ``corner '' in the Lancers was
trying to cross a motorway at rush hour. This was not Karin's fault. Once again
more experienced people kept me right with good humour and good grace.
I'm a pretty diffident chap and was at ease and on my feet within minutes. Most
of those attending came along in pairs or as part of larger groups. Dances call
for couples, fours, sixes and eights, so it's possible to stick with one's
friends and meet new people at the same time. Women dance cheerfully with each
other. You do what you like. Most people come here often: so you don't need to
ask.
The class starts again on January 15. At Easter, Freeland and Karin are
organising a residential course on Skye. There, as at the Riverside Club,
beginners are welcome.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Recognition at last for a woman's true worth</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAMOLA TALWAR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766120</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WOMEN are set to become common currency in Scotland under a proposal to put
them on banknotes being considered by the Clydesdale Bank.
It would be the first time that a woman's face has been imprinted on currency
notes in Scotland. The representation of women on English notes is only
slightly better. The Queen and ``The lady of the lamp'' Florence Nightingale
gaze out from notes issued by the Bank of England.
The plan is to restrict the nominations to prominent historical figures to
avoid any unseemly controversy that could develop if past and present political
figures were suggested. ``We would definitely prefer a historical Scottish
character,'' said a Clydesdale Bank spokesman who added that no final decision
had been taken.
Suggestions already received by the bank include Elsie Inglis who set up
hospital units staffed by Scottish women in Serbia during the First World War,
after being told that the Government was not interested in the services of
women. A maternity hospital in Edinburgh named after her is no longer open.
Another suggestion is Flora Stevenson who was the first woman to sit on a
school board in Scotland. She was also involved in the women's suffrage
movement, and a school in Edinburgh was named after her.
The Herald asked contemporary Scotswomen to name who they would like to see on
a note. Ms Ray Michie, the Liberal Democrat MP, voted for Jenny Geddes who
tumbled into the history books when she threw a church stool at an English
minister.
``I think it's a great idea, but I would prefer someone other than Mary Queen
of Scots or St Margaret. We have not been able to look after our own affairs
for such a long time that not many women have come to the forefront,'' Michie
said.
Ms Annabel Goldie, vice-chairman of the Scottish Conservative Party, found it
difficult to name a famous Scotswoman in history. She said she could not even
remember the men on banknotes and could only recall Edinburgh Castle in the
background.
Goldie finally settled for Eve. ``I would like Eve on a banknote. I would like
her with a fig leaf. Eve has a lot to answer for. She would be an instructive
example. Her face on a banknote would draw me up short and make me reflect on
what I was doing. In this cynical age we are so busy spending the money that we
don't pause to think who is on the notes,'' Goldie said.
SNP MP Margaret Ewing wondered how appropriate the plan was with a single
European currency looming, but added: ``I would like the picture of an old lady
who is not named. It could be everybody's mother or grandmother.''
Despite her initial hesitation she supported the idea as it would reflect
women's contribution to society. She felt Mary Queen of Scots would draw
substantial romantic interest from tourists. Her other nomination went to one
of Robert Burns's loves, Jean Armour, as 1996 is the Burns bicentenary year.
Labour MP Helen Liddell proposed Marion Gilchrist for leading the way for women
into medicine. Gilchrist was the first woman to graduate with a medical degree
from Glasgow University in the late nineteenth century.
Ms Elspeth King, the author of The Thenew Factor on forgotten women in
Scotland's past, believed that throughout history women's contribution had been
underplayed.
She suggested St Margaret of Scotland; Isabel Elder, who founded the Elder
Library in Glasgow, for the impetus she gave to the education of women; Flora
Drummond for her involvement in the women's suffrage movement; and writer
Catherine Carswell, whose books include a biography of Robert Burns.
In countries around the world the preference seems to be for symbolic female
figures in traditional costume as on French, Russian, Greek, African, and Irish
notes.
Israel is one of the rare countries that placed its former Prime Minister,
Golda Meyer, on banknotes. The current series of Chinese currency features
women representing different ethnic groups.
The Queen no longer figures on notes of Commonwealth countries such as
Australia, New Zealand, and Canada, but still appears on the currency of the
Cayman Islands and Bermuda.
The reaction of most Scottish women was that the move in this country was long
overdue. They believe it should be the start of more concrete steps to uncover
inspiring stories of Scottish women buried in the cobwebs of the past.
Once a decision is taken on who will be the first Scotswoman to grace a
banknote, it may well become as commonplace to have Scotswomen looking out
disapprovingly from banknotes at spendthrifts as the traditional Scottish male
icons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000040</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Unhappy returns</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JENNIFER CUNNINGHAM</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766121</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JENNIFER CUNNINGHAM investigates the rights and wrongs of refunds on unwanted
gifts
ONE of the saddest sights of the season of goodwill is the queue of people
trying to exchange or refund the jumpers or shirts, presumably painstakingly
chosen by their nearest and dearest.
So what do you do if Auntie Jeannie is convinced you are two sizes smaller than
you are or vice versa ? If you are the giver rather than the receiver, the
advice of consumer officers is to patronise the patron saint of exchanges, keep
the receipt or even better, if you know it is equally likely to be a hit or a
miss, ask the shop to write on to the receipt that this article may be
exchanged if not suitable.
Only if the goods are faulty, can you count on your money back, however. Even
Marks and &amp; Spencer who used to trade on a promise of refunding unsuitable
goods, now offer gift vouchers to spend in the store if there is no receipt. It
is a fair exchange for genuine customers while putting a spanner in the
shoplifters' latest dodge of stealing from one branch and claiming the refund
in another.
Few people, however, give presents with the receipt attached. Alan Adams,
Strathclyde's principal consumer officer, suggests including the receipt in a
sealed envelope to be opened only if the present is unsuitable. He claims to
have used this device himself, but admits to a suspicion that the recipient
sneaked a look.
There is a clear obligation on the part of the seller to give back cash, if the
goods are faulty rather than unsuitable. It may be less than the full amount
depending on how old the article is and how much use has been made of it. The
amended Sale of Goods Act came into force last January as a clarification of
grey areas of consumer law, it removed the phrase ``of merchantable quality'' -
key to thousands of legal wranglings in favour fulfilling the purpose for which
it was bought. It also requires the retailer to offer a cash refund instead of
a replacement, repair or credit note.
That knowledge is likely to be of more use to bargain-hunters in the January
sales than to churlish souls in receipt of ``unwanted gifts''. They are likely
to appear in the small ads once again, because if not faulty shops are not
obliged to exchange or replace them. Most of the major High Street names do,
because they trade on their reputation, according to consumer protection
officer, Andy Moynihan, but he warns that shops which depend on selling at the
cheapest price, usually have a policy of not exchanging. A new hazard is
seasonal shops which open in empty premises in the run-up to Christmas and
disappear before the season of returns.
It is a good idea to use a credit card for purchases of individual items which
cost more than #100 according to Alan Adams, because it offers an extra degree
of protection because both the credit card company and the retailer are
responsible and the consumer has the right to take action agianst either or
both. In the case of a trader who has disappeared, for example, someone who had
paid by credit card could expect redress from the credit card company, such as
Access or Visa, but not if using a debit or switch card.
</TEXT>
