<HEADLINE>OIL INDUSTRY Abbot makes #8m bid for OIS</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766122</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OIL INDUSTRY
Abbot
makes
#8m bid
for OIS
DRILLING company Abbot Group last night launched an #8.25m takeover bid for
OIS, an Aberdeen firm which provides technical inspection services for the oil,
petrochemical and power generation industries, writes ROBERT POWELL.
Abbot offered one of its own shares for every OIS share - valuing OIS shares at
27.5p. It also offered a cash alternative of 24.5p.
The drilling company approached OIS with an offer six weeks ago. Receiving no
reply, it decided to launch a bid any way.
OIS officials were not immediately available for comment.
Abbot said there was potential for considerable synergy between the two groups.
Both have their UK operations centres in Aberdeen and are heavily engaged in
the offshore oil and gas industry.
``The board of Abbot believes that there is considerable potential to improve
the performance of OIS. This will be achieved by a combination of
cross-marketing of the enlarged group's services to a broader customer base and
opportunities to collaborate on major projects and develop business for the
combined group in new geographic areas,'' the company said in a statement.
Abbot said there were also savings to be made by eliminating the duplication of
head offices.
Abbot chairman Alasdair Locke said OIS had delivered disappointing profit and
dividend performances since it was floated on the Stock Exchange three years
ago and was unlikely to improve under its present management.
``The fundamental problems of OIS under its present management run so deep
that there can be little foreseeable chance of significant improvement in
levels of profit and dividends,'' he said.
OIS shares were floated at 50p, but had been below 25p for the last three
months. The announcement of Abbot's bid, just before the market closed, pushed
them up 7p to 25p.
Abbot shares fell 3p to 52p.
</TEXT>
