<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Surgeon cleared of abortion during hysterectomy charge</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766123</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SURGEON who performed a hysterectomy on a pregnant woman was cleared
yesterday of carrying out an illegal abortion.
Consultant obstetrician and gynaecologist Reginald Dixon, 59, was found not
guilty of procuring a miscarriage on part-time college lecturer Barbara Whiten,
38.
He said later he would return to work in the operating theatre within the next
few days.
After the verdict, childless Mrs Whiten broke down and sobbed before being led
from the court by her husband and two stepsons.
During the three-week trial at Nottingham Crown Court she had claimed the
surgeon had ``flippantly'' told her she had been pregnant, the day after
carrying out a full abdominal hysterectomy at Kings Mill Hospital,
Sutton-in-Ashfield, Nottinghamshire, on March 8, 1993.
After the verdict, Mr Dixon said: ``It is a great relief to see the end of
nearly three years of severe stress for me, my family and, of course poor Mrs
Whiten.''
Mrs Whiten had been referred to Mr Dixon after being diagnosed as having
endometriosis, a womb disease.
Despite telling nurses she had not had a period for three months, no checks
were made to see if she was pregnant before she was wheeled into theatre and
met Mr Dixon briefly before being anaesthetised.
He was charged, after a lengthy investigation by Nottinghamshire police, under
the Offences Against the Person Act 1861.
The jury of seven men and five women took two hours and 10 minutes to return
their unanimous verdict.
Mr Dixon's counsel, Ms Nicola Davies QC, said he had acted in good faith under
the emergency procedures of the 1967 Abortion Act which allows surgeons to
abort a foetus if they believe the continuation of the pregnancy could cause
grave or permanent mental injury to the patient.
The court heard Mrs Whiten, of Kirkby-in-Ashfield, had a history of depression
and had twice tried to commit suicide.
She broke down as she said in evidence: ``I would have loved to have a baby.''
Mrs Whiten, who has been treated for post-traumatic stress disorder, said Mr
Dixon told her of the pregnancy during his ward round.
She said: ``He got to the bottom of the bed, looked over his shoulder and said:
`By the way, the womb was rather swollen and I suspected there was a pregnancy
but I carried on because that was what you would have wanted.'
``I didn't believe what I was hearing. Then he just walked away. I was
absolutely shocked, horrified.''
She denied ever telling other doctors that she did not want to become pregnant
and said she agreed to the hysterectomy after being told it was the only way to
cure her painful condition.
Mr Dixon said he was faced with a ``quandary'' when he realised his patient
might be pregnant.
After checking her notes, in which junior doctors had stated she did not want
to be pregnant, he decided to continue the operation, bearing in mind her age,
mental history, and the possibility the foetus may have been damaged by male
hormones she had been taking.
Later, Mrs Whiten's solicitors said in a statement ``Mr and Mrs
Whiten.......have not had time to think about the verdict or any civil action
and they both want some time on their own. They are going to go home and
hopefully get some rest.''
Kings Mill Hospital said: ``This case has been very stressful for all those
involved, particularly Mr Dixon and Mrs Whiten.'' It had also been distressing
for the staff and patients of Kings Mill, ``who have the utmost respect for Mr
Dixon professionally and personally''.
The statement added: ``We are pleased that, following the verdict, Mr Dixon can
continue his work......'' He has worked at the hospital for 13 years.
Mrs Whiten was 11 weeks pregnant with a son when the operation was performed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000043</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000043</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Overtime for the askers of the unasked question</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766124</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OH, WHAT joy it is. Americans are thrilled and delighted at having some real
news, the royal divorce, after all that dreary stuff about the budget and the
blizzards. All the papers are full of it this morning. The talk shows were
abuzz with semi-informed gossip and the British ambassador has been summoned to
brief the Washington Post.
Sir John Kerr was, in fact, invited to lunch at the Post some time ago, to meet
the publisher, Mrs Katherine Graham, and all the editors. The lunch is today
and no doubt there will be a brief, ernest discussion of matters Irish and
transatlantic. But what they will all want to talk about is divorce, scandal,
and will Princess Di get the vacant title of Duchess of Windsor.
British journalists are popping up on CNN and other shows to offer their
well-prepared analyses of the significance of unpublished royal letters and
questions unasked in royal interviews. Is James Hewitt really trying to sell
the princesses's letters? One of the supermarket tabloids claimed to have seen
them and published steamy extracts a week ago. Why was Mr Carling not mentioned
by the Beeb?
The phrase ``fairytale wedding'' echoes across the airwaves and the name
Cinderella is heard in the land. For a republic, America is extraordinarily
interested in the British monarchy. All the networks are planning specials this
evening, with more film clips of fairytale wedding and talking heads,
especially royal talking heads, giving the shows such names as Battle Royal.
They are saving that old chestnut, Gone With the Windsors, for later.
The princess was in New York 10 days ago, a one-day trip to take part in a
charity dinner. The paparrazzi camped outside her hotel during her entire time
in the city and were disappointed when she sneaked out the back.
Mr Henry Kissinger greeted her at the dinner with a kiss on each cheek. We
didn't know until then that they were such pals, or that royalty had sunk to
the level of minor, kissable film stars. One of the Brito-pundits on CNN today
suggested that she will move into the Trump Tower in New York, home-from-home
for various celebrities.
It is less elegant than the chateau in the Bois de Boulogne where the Duke and
Duchess of Windsor ended their days as guests of the French Government but New
York can absorb famous exiles quite easily - and Mr Donald Trump can guarantee
privacy for the most camera-shy ex-princess.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Some royal marriages that might have been</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANVAR KHAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph </GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766125</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS a royal marriage reaches its bitter concluding chapter, it is an excusable
occasion, even if only of prurient interest, to recall some royal marriages
that might have been. Here's a resume of those who didn't make it.
When American Koo Stark snuck off to Mustique with Prince Andrew in '82, the
BBC aired snippets from a work of art in which she starred called Emily. Koo,
it came to light, was a soft porn actress.
Other demanding roles had included playing the lead in Cool Passion, an
innocent girl who refuses to pleasure nuns, who is sodomised by a Lord, savaged
by dogs, and raped by two graverobbers to the sounds of Wagner, Vivaldi, and
Berlioz.
``Koo would make someone a perfect wife,'' said Mr Wilbur Stark, her father,
when the revelations hit the fan. ``She is a very selective girl.'' Obviously.
But what about Prince Andrew himself, 22 at the time, a man who allegedly told
the Queen that ``girls who live with mummy and daddy, ride horses, and take
secretarial courses simply don't interest me at all''.
The press and the palace duly decreed that given her, ahem, body of work, Koo
had no morals, and therefore was an unsuitable partner for the prince.
Of course they hadn't met the future wife yet, Sarah ``Fergie'' Ferguson, the
topless, toe-sucking children's novelist.
And what about the sad case of Group Captain Peter Townsend, Second World War
pilot, hero, equerry, and lover of Princess Margaret? They were doomed, doomed.
The princess publicly announced that she would not marry him and the nation,
still somewhat shaken by the abdication of Edward VIII to marry Wallis Simpson,
was reassured.
However, the palace has always promulgated a freaky interpretation of human
emotion, to which Townsend, judging by this statement, made in a 1978
interview, had already succumbed: ``If you spend all your time in bed making
love, you can't win battles. All passion dies after six months or a year. I am
faithful to duty. If Margaret had wanted it, I would have married her. We
didn't part with tears in our eyes. We just felt like a stiff drink.''
There is still, however, the unresolved matter of Mrs Camilla Parker-Bowles,
married, divorced and, as always, available. She allegedly approved of Diana
but probably as breeding stock.
Camilla would not have tended the sick and needy. Not for her the Aids crusade.
If she had made it to princess, she would probably have raised the profile of
horse charities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wretched name of Brocket must not be forgotten</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRIAN WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766126</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Up spoke the men of Knoydart; ``Away and shut your trap.
For the word of a Saxon brewer's boy we just don't give a rap.
We're all of us ex-Servicemen who fought against the Hun.
We know our enemies by now - and Brocket, you are one.''
HAMISH Henderson's great anthem marked almost the last land raids in the
Highlands, carried out by men returning from the Second World War and
confronted with the horrible irony that the land they coveted, in order to live
and work in the place of their birth, was still owned by Lord Brocket - one of
Adolf Hitler's leading British admirers.
Brocket Hall was Britain's Vichy-in-waiting. Now it is a conference centre
whose owner, the third Baron Brocket, had #20m of vintage cars in the garage.
Most of us, if we needed the money in that position, might have thought of
selling a few of them. But there is nothing straightforward about the British
aristocracy. How much craftier to chop them up and melt them down!
I would like to think that among the vestiges of local population in Knoydart
this week, a toast was sipped to the fall of the House of Brocket. All good
things are worth waiting for. And the descent of the third Baron, alias Charles
Ronald George Nall-Cain, could scarcely have been more spectacular.
Unfortunately, it was not yet the descent into the cells. After Brocket (Eton
and the Hussars) admitted trying to swindle two insurance companies out of
#4.5m, Judge Rodwell let him out for Christmas ``so that he might be allowed to
attend to matters of deep family concern''. (If my constituents tried that one
in Kilmarnock Sheriff Court they would probably get an extra 30 days.)
Perhaps the suite of well-appointed cells recently vacated by Mr Darius Guppy
have not yet been refurbished. Or maybe Lord Brocket will use the time to
consult the same physician who diagnosed Alzheimer's disease in Ernest
Saunders, leading to his release (on compassionate grounds) and subsequent
miraculous recovery. The law works in mysterious ways.
The Brocket baronetcy was bought from Lloyd George in 1921 for the equivalent
of #500,000. For that reason and no other, the third Lord Brocket retains a
season ticket with full speaking and voting rights to the House of Lords where
he takes the Conservative Whip.
Neither has he been shy about exercising these rights. In the light of his
conviction as a swindler on the grand scale, some of his contributions to the
columns of the House of Lords' Hansard have acquired an added piquancy.
For instance, he was very keen under rule of law during the miners' strike,
demanding action against pickets who ``constitute a threat to law and order and
to freedom of the individual''.
Then there was Lord Brocket on the poll tax: ``No socially minded person could
possibly disagree with the principle . . . I can thoroughly recommend to the
poll tax demonstrators in Wandsworth the game of cricket, or perhaps rugby, if
they are at a loose end.''
Lord Brocket confirmed his Thatcherite credentials in an economic debate: ``The
Government, quite correctly I believe, have changed the country's thinking in
that it is admirable to be successful and this natural inclination to
accumulate wealth is neither perverted nor in any way wrong.'' Tell that to the
insurance companies!
With power of hindsight however, Lord Brocket's most revealing contribution to
their Lordships' House came during a debate on the DTI report on the Al Fayeds
and the House of Fraser: ``It may well be that a rosier picture was painted of
their wealth. But which one of us has not at some time discouraged our bank
from believing that our assets are a little greater than they are? It is only a
matter of degree.''
The next line of Hansard reads: ``Noble Lords; `Oh!''' Lord Brocket had
apparently done the impossible. He had shocked the House of Lords on the
subject of money. The following speaker - Lord Longford, whom he might now get
to know better - chastised him: ``I believe that a lie is a lie, and if you lie
for a period of time you are a discredited person.''
All good fun, but the incredible point is that these were contributions to
debates in what is theoretically the highest debating Chamber. And just as
happened regularly between 1974-79, Lord Brocket (if available) will be able to
vote with the rest of them to obstruct and delay a Labour Government's
legislation.
That is not a marginal point of democracy, but a central one. The first Lord
Brocket bought the title. The second Lord Brocket was pro-Nazi. The third Lord
Brocket is a convicted fraudster. But the fourth and fourteenth Lords Brocket,
unless something is done, will still be in there legislating.
Thankfully, something is going to be done. Labour is committed to removing the
voting rights of hereditary peers - a small and woefully belated step in the
right direction. When it comes to discussions about availability of
parliamentary time, I trust that the wretched name of Brocket is not forgotten.
``We know our enemies by now - and Brocket, you are one.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A RASH OF CRUCIAL SYMPTOMS</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARAH URQUHART</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766127</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DR ALAN Pithie, a consultant in infectious diseases at Ruchill Hospital in
Glasgow lists the symptoms of bacterial meningitis as a severe headache,
drowsiness and a fever. In 50% of cases a fine rash also occurs, which blanches
on pressure.
``Not all the symptoms may occur,'' he says, ``but those that do will develop
simultaneously.''
The symptoms develop quickly and are similar to those of flu. This makes
knowing when to call in a doctor a problem.
As well as causing inflammation of the meninges - the lining of the brain - the
bacterium can cause generalised septicaemia - blood poisoning.
According to the Menigitis Research Foundation the main symptoms to look out
for in this case are: a high fever which may not be initially present,
shivering and cold hands and feet, a rash, nausea and vomiting, rapid
breathing, drowsiness, severe muscular aches, abdominal pain and sometimes
diarrhoea.
Septicaemia can occur with or without meningitis. The trigger symptom is the
rash of tiny pink spots which later develop into larger purple, bruise like
marks.
According to the foundation a simple test for septicaemia is to press a glass
against the rash. A septicaemic rash will not fade and will remain visible
through the glass.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Charles ends speculation that Camilla will become queen</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766128</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SPECULATION that Camilla Parker Bowles could one day become Queen Camilla has
been rife ever since news of her intimate relationship with the Prince of Wales
first emerged.
Just how deep their friendship ran was first detailed in Andrew Morton's
biography of the Princess of Wales.
However, it was the prince's public admission of adultery in the Dimbleby TV
interview last year that fuelled speculation he might eventually remarry - to
48-year-old Mrs Parker Bowles.
The princess herself confirmed her estranged husband had long been in love with
Mrs Parker Bowles with her comment in last month's Panorama interview: ``There
were three of us in this marriage, so it was a bit crowded.''
Yesterday's statement from the prince's press secretary that the heir to the
throne has no plans to remarry effectively means Mrs Parker Bowles must confine
her role in the prince's life to that of mistress.
One obstacle to a possible royal union with her was removed earlier this year
when her marriage to Andrew Parker Bowles ended after 21 years.
It also appeared, from opinion polls, that even the public, initially hostile
to the notion of Charles and Camilla becoming husband and wife, were beginning
to warm to the prospect.
Mrs Parker Bowles's refusal to talk publicly about her affair with the prince
has made her a figure about whom little is known.
She has, at the same time, helped to win round some sections of the
establishment who admire her discretion.
Hardened royal watchers had little success in lifting the veil of secrecy which
has shrouded her private life and, despite an almost constant media spotlight,
Mrs Parker Bowles has managed to maintain an almost dignified mystique.
The only insight into the woman who has entranced the Prince of Wales since
they first met 25 years ago has come from more outspoken members of her family.
Her former brother-in-law, Mr Richard Parker Bowles, told the Mail on Sunday
last month that Camilla was a ``wrecker''.
He claimed she was ``made of teak'' and actually encouraged Diana to marry
Charles because she thought she could manipulate the young princess.
``When it came to Prince Charles, Camilla always knew that she held his
heart,'' he added.
Political opinion has been shifting gradually towards the idea of the prince
marrying Mrs Parker Bowles.
In a poll of MPs conducted by the Sunday Times last weekend, exactly 50% of
Labour Members who responded believed the union should be allowed to take place.
Only 26% of Tory MPs thought the prince would be able to wed his mistress and
become king.
Before yesterday's dramatic announcement, there had been mounting speculation
among privy counsellors and MPs that Mrs Parker Bowles could take the title
queen consort if she was married to Prince Charles when he was crowned king.
Many agree Camilla would have made the ideal wife for Charles, with their
mutual love of hunting and the outdoors.
They are similar in age - Charles, at 47, is a year younger than his mistress -
unlike the gap of 13 years between him and Diana.
Mrs Parker Bowles has an intriguing historical link with royalty as her
great-grandmother Alice Kepple was mistress to Edward VII.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jane Scott investigates how the department stores dress up their cafes' festive fare while Anvar Khan reveals what the best-dressed tree will be wearing this Christmas No crackers, that's par for  the course</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JANE SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766129</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN the going gets tough, the tough go shopping, but even the most
battle-hardened need a break sometimes, and the lunchtime search for a
restaurant is on.
It might be adding insult to injury - after all, you've just spent next month's
rent money on presents for the family there - but the canteen in the department
store is awfully convenient and lo and behold, they're serving Christmas lunch.
But is it worth the visit? The Herald sent out some of the toughest testers in
the business, members of the Strathclyde Elderly Forum pensioners' action
group, to see what they made of the festive fare at Glasgow's department stores
and supermarkets.
The response was an almost universal ``Could Do Better''. Cold food and long
queues were frequent complaints, but where staff were friendly and helpful the
store immediately scored higher marks. Christmas shopping over? Then let's get
stuck in.
n.Store: Debenhams, Argyle Street.
Tester: Edward Traynor.
Meal: Turkey, peas, roast potatoes and cranberry sauce; passion cake; #5.59.
Overall rating: good.
Would you recommend it? Yes.
``There was nothing I particularly liked or disliked, but the place was almost
full at 12.45pm.''
n.Store: Frasers, Buchanan Street.
Tester: Nan Masson.
Meal: Turkey, sprouts, carrots; Christmas pudding; #6.95.
Overall rating: Poor.
Would you recommend it? No.
``The meat course was cold, the bacon round the sausages was dried out and the
stuffing was horrible, but the Christmas pudding and brandy sauce was hot and
tasty. If they can produce a Christmas lunch for #7 they could at least serve
it hot!''
n.Store: BHS, Sauchiehall Street.
Testers: Betty Porter and Mrs JM Gilchrist.
Meal: Turkey, sprouts, carrots, potatoes, sausage stuffing; Christmas pudding,
coffee; #6.04.
Overall rating: poor.
Would you recommend it? No.
``The meal was cold and when returned for heating there was very little
difference. We were not offered cranberry sauce although it was listed.''
``Disappointing generally for such an establishment. Poor display for Christmas
meal and difficult to read.''
n.Store: C&amp;A, Trongate.
Testers: George Bennie and Duncan Munro.
Meal: Turkey with sausage stuffing and trimmings; trifle; #3.99.
Overall rating: average.
Would you recommend it? Yes - but only for the price.
``Meal could have been warmer.''
``The veg was over-salted for my taste, but the turkey portion and quality was
good.''
n.Store: Woolworth, Argyle Street.
Testers: Sarah Hart and Jean Smith.
Meal: Turkey, roast potatoes, Duchesse potatoes and peas; milkshake, Christmas
pudding, tea; #4.75.
Overall rating: average.
Would you recommend it? No.
``The wait we had was very poor.''
``We had to wait a long time for the meal. It was a shame for the girls because
they were overworked. They did try their best.''
n.Store: Littlewoods, Argyle Street.
Testers: William and Georgina Pollock.
Meal: Tomato soup, turkey, sausage, stuffing, carrots, sprouts, potatoes; lemon
meringue pie; #7.18.
Overall rating: average.
Would you recommend it? No.
``The cost was too high, but the restaurant was clean and the service good.''
``The meal was fat and greasy, but I liked the soup and the sweet. The service
was quick and the restaurant clean.''
n.Store: Asda, Sylvania Way, Clydebank.
Testers: Rhona Pidgeon and Audrey Wilson.
Meal: Turkey, stuffing, sprouts, potatoes; cappuccino cake and cream; #6.88.
Overall rating: Excellent/ good.
Would you recommend it? Yes.
``I particularly liked the friendliness and helpfulness; I haven't visited this
restaurant for a very long time, but I will be back.''
``This is a pleasant, good eating place. I liked the friendliness of the staff
and the cleanliness.''
</TEXT>
