<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Vauxhall deal puts pressure on rivals</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766130</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A THREE-year deal for Vauxhall's 8000 manual workers looks set to increase the
pressure on other UK motor manufacturers to concede a shorter working week.
Under the offer, being recommended by negotiators, Vauxhall workers will
receive a pay rise of 4%, or #12.25 a week - whichever is greater - followed by
rises in line with inflation in the next two years.
The company has also offered to cut an hour off the 39-hour working week,
although a commitment to work 48 hours of overtime during a year has been given
by unions.
Vauxhall workers have been banning overtime and finishing work two hours
earlier on Friday to press for a two-hour reduction. The workforces at Luton
and Ellesmere Port are expected to be balloted on the deal in the new year.
In conceding a cut in the 39-hour week, Vauxhall has made it virtually
impossible for Ford - whose 22,000 blue-collar workers are due to be balloted
on a 9.25% deal over two years with no cut in hours - to avoid doing the same
or be forced to buy off its workforce to retain 39 hours.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Instructor cleared of blame for pupil's fall</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766131</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN Edinburgh climbing instructor yesterday was cleared of all blame for the
injuries suffered by a pupil in a fall from a Northumbrian rock face.
Mr Peter Pope, of Molesey in Surrey - who fractured his spine and his left
wrist in the fall - failed in his bid for compensation and was ordered to pay
costs.
Judge Diana Cotton QC said climbing was a dangerous sport and noted that Mr
Pope, 53, had been ``determined'' to blame the 1990 accident on his instructor,
Mr David Cuthbertson.
The judge ruled: ``There was no failure by Mr Cuthbertson either to instruct or
supervise Mr Pope which was causative of the accident.
``I believe that Mr Pope's position throughout has been that he paid for a
guide and that he was entitled to have his safety guaranteed.
``To engage in what even he regarded as a high-risk sport in that frame of mind
was, I consider, foolish.''
Mr Cuthbertson, now 37, of Colinton Mains Road, Edinburgh - a member of the
Association of Mountain Guides - had been Mr Pope's instructor during a
climbing expedition to Back Bowden Doors, Northumbria, in Easter 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gas prices set to tumble</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<FLAG>business comment</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974766132</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE formal signing tomorrow of the #2000m deal between BP and Sonatrach to
develop the southern Algerian gas fields has far-reaching repercussions which
should be good for both British and European consumers.
But it delivers another nasty blow to British Gas and also to Shell which has a
quarter of its gas reserves in the North Sea as well as substantial gas
distribution interests in Benelux and Germany.
At present, the average cost per therm is about 15p for an industrial user in
the UK which is the lowest price in the western world and about 45% of the cost
of both France and Germany.
The pity is that British Gas is now making losses of perhaps 2p per therm
because of the contracts it entered into to develop gas fields and is now
sitting on a #40bn surplus of gas contracted at 20p per therm.
The private consumer side is still highly profitable but British Gas's market
position is being increasingly undermined by new operators such as Amerada Hess
now offering a 15% discount on annual bills of over #1100 in some parts of
Britain and Total of France another package much the same.
British Gas is trying to offload its long-term surplus into Europe through an
inter-connector to Zeebrugge in three years time and is pressing for it to be
allowed into the Belgian industrial system and also access to Germany. But the
key player is arguably the German chemicals colossus BASF whose Wintershall
subsidiary is importing massive quantities of gas from Russia's Gazprom and is
determined to gain market share at the expense of the more established and
ossified Ruhrgas.
The BP-Sonatrach arrangement will result in gas being supplied through the
Transmed pipe to Italy and later through the Mahgreb system into Spain and
Portugal and so put even greater downward pressure on prices.
Industrial customers in all these countries will benefit before the householder
because they will have greater flexibility in sourcing. But prices will
inevitably fall across the board as more distant producers such as Iran and
Qatar enter the scene with a commodity which does seem to be in global surplus
for at least the next three decades.
Although British Gas is trying all means to be released from its expensive
contracts, it faces the most difficult problems of any of the utilities in 1996
as the European gas market enters a period of fundamental and probably chaotic
restructuring. It is difficult to see it coming out other than covered with
wounds.
Balancing act
THE UK's trading balance with the rest of the world looked a lot healthier than
expected following publication of the third-quarter current account which
includes the beneficial impact of invisible earnings from financial services,
investments and tourism.
According to British Invisibles, a private sector body which promotes
invisibles exports, these continue to show a strong surplus and should come
close to equalling the record #20.4bn recorded in 1994.
This is all to the good and will offset to a great extent the deficit on the
country's visible trade. But they are also primarily responsible for showing up
the precariousness of trying to forecast or estimate the balance of payments.
There are often major revisions to these figures which are after all only
estimates. The second quarter of the current year is a case in point with the
contribution from investment income now revised up from #1500m to #2000m. This
just for one quarter.
Adjustments can amount to a considerable sum, completely changing the
complexion of the balance of pay-    ments not just as the year progresses but
also in the final quarter as has happened in the past.
At the moment the figures are working in Britain's favour and will probably
continue to do so. But it does make nonsense sometimes of all that has gone
before.
Boring Hanson
ONE equity that is unlikely to figure on many 1996 buy lists is Hanson despite
the very poor showing this year, when the shares have underperformed the market
by 26%.
The yield is nudging 8%, twice the market average, and it is difficult to see
what will make the shares turnround. One analyst has described the group's
problems as those of old age which is rather cruel given that its founder and
leader Lord Hanson is now rising 74 but it does sum up the group's predicament.
Growth becomes progressively more difficult as a conglomerate gets larger.
Targets have to get bigger and bigger and as the activities proliferate
poorly-performing areas end up cancelling out the growth sectors and earnings
stagnate.
Conglomeracy has been out of fashion for years now and yet Hanson has not tried
to adapt to the times and still has no strategy except to grow by acquisition,
the latest being Eastern Electricity. Belatedly it is making major divestments
and concentrating on core activities.
The case against Hanson is not so much bearish as boring, with a third of the
group in low-growth areas like tobacco and energy and the bulk of the rest in
building materials and chemicals which are notoriously cyclical.
Some #2000m to be realised from disposals next year will de-gear the balance
sheet but the main problem is cash flow. Eastern will not be the cash cow some
thought because it has a heavy capital spending programme in hand, including
power stations.
Lord Hanson has already ridiculed the idea of the dividend actually being cut
but the point has now been reached where the market would take a dim view if it
was raised, which he would no doubt like to do, as its sustainability would be
in doubt.
There is one way excitement could be rekindled - a massive break-up of the
while group - but Lord Hanson would surely be unable to oversee the
dismemberment of his life's work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Church and state matters loom large in royal romances both past and present Implications of the hitches</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MACLEOD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph </GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766133</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROYAL divorce chills the constitutional blood of big chiefs in the British
state and the prime difficulty is that of the sovereign's relationship with the
Church of England. In Scotland, the Kirk is merely the national church,
recognised by the state but entirely free from the scrutiny of Parliament and
any executive influence by the monarchy.
The Church of England is a truly established body. The sovereign is its supreme
governor; she, in principle, appoints bishops (though the function is now
devolved to a complex arrangement between Downing Street and the Church
hierarchy) and Parliament still, in theory, directs the Church of England in
matters of doctrine and worship. This was last demonstrated in the famous
stushie of 1928, when the Revised Prayer Book was rejected by Parliament.
The Church of England inclines to a Roman Catholic repudiation of divorce and,
specifically, ecclesiastically sanctioned remarriage after divorce. This is
most ironic. It was through a most famous divorce that the Church of England
split from Rome in the first place.
The claim of the Tudor dynasty to the English throne, nearly 500 years ago, was
somewhat tenuous. Henry VII won the throne only by concluding the Wars of the
Roses and bumping off Richard III. While he strengthened a flimsy claim to
sovereign right by marrying Elizabeth of York - a sister of the princes in the
tower - a good clear succession was vital if the Tudor claim to rule could be
cemented.
Arthur, Prince of Wales, had to make a good marriage. So he wed Catherine of
Aragon and, shortly afterwards, died. Rather than waste a perfectly good bride
and fall out with the Spanish monarchy, his brother Henry duly married
Catherine in turn. This, by canon-law of the time, was technically incestuous.
A Papal dispensation was sought and obtained, on the improbable basis that
Arthur's marriage to Catherine had not been consummated.
However, Henry VIII, as he now was, desperately needed a male heir. Catherine
produced one daughter, Mary, but no surviving boys. No queen regnant had then
sat on the English throne. A female heir could not be chanced. Henry (who was
cursed with a theological mind, as well as a raging ego) became convinced that
his lack of a son was God's righteous judgment. His marriage was unlawful. The
heavens were angry. And Anne Boleyn, who now featured in his life, was both
beautiful and seemingly fertile.
The Pope refused to grant annulment or divorce. He could not afford to insult
Spain and the Holy Roman Empire. So Henry made himself effective Pope of the
Church of England. He even, rather cheekily, arrogated the title of Defender of
the Faith for that role - which the Pope had granted him as a faithful son of
Mother Church.
Catherine died of a broken heart. Anne Boleyn fell from favour, was divorced
and beheaded. Henry divorced his fourth wife, Anne of Cleves, because she
proved much uglier than the advertised product. He divorced and beheaded
Catherine Howard too. Small wonder that his two daughters grew up with evident
psycho-sexual problems. Mary's wretched marriage ruined her monarchy, and
Elizabeth, child of Anne Boleyn, never married at all.
Charles II could well have sought a divorce, over a century later, if he had
wanted one. His Queen, Catherine of Braganza, was barren. The Duke of York,
Roman Catholic heir-presumptive, was widely loathed. However, Charles seems
genuinely to have loved his wife and resisted all schemes for her removal. It
is perhaps the only honourable aspect of his disreputable career. It is said
that Charles had married before, to the cheerful tart Lucy Scott - certainly he
made their son Duke of Monmouth - but Charles never admitted this. Otherwise,
the Duke of Roxburghe and Buccleuch would be king.
James succeeded and was overthrown; his little son disinherited. The exiled
House of Stuart was barred from succession and, following the death of James's
daughter Queen Anne in 1714, the Crown passed by statute to George, Elector of
Hanover, great-grandson of James VI, and between whom and the throne at least
38 people had a stronger claim.
George I was already divorced. He was a strange, dull, boorish man who never
spoke more than a few words of English and spent most of his reign in Germany.
By 1714, he had savagely repudiated his wife, Sophia Dorothea - who had
foolishly embarked on a very obvious affair - executed the lover, divorced the
wretched Sophia Dorothea, and slapped her in a grim Hanoverian tower. There at
length she died. She never saw Britain and was never queen. George I did not
remarry and, in 1727, their son George II succeeded him.
When George III became king in 1760, he had to make a good marriage. There is
an abundant evidence that he was married already - to an obscure Quaker lassie
- but the bond was secret and easily set aside. George married Charlotte of
Mecklenberg-Strelitz. It is said that, some years later, she learned of the
earlier ceremony - the lady involved was now dead - and, mortified at the
thought of living in sin, insisted on a second marriage service with George,
drolly disguised as a ``turn'' in a masqued ball. (If this is true and the
additional wedding followed the birth of Edward, Duke of Kent, in 1776 -
Victoria's father - then he was a bastard and our whole royal house
illegitimate.
By now royal marriage was fraught with legislation. The Act of Settlement of
1701 forbade any Roman Catholic, or the spouse of a Roman Catholic, from
succession. George III - whose relationship with his sons was diabolical -
forced through the Royal Marriages Act, forbidding any of his descendants to
marry without the sovereign's permission, until they had reached the age of 25.
(This is still on the statute book, so the Queen must be bothered by a lot of
obscure relatives.) What provoked George to this was that his son, the Prince
of Wales, had secretly married a Roman Catholic wifie, Maria Fitzherbert.
Nevertheless, the young man was compelled to ignore this and proceed with a
grand wedding to Princess Caroline of Brunswick. Caroline was fat, washed
seldom, ate messily, and smelled. ``I need brandy,'' gasped the prince to his
valet when the lovebirds first met, and at the ceremony itself he was so drunk
he could scarcely stand.
George loathed his new wife and, at length, when her debauches became the talk
of tout Londres, tried to divorce her. (He was now Prince Regent, his father
having gone quite mad.) The celebrated ``Delicate Investigation'' was launched
in Parliament. The quotes and evidence still make good reading but the divorce
was denied; the mob, in true English fashion, stormed the streets on Caroline's
behalf. In 1820, George III died. George IV refused to acknowledge his wife as
queen and when she turned up for the coronation she was denied admittance. She
left, storming and cursing, and died soon after.
When George IV died in 1830 - ``there can scarcely be a wet eye in the kingdom
for this debauched monarch'', The Times editorialised sourly - they found,
rather sweetly, a miniature of Maria Fitzherbert in a locket on his breast.
In the long reign of his niece Victoria - despite the cheerful carnality of her
own heir - the royal family became respectable. It fell to her great-grandson,
Edward VIII, to revive old torments.
Edward succeeded George V in January 1936 and he was maniacally in love with
Mrs Wallis Simpson, who was married already and who had previous spouse still
living. She would happily have remained the king's mistress and this his
Ministers would have tolerated.
However, when he applied for divorce in the late autumn, it became apparent
that Edward, in all seriousness, meant to marry her. Technically, he had every
right to do so. The sovereign could marry whom he chose but he was readily
tricked into seeking the counsel of the Cabinet. He was thereafter bound, by
constitutional precedent, to follow the advice of his Government, and the
governments of the dominions.
Mrs Simpson was an American and a commoner. She was also a lady with of shady
past and dubious connections. That was enough to hang her in political eyes but
her marital past was sufficient excuse to resist the king's desire. The Church
of England now had a Catholic view of divorce: basically, that marriage was a
sacrament and a true marriage could not be broken. A marriage of the Supreme
Governor to a divorced lady was unacceptable.
Edward VIII, in other respects, was unacceptable already. Mrs Simpson's divorce
could readily have been blocked and the whole abdication avoided. That no
effort was made to do so is significant.
By the time George VI died, in 1952, folk in high places knew that his younger
daughter, Princess Margaret, was in love with his equerry, Group-Captain Peter
Townsend. Townsend was handsome, gracious, witty, and a war hero. He was also
divorced. He had been the innocent party in the divorce - granted on the basis
of his wife's adultery - but he was divorced.
The crisis bubbled on for several years, until - with the implacable will of
her mother, the Church of England hierarchy, and Anthony Eden's Cabinet against
her - threatening loss of royal status, wealth, and protection if she dared so
to wed - Margaret turned 25 and was free, in law, to decide for herself. It was
useless.
``You may put your books away, Archbishop,'' she said sadly, when the smarmy
Fisher came with his latest battery of tomes and lecture-notes, ``I have
decided not to marry the group-captain.''
``What a wonderful person the Holy Spirit is!'' exclaimed the cleric.
Margaret, in 1960, married Anthony Armstrong-Jones. By the end of the decade,
the bond was in deep trouble and, in 1976 - somewhat smothered by Wilson's
resignation and the breaking of the Thorpe scandal - the Snowdon's separation
was announced. Divorce duly followed in 1978.
Margaret was marginalised and unpopular. Damage to the House of Windsor was
minimal. Surely there could be no more divorce scandals in the close-knit House
of Windsor?
We ken noo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
