<HEADLINE>Jail for man cleared of sex-shop killing</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766134</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN cleared on appeal of murdering a woman during a sex attack was jailed
yesterday for 18 months for two indecent assaults.
Wayne Darvell had carried out the attacks after being released from prison by
the Court of Appeal.
Darvell, 35, was jailed for life in 1986 and served seven years for the murder
in a Swansea sex shop the previous year of an employee, Ms Sandra Phillips, 38.
She had been sexually assaulted and petrol was splashed over her body.
Darvell's campaign to be freed was led by the BBC's Rough Justice TV programme.
It succeeded in 1992 because of doubts about prosecution evidence.
Darvell, of Neath, West Glamorgan, was jailed at Swansea Crown Court yesterday
for indecent assaults on girls aged 17 and 13.
In August last year, he was fined #250 for an indecent assault on a legal
secretary in a Neath alleyway.
After Darvell and his co-accused brother, Paul, had their 1986 murder
convictions quashed, three policemen were charged with attempting to pervert
the course of justice. They were cleared by a jury.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NO HEADLINE PRESENT</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JACK MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766135</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOURNO Ken Roy once wrote a profile about yer Urban V here. Said he looked
forward to my autobiography and hoped I finished it before my heart attack.
(Ken, like many others, suspects that my vigorous approach to life will result
in an early demise. It is not always like this. Archie Hind, the novelist and
critic, was telephoned once by an aged cousin who told him that his uncle Andy,
aged 92, had died in his sleep. ``He wis nivver the same,'' said the crone,
efter he wis gassed in the First War......'')
But this Roy may be right at that. Every Christmas sees my heart attack mair
likely. It is Christmas that does it.
I hate Christmas: I write this every year. I was listening to a wireless
Scotland programme in which a lady journalist examined the curious notion that
women get the worst of it at Yuletide. You know the drivel: the women do all
the cooking of the various beasts laid in front of them and the men just go
down the pub.
In the case of most lady journalists if I was their man I would forego the
turkey and trimmings and have organised the air-tickets to Bermuda months back.
But I am not married to a lady journalist: in fact I am not married at all. But
I still get rubbish at Christmas.
Far from women doing all the work at the Festive, it is the men who are given
all the unnecessary guilt. For a start, for years I did the Christmas dinner
and enjoyed it. My own brother does, with the willing acceptance of his partner
who doesn't even resent being told what to do in the matter of the duxelles
because, goddamit, my brother does the bloody cooking all the year round anyway.
Yet I have a wee feeling that I am not right here. I mean, my brother loves
Christmas. His little eyes are shining with the prospect of the fairy lights
strung across his soul and psyche. His daughter, a teenage lass who at present
makes Gertrude Lawrence appear a rubicund milk-maid from an Ivor Novello
operetta, she is that sophisticated, is aghast at my younger brother's dreadful
enthusiasm. But for myself I like it.
Jaded as I feel, the sight of a 46-year-old man jouking round the most obscure
electrical shops for the one fairy light which will let the others work at all,
or the sheer vision of the foolish chap making his own marzipan and flaming the
brandy for his version of fruit mincemeat one can perfectly easily purchase out
of a Robertson's jar...... Jesus, you should see him on Chrstmas morning when
he stands above you like Jules Streicher in jack boots, just to make sure you
open your presents. He wraps his presents with more glittering packaging than
Tony Blair has ever thought up.
And last year I enjoyed Christmas because of his relentless and childish glee
at Chrissie. I enjoyed as splendid a dinner as one could imagine in the house
of wee George Quar, Scottish telly chef, he of the bow-tie, ready quip, and
ex-Allan Glen's boy, whit else? But yet I still hate Christmas, and suspect the
heart attack is nearing. It does each year and nothing to do with overeating or
drinking too much: I do that every day as it is.
Ken Roy, the journalist who predicted my early shuffle off should know this.
You should see me at this time of year when the amateurs are out. Especially
the amateur professionals.
I can - just - put up with the novices who fondly imagine they can drink like
Brendan Behan in New York, the last days. I can do a deefy to those who turn up
once a year simply to tell me that there is another wean on the way and they
don't bother reading John Macleod. The other way round would be interesting
though not as peculiar a juxtaposition.
What I can't manage is pubs shutting early and publicans not giving me a wee
lock-in because they are pissed off by the sudden incursion of the public and
then take it out on me. Or TOA taxis who don't bother coming in the pub to tell
you that your taxi has arrived and when you ring the blaggards you are informed
that you should have been waiting in the snaw/sleet/rain/cauld for a taxi
driver.
Damned glad they were to have you the rest of the year. Contempt for the public
should be consistent and not just confined to Yuletide. This is where the heart
attack comes. When I can't get a cab or a drink or a table in a restaurant and
when the wireless tells me how wonderful the family is and the blatts tell me
that single people are at fault for their own misery at this time of year.
Happy Christmas. And not a Christmas card either, to any of you. Wait till New
Year and I'll have the heart attack then. No, later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000055</DOCNO>
