<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rave case highlights impossible crime Judges clear up meaning of intent law</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766136</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN alleged Hanger 13 drugs dealer is to stand trial - accused of attempting the
impossible.
It is alleged that Mr James Docherty believed he was in possession of ecstasy,
although the 20 tablets turned out not to be a controlled drug at all.
The prosecution has been made possible by a Court of Criminal Appeal ruling
that it can be a crime under Scots law to attempt to do something which is
physically impossible.
The decision brings the law of Scotland into line with England. Last week,
22-year-old Louise Skidmore, a former British international synchronised
swimmer, was jailed for two years in Plymouth for offering tablets she
mistakenly thought were ecstasy.
Mr Docherty, 24, of Queen Mary Street, Bridgeton, Glasgow, was charged with, at
Hanger 13, Pavilion Road, Ayr, in November 1994, taking possession of 20
tablets which he believed contained ecstasy with intent to supply and
attempting to have the class A drug with intent to supply it.
He argued at Ayr Sheriff Court that this was not a competent charge under Scots
law and took the case to the Court of Criminal Appeal after his plea was
rejected.
The case went before five judges because they had to reconsider previous
three-judge decisions dating back more than 60 years.
The leading judgment was delivered by Lord Ross, the Lord Justice Clerk, who
heard the appeal with Lord Justice General Hope and Lords Sutherland, Cameron,
and Johnston.
Lord Ross said it was essential to bear in mind that an attempt to commit a
crime was a different offence from committing the complete crime.
There could be no question of an accused committing a crime which was
impossible to commit. The most that he could be guilty of in these
circumstances would be an attempt to commit the offence.
``The fact that it is impossible to commit the complete crime does not, in my
opinion, preclude the Crown from charging an accused with an attempt to commit
the crime.
``I see nothing illogical in an accused being charged with attempting to commit
a crime which is impossible of achievement.
``A man may be convicted of an attempt to steal by putting his hand towards
another man's pocket with the object of stealing money, even though there was
nothing in the pocket to steal.''
Because he had taken steps towards committing the crime, he could be convicted
of attempted theft.
Lord Ross added that a previous statement by a judge in 1928 that ``to attempt
to do what is physically impossible can never be a crime'' was an unsound
statement of the law.
He also disapproved of a ruling in a case from 1937 that before the Crown could
charge someone with attempting to procure an abortion the woman must be
pregnant.
He added, however, that the belief of the accused was a relevant consideration.
In a case like the present one, the Crown had to allege that the accused
believed that the tablets in his possession contained a controlled drug.
``If he did not believe that, the charge of attempting to commit the crime
could not succeed.''
Lord Ross gave a number of hypothetical examples - a man who tried to
assassinate a corpse or a bolster in a bed believing them to be live bodies, or
taking away an umbrella with intent to steal only to discover later that it was
your own umbrella.
``I am satisfied that all these instances would constitute relevant charges of
attempt to commit the complete offence because the accused had the necessary
criminal intent and had taken positive steps to carry out his purpose.''
Lord Johnston gave other examples of cases where a charge of attempting to
commit a crime which turned out to be impossible could be brought - attempted
rape of a tranvestite where the attacker thought the victim was a woman, and
attempted bigamy where the accused believed his first wife was alive although
she was in fact dead.
All five judges agreed that the charge against Mr Docherty should stand and
refused his appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Links in helping to build up resistance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MACDERMID</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766137</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MENINGITIS strikes fear into parents every winter as they read of an outbreak
here, a death there. Statistics indicating that it isn't really on the
increase, that there is no pattern to it, that death or serious after-effects
are rare, are of little comfort to the unlucky few.
In fact there are about 2000 cases every year in the UK of bacterial
meningitis, the most serious variety, and one case in ten proves fatal.
Dr Leslie Smart, who monitors notifications at Ruchill Hospital in Glasgow,
said: ``Every time someone dies it hits the headlines, and rightly so. It is
important to get treatment as quickly as possible, so parents should be on the
look-out for signs and symptoms.''
One of the enduring mysteries is why a relatively common organism can come out
of the blue to strike down young children or teenagers with such devastating
results, leaving others around them untouched.
It is a mystery which Dr Caroline Blackwell and fellow microbiologists at
Edinburgh University have dedicated themselves to solving.
They have found themslves in a sinister world of viruses which pave the way for
the meningococcal bacteria to take hold, and of germs which use the body's own
defences - the white cells - as Trojan horses to ride through the circulation
and nervous system.
Some of these phenomena may hold the answer to many cases of cot death as well
as meningitis - alhough they are separate disorders there are eerie parallels
between the two.
``We are looking at inherited characteristics, viruses and cigarette smoke to
determine why one child in a group is susceptible and not another,'' Dr
Blackwell said yesterday.
``One of the factors we are interested in is why virus infection might make
people more susceptible, because there have been reports of an upsurge in cases
of meningitis after a flu outbreak.''
Babies under two are unlikely to have had flu before they contract meningitis -
but every winter thousands of them are affected by Respiratory Syncytial Virus,
(RSV), and many require treatment in hospital intensive care units.
Dr Blackwell and her colleagues believe there may be a legacy from this illness
in the form of a substance which makes the cells lining the baby's nose and
throat stickier, allowing the meningococcal bacteria to get a better hold.
``It may be something new, or the RSV may be increasing the levels of something
which exists naturally,'' she said.
Normally the presence of the bacteria - which can be found in about 10% of the
population at any one time with no ill effect - helps the baby to develop
immunity.
``It might be that the sticky substance leads to greater numbers building up
until an opportunity emerges for them to hop into the blood and nervous system,
without triggering the white cell's immune response.
``Antibodies which encounter these germs normally coat them and get them into
the white cell to be killed off. In the absence of the antibody they get in by
the back door.
``People who don't have the antibody, like babies and young children, may not
have been exposed at low level in order to gain immunity.
``This normally grows in strength up to the age of 12, by which time mos
children are immune.
``But they may still encounter a strain of bacteria to which they have not
acquired immunity - different groups of meningococci have different overcoats
to which the antibodies stick and help the white cells remove bacteria from he
blood.''
Investigations into the role of cigarette smoke have taken Dr Blackwell's team
to Greece, in a project sponsored by the Greek health ministry, the Athens
School of Public Health and the Meningitis Association of Scotland.
``There could be two effects - children who live with smokers may be more
susceptible to virus infection - which might also account for the higher rates
of cot-death among babies in smoking households,'' she said.
``Or it could be that people who smoke are more likely to be carriers of the
organism. We have found, for example, that teenage smokers are more likely to
have the meningococcal bacteria, but active smoking does not appear to be a
risk factor for meningitis.''
Previous studies have shown that children who live with smokers are at an
increased risk of the disease, and Dr Blackwell's team found their own evidence
for this in Greece, where children whose mothers or grannies smoked were more
likely to be carriers of the meningococcus bug.
This effect was not replicated in smoking fathers; those who were responsible
for children's care through the day were the key.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
