<HEADLINE>LAW SOCIETY OF SCOTLAND President named</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766138</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GRANT McCulloch (above),    43, a solicitor advocate and a leading personal
injuries lawyer, is to be the next president of the Law Society of Scotland, it
was announced yesterday, writes CHRISTOPHER REEKIE.
He is currently vice-president of the Society and will take   office for one
year from next May.
Mr McCulloch is an accredited specialist in medical negligence cases. He was
involved in the TSB flotation case and last year in Martin against Chapman, a
case which produced the highest-ever award of damages for personal injuries in
Scotland.
He became a Law Society Council member in 1987 and has chaired committees
including judicial procedure and professional practice. He has been a partner
with Drummond Miller WS since 1979.
R.John Elliot, chairman of the Law Society's professional practice committee
and chairman of Lindsays WS, is to be the new vice-president of the Society
from May.
</TEXT>
