<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Singing out the old</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN FERGUSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766139</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SILENT night? Forget it. The little town of Bethlehem lying still in a
dreamless sleep? Oh, please. Forget all those Christmas cards with their
placid, beatless cores and dusted, hobbling old words. Nowadays, in clubland,
nothing is calm, though all remains bright, and Glasgow is no little town
devoid of dreams. Club-culture turns silence into blistering sound and sleep
into something that the body can wait for. Today it is becoming almost
traditional for people to spend Christmas Eve and Hogmanay in the hot bosom of
a club on the helter-skelter ride of sound, light, energy and dance.
Traditional? too strong a word for it? Well, perhaps. Increasingly popular is
probably a more realistic term, but Christmas and New Year clubbing is not far
from reaching traditiondom. Yet what character does seasonal clubbing have that
warrants such popularity?
Once through the door, dressed-up, supped-up, buoyed-up for the night's events,
club-goers can naturally expect to find different experiences on different
nights at different venues.
First of all, it has to be understood that there are two main club camps: the
devotional clubber who is serious and analytical about venues, DJs, musical
trends and the effects of dry ice on the unborn child, and the cheddar-clubber
who loves all things cheesy, a mild Madonna track, a mature handbag and a
crumbly old Sugar Daddy to spread her dreams on buttered toast. The
devotional-clubber will pay homage in venues like The Tunnel, The Arches, The
Sub-Club and the Arena. The cheddar-clubber follows the strong scent to
Cleopatra's, The Cotton Club and Victoria's where they will encounter chart
hits, seasonal singalong songs and typical chintzy, sparkly party decor. But
both divisions want to party as much as the other at the end of the year -
after all, partying knows no social barriers, is no respecter of age or race.
The very act of partying is, in itself, definitely traditional.
Over the past few years the strongest tradition of festive clubbing has been an
increase in entry fees to capitalise on the surfeit of hungry clubbers
desperate to devour a clubbing experience. Did someone - above the clamouring
party sounds - say ``exploitation''?
``Christmas and New Year has always been a good excuse for clubs to make a lot
of money,'' agrees Stephen Faulkner of Reds on Sauchiehall Street, a club that
falls nicely between the crass and the credible, ``We're keeping our prices
down, and still having drink promotion nights in the hope that people loyal to
the club will come to us throughout the season, not just for a couple of
nights.''
Happily, the club promoters' and owners' desire for a fast festive buck seems
to have kept its head lower than usual this year, many clubs are endeavouring
to keep their entry charges at a typical amount for their venue, but the big
bad wolf of growing competition between clubs could have more to do with this
than a charitable change of heart.
And yet, for all its growing success, clubs are still unsure quite what to do
with Christmas Eve and Hogmanay. Devotional clubbers have only recently found a
New Year countdown in their favourite venues, due to the seriousness that house
and techno music initially inspired. Nowadays, the genres have a little more
sense of humour, but clubs are still uncertain just how far to exercise it. And
because guest DJs are hard to find as few disc-spinners want to be in a strange
city slaving over hot decks on such important nights, most venues fudge, they
mish-mash, they throw something together. The nights are like empty vessels
with ineffectual tinsel rudders that mean it could sail off in any number of
directions; not exactly a luxurious yacht, and no-one really steering the
evening.
``The way we see our nights at The Tunnel,'' says Brian Reid, area manager for
Big Beat, the company that owns the club, ``is that we don't want to get in the
way of people having a good time. Michael Kilkie will be the DJ on both
Christmas Eve and Hogmanay. There won't be a single bit of tinsel in the place
but we'll be painting a Christmas scene with the decor.''
Decor is at least one area where clubs can confidently add festivity without
infringing upon musical expectations. The rest is left to the natural evolution
of atmosphere provided (or not) by the club's clientele; the good time
hopefully being had by all.
If Christmas Eve and Hogmanay are precarious nights for clubbers, at other
times in the Christmas/New Year season clubbers needs are quite nicely
saturated. Sly is a student night at The Tunnel on December 26 with an
excellent reputation for delivering seasonal kitsch alongside necessary sounds.
Edinburgh's infamous techno extravaganza Pure has another one-night-stand at
The Barrowlands on December 30, and on the same night the illustrious Cream
promoters take up The Arches and make the space their own. Also at The Arches
on Boxing Day, the great John Digweed is the guest of Streetrave, with CJ
Macintosh in support.
The message seems to be that if serious clubbers want to be certain of a good
time then they should take advantage of the whole festive season rather than
relying on the Eves - Christmas or New Year.
To cut a long dress into a short party frock, Christmas Eve and Hogmanay
clubbing is, for the devotional clubber, a growing phenomenon in search of a
tradition, treading the thin hem-line between club-preciousness and
clubbers'-seasonal exuberance. But it's all surely set to change as clubbers
learn to take themselves less seriously, and promoters gain a sense of humour
as well as a scent for cash.
In the meantime, a new food should perhaps be added to the traditional seasonal
fare of turkey, mince pies and cranberry sauce - cheese, spread on thickly and
dressed in a tacky mini and a Santa Claus hat. After all, at this time of the
year, there's so much of it about.
</TEXT>
