<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Flawed recipe for success</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766140</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOO few prison officers at Holloway. Too few nurses at the Royal Edinburgh
Hospital. Overcrowded classrooms in schools. Youngsters begging on the streets.
Stress at work at a worrying level. Unemployment rising again. Millions turning
to gambling on the National Lottery.
This may be the recipe for economic success, but whatever happened to human
happiness?
Elspeth Porter,
116 Danes Drives, Glasgow.
IN the age where the breakdown of civilised behaviour seems to be accelerating,
and governments are feebly reacting to events instead of shaping them, is it
any wonder that hitherto decent and law-abiding people are becoming fearful for
the future for themselves and their families?
There is no-one I know, regardless of age, who envisages a brighter future for
the generations to come. The tragedy of such thinking is that it is
self-fulfilling and can only serve to encourage many to grab what they can for
themselves in an increasingly hostile attitude to authority.
Sadly, for most of us, selfishness and greed seem to be endemic in the highest
echelons of our institutions, with the result that contempt for authority is
universally felt if not openly displayed.
I feel especially sorry for our police forces who are in the front line between
the disillusioned, disenfranchised, and dispirited sections of our community
and an increasingly insular Government.
Is it any wonder that extreme nationalism and fascism are on the march once
more?
As a Scot, I feel that we as a nation might yet set an example of tolerance and
fair play that other nations will recognise and emulate.
In the present political quagmire, however, this would only come about through
the installation of a national democratic Government with attendant powers to
harness the indigenous and still potent force of a people whose sense of
justice is historically proven.
Wm P Henderson,
15 Rockhampton Avenue,
Westwood, East Kilbride.
IN his article (Judges who can do the country a large favour, December 15) on
the Save Our Railways action against privatisation, Brian Wilson cites John
Major's ``I will tell the Rt Hon Gentleman that what is rising is investment in
the railways and the standards of service to the passengers''.
He also told the nation at large in 1992 that there would be no increase in
taxes. Not a lie, of course, merely a prophecy and promise bedevilled by
``events'' - or ``life'', as some people call it.
It would seem that if the population, if not the world, at large would stand
still and do nothing, the Government's promises could be realised. It's all
those nasty ``events''. By the same token, of course, supposing that what Mr
Major says is true, the rises in ``investment in the railways and the standards
of service'' are also ``events'' and in no way the outcome of Government
policies.
Or have we all got it wrong in this pantomime season? Is John Major the Good
Fairy and are the Tories Guardian Angels, with malevolent Unemployed,
Foreigners, Criminals, Single Parents, Schoolchildren With Knives, and other
forces of evil bringing about``events'' that thwart Unalloyed Good (or Tory
policy, as it is called)?
What if the Conservative Party stood still (or went into Whipping-boy
Opposition) for a decade or two and let the rest of the Creation get a look in?
F G Robinson,
11 Woodlands Court,
22-24 Woodlands Terrace,
Glasgow.
ISN'T it marvellous that Hampden Park can get #23m from the Lottery fund, and
yet the Clyde Maritime Trust may be forced into selling the sailing vessel
Glenlee through lack of funds?
After all, we're not all that brilliant at football, are we?
Ian Sinclair,
3 Elm Road,
Burnside, Rutherglen.
</TEXT>
