<HEADLINE>Warning over #6-a-week increase in council rents</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766141</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COUNCIL rents in Aberdeen could rise by #6 a week as a result of new financial
controls imposed by the Government unless current investment in the housing
stock was reduced, it was warned yesterday.
Councillor Ramsay Milne, housing convener of Aberdeen District Council and the
new Aberdeen City Council, condemned the Scottish Office decision which will
see an #8m cut in the authority's housing capital spending budget.
Under the new rules, which take effect from April 1, councils will be forced to
use 25% of their capital receipts for the repayment of debt.
``This means we are not only having to cope with a lower figure from last year
but that we will only be able to use 75% of it on our stock,'' he said.
He attacked the Government for ``blatantly massaging the figures to make them
look better''.
Mr Milne said the Scottish Office figures were based on an estimated sale of
821 council homes while the council's statistics showed the number would be
around 700, leaving a discrepancy of over #2.65 million.
Aberdeen council rents for the next financial year will be fixed in February.
</TEXT>
