<DOCID>GH951222-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sacked gamekeeper denies he was poaching</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766142</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GAMEKEEPER, sacked after being accused of salmon poaching, yesterday said he
would not have put his job on the line by doing something so silly.
Mr Andrew Thomson, 31, from Invergarry, also insisted there was no hook on the
line when he was surprised on the bank of the River Garry in Inverness-shire by
the new laird.
Mr Thomson, originally from the Glasgow area, claimed at an industrial tribunal
in Inverness that he was only ``test casting'' a new rod he had taken on
approval from an angling shop in Inverness. There was a fly on the line but no
hook. He eventually bought the rod.
He said new laird Paul Williamson, 30, from Norfolk, did not come close enough
or touch the line to see if there was a hook on it. Mr Thomson agreed he was
going through the same motions as someone angling.
The bailiff said he was ``devastated'' when, three months later, his bosses,
the Ness District Fishery Board, accused him of fishing illegally and dismissed
him.
The tribunal will give its decision later on the unfair dismissal case.
</TEXT>
