<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mountain safety review is placed on hold</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766143</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE results of a review of the Scottish Avalanche Information Service announced
earlier this year by the Scottish Office are not likely to be published until
May next year, it was confirmed yesterday.
Concern has been expressed in some quarters that the service, established in
1988, has not been extended beyond the mountain areas of Lochaber, Glencoe, and
the northern Cairngorms.
Eleven of the 23 victims of avalanches in the past seven years have been in
areas that are not covered, such as Torridon in Wester Ross, Lochnagar on
Deeside, and Creag Meggaidh in the Loch Laggan area.
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth decided to commission a review costing #5500
to look at the service in view of the 12 deaths which occurred in avalanches
last winter.
A review group, whose members include representatives from the Mountaineering
Committee of Scotland and the British Mountaineering Council, will report to Mr
Forsyth next May after gleaning expert advice from mountaineers on the most
effective way of providing the service.
Mr Forsyth stressed yesterday that the review, carried out under the auspices
of the Scottish Sports Council, was concerned with getting expert advice on the
most effective way of providing an avalanche information service.
Mr Hamish MacInnes, an international consultant on mountain rescue, who was
instrumental in establishing the avalanche service in Scotland, said last
night: ``The service is very important to Scotland because of the greater
emphasis these days on outdoor activities.
``It is every bit as vital as daily weather forecasts and badly needs expanding
to take in more areas than it covers at present. Hopefully, the review may lead
to this.''
</TEXT>
