<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ten-year sentence for screwdriver attack</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766144</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PERSISTENT offender who stabbed a man with a screwdriver, endangering his
life, was jailed for 10 years yesterday at the High Court in Glasgow.
The court had heard how 23-year-old Frank Carroll had stabbed Mr Stewart
McFadyen, a worker in a surgical appliance business, after an attempted robbery
at Templeton Business Centre in the city's east end on August 31.
Carroll, of Whitevale Street in Camlachie, was charged with the attempted
murder of Mr McFadyen, who had suspected him of robbery and accosted him in a
lift. Carroll had attempted to break into a parked car.
The screwdriver had pierced one of the two main arteries of Mr McFadyen's heart.
During the two-day trial, surgeons told Mr Iain Bonomy QC, prosecuting, that
when Mr McFadyen arrived at the city's Royal Infirmary he was on the point of
death.
Blood pumping from his pulmonary artery was filling up the heart sac to the
point where it was so enlarged it was ready to stop beating.
Doctors just had 10 minutes to find out what was wrong with Mr McFadyen and
save his life.
In the desperate race against the clock, surgeons opened up his chest, released
the blood from his heart, looked for the injury, and made repairs.
Mr Bonomy revealed that Carroll, a persistent housebreaker and car thief, had
four convictions for resisting arrest where police were involved.
At the time of the offence, Carroll was doing 125 hours community service at
the Templeton Business Centre after a conviction at Airdrie Sheriff Court in
October 1994.
He was also out on licence after serving half of a six-month sentence for car
theft.
Jailing him for 10 years, Lord Gill told him: ``Your record establishes that
you have been a persistent criminal since you were 18.
``With this conviction, you have moved into a much graver category of crime.
``The medical brilliance of doctors saved you from a life sentence today. This
was a very grave crime.''
Lord Gill ordered that Carroll finishes the other half of his six-month
sentence before starting the new one.
Following the sentence, Mr McFadyen commented on his ``have-a-go-hero'' status.
He said: ``I was standing looking out of a window overlooking the car park when
I saw this guy break into a workmate's car and then head towards the building.
``I ran down the stairs and grabbed him by the arm. I told him that I'd just
seen him breaking into a car but he denied it.
``The next thing I marched him to the lift and put him inside.
Mr McFadyen added that if in such a situation again, he would call the police.
``And that's what I would advise anyone else to do who finds himself in a
similar situation. It's not worth risking your life for.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Singer's brother sent to secure hospital</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766145</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE brother of pop star Boy George was committed yesterday to a secure mental
hospital for an indefinite period for the manslaughter of his wife.
St Albans Crown Court was told that Gerald O'Dowd, 32, was a paranoid
schizophrenic who was suffering from delusions when he stabbed his wife Gillian.
Mr Graham Parkins QC, prosecuting, said the 32-year-old was ``almost certainly
resting'' when she was stabbed once in the heart at home in Tring,
Hertfordshire, in September.
Psychiatrists told the court O'Dowd had been suffering from a severe mental
illness.
After stabbing Gillian, he drove to Tring police station and placed a knife on
the bonnet of a police car outside, Mr Parkin said.
He told two officers: ``I think you'd better take this. I think I have killed
my wife.''
O'Dowd had pleaded not guilty to murder but guilty to manslaughter on the
grounds of diminished responsibility.
Mr Adrian Redgrave, QC, for the defence, said his client had no recollection of
the killing and was shocked and grieved by Gillian's death.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>It is harder to be sick when you are also poor</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766146</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WOULD like to thank you for the article in Weekend Extra on November 4 about
La Quetzal in Guatemala. I am pleased to continue buying your paper knowing
that you have a commitment to reporting the truth about our world and that you
have given people an opportunity to do some good, via the Scottish Catholic
International Aid Fund, for the people of La Quetzal.
I have been a SCIAF supporter for many years and normally at this time send a
donation to it in lieu of Christmas presents to my mum and dad and my sister
and her husband. This year's donation goes to La Quetzal and I have photocopied
your article to let them see who they are benefiting.
Perhaps next year you could feature a similar article and suggest that people
donate to a project instead of buying presents for people who don't need them?
One of the best presents I ever had was when I opened a card from my sister
which said: ``A donation has been made in your name to buy food for a year for
a street child in Guatemala''. It still brings tears to my eyes when I think of
it.
Over the past fortnight, since the beginning of December, my two sons and I
have been suffering from flu. It occurred to me during this time how fortunate
we are to live in a comfortable, centrally-heated house and not to have to
worry about the electricity bills when I am constantly washing and drying
sheets because the boys have been fevered and sweating.
And of course we have ready access to a doctor. My boys have asthma so we never
have trouble asking for a doctor and our GPs are excellent.
My younger son, who is 12, has been in and out of hospital since he was three,
and I have always been aware how much harder it is to be sick when you are also
poor. This is as true for the people here at home as it is for the people of La
Quetzal. What an unjust world!
Anne Russell,
14 Wellington,
East Kilbride.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Invitation that could not be taken sitting down</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM SHIELDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>diary</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766147</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE scene is One Devonshire Gardens, the frightfully upmarket Glasgow hotel,
where Hamilton and Inches, the frightfully upmarket jewellers are having a wee
do. The idea is to sell some of their frightfully expensive baubles to a
discerning West End of Glasgow public who were warmed up for the purpose by
being served a little wine and a few canapes.
A lady journalist has been invited along to this glittering event and, after
being on her feet for some time, she parks her backside on one of the hotel's
frightfully upmarket armchairs. A waitress offers her a canape at which she
duly begins to gnaw.
At this point a frightfully upmarket lady from Hamilton and Inches approaches
and asks her to stand up. ``Why?'' she asks, not unreasonably. ``This is a
cocktail party,'' the H&amp;I lady hisses. ``One doesn't sit down at cocktail
parties.'' At least, now we know.
Taking the fizz
WE are indebted to Glasgow Guzzler, the organ of the West of Scotland branch of
the Campaign for Real Ale, for an unusual recipe for a home-made brew.
It reports how a chap called Bruce Williams, whose brewery produces Heather
Ale, gave a demonstration of how to make an instant creamy beer of the type now
favoured by so many drinkers: ``He took a half-pint glass of soda water, gave
the liquid a beer-like caramel colour by squeezing out a damp tea-bag, then
added to it some propylene glycol and isomerised hop extract.
``Then he gave it a thick creamy head by blasting some nitrous oxide into it.
The end product looked, smelled, and even tasted like a half-pint of beer, even
though two minutes earlier it had just been a glass of soda water.''
The recipe is not a recommendation from the Camra people as to what we should
be supping this festive season. It is yet another attack on the big brewers
who, they claim, ``are flooding the market with keg beers which use a mixture
of nitrogen and carbon dioxide to make the beers a bit less fizzy while
appearing to be a real ale''.
Mr Williams described his instant beer as a ``brewery formulated cocktail''. It
sounds more like a Blue Peter ale, with shades of John Noakes saying: ``And
here's one I made earlier''.
Ups and downs
WE are also indebted to The Absolute Game (OK, we admit that this ``indebted''
bit is another way of saying we are about to plagiarise shamelessly from the
aforesaid publication) for an update on the trials and tribulations of Hamilton
Accies FC.
The club is anchored, as they say, at the foot of the first division and are
homeless since Douglas Park was reduced to rubble in readiness for the
contruction of a Sainsbury's supermarket.
Repeated promises of a spanking new stadium in which to build a bright new
future appear to have fallen on sceptical ears. The TAG mag reports Willie
McInally, the Accies supporters club bus convener, as saying: ``I suppose we'll
believe it when we see the first brick being laid.''
He is backed up by Colin Mitchell, editor of HASH, the club fanzine, who says:
``We will not believe it until we are sitting in it.'' More realistic is the
anonymous fan, who asserts: ``I will not believe it until I am sitting
depressed in it.''
Sound and fury
NOW that the Diary is on the Internet, we get many messages from far-flung
parts, some of which are not far-flung enough. But we liked this possibly
apocryphal tale from Toronto. It concerns the local minister who pulled up
behind a car stopped at the lights and noticed that it boasted a bumper sticker
saying ``Honk if You Love Jesus''. He duly honked, only to have the occupant of
the front car leap out and approach him shouting, ``Can't you see the f*******
lights are red?''
Strip torn off
FERGUS McCann is at a social function and is in buoyant mood, given Celtic's
recent run of good results. ``What would you say if I told you that I had #20m
here to complete the rebuilding of Celtic Park?'' he asks, patting the
left-hand pocket of his jacket. ``And what would you say if I had another #15m
here to buy players?'' he asks patting the right-hand pocket.
``I'd say you were wearing David Murray's jacket,'' replies one of the
assembled company.
The end is nigh
AND so we reach the final chapter of our quest to find the perfect fourth Wise
Man to visit the stable in Bethlehem.
John Quinn of Lenzie wins a Langs whisky first-footing kit for his nomination
of Rab C Nesbitt saying ``Err merr myrrh - fae me an Mary, Mary.''
Norrie Stevenson of Doonfot, Ayr, wins a bottle of Langs Supreme whisky for one
of the worst puns in living memory. Norrie suggests that Humphrey Errington
would turn up with a lump of Lanarkshire Blue, courtesy of his new company
Cheeses of Nazareth.
Andy Murray receives a bolt of lightning for suggesting that Glasgow City
Council have decided to up the security at their George Square nativity scene
by nailing the Baby Jesus to the crib.
There's still time
LAST-MINUTE shoppers still have time to get along to the Lobey Dosser gift shop
which has newly opened at the Halt Bar in Woodlands Road, Glasgow, right
opposite That Statue. Umbrellas, T-shirts, pens, ties, and jigsaws all bearing
the Dosser Industries imprint are available. Part of the profits go to
maintaining the world-famous equestrian statue which recently, we have to
report, suffered a severe fetlock injury requiring the attention of men with
soldering equipment.
The injury was sustained by big boys jumping on the back of the wee horse. They
also broke El Fideldo's reins. All has been put right now and the statue even
has a new coat of patina for its Christmas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shooting stars and turkeys</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766148</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MORE years ago than I care to remember, I carried out an investigation for the
late-lamented Sunday Standard into the size of the public-sector carrot
assembled to persuade Roche, the tight-lipped Swiss-based pharmaceutical
multinational, to build a vitamin C production plant at its existing vitamin B1
and B5 facility at Dalry in Ayrshire.
The carrot was stoutly rooted in deep soil, but eventually, after some serious
digging, I came up with an estimated cost, to your purse and mine, of each new
job. An astonishing #350,000. Between them, the Scottish Office and Strathclyde
region were contributing #70m in grants and infrastructure costs to a project
with a total price tag of #162m. All to create 200 new jobs.
When the story appeared, Roche senior management in the UK got very agitated. A
top team flew to Glasgow to confront me. We sat down - the simmering tensions
ruffling the tablecloth - for a lunch where I fully expected to be the main
course. Instead, they spent most of the meal interrogating me on who had fed me
my evidence.
In their innocence, the Roche execs did not know that case-by-case details of
regional development grants, regional selective assistance, and other state
investment incentives were published, on a regular basis, by Government. The
trick was knowing where to look. There was a presumption, in their questioning,
that the state aid they were getting for the Dalry project should have been
kept a closed commercial secret.
Globetrotting companies and the governments keen to lure them and their jobs
are often anxious to play down the importance of hard cash in deciding between
this location or that. The quality of the local skills base, access to markets,
and a hundred and one other factors, they'll tell you, loom just as large in
the final decision.
But the truth is that the market for inward investment, like every other free
market, operates on a price mechanism. And, with upwards of 35 million people
unemployed across the European Union, this is most definitely a seller's
market. In all but exceptional cases, if a government doesn't put a big enough
carrot on the table, it won't be at the races when the final choice is made.
When the Chunghwa Picture Tube company of Taiwan was finalising plans recently
for its major new plant at Mossend in Lanarkshire - #260m investment, 3300
direct jobs promised - a last-minute snag emerged. No-one had told Chunghwa's
president that the Government assistance package he was already promised - #80m
plus or #24,000 a job, 'tis said - was taxable.
``Get me the Irish on the phone,'' came the aggrieved instruction, as the
Scottish team scrambled to raid the Lanarkshire Development Agency's
accumulated budget surplus and tweak the package just enough to soothe fevered
oriental brows and secure the biggest single investment ever attracted to these
shores.
A few weeks ago the Irish looked like having the last laugh on another major
investment Lanarkshire would love to get its hands on. Nokia, the Finnish group
best known for its mobile telecoms business, is contemplating building a #26m
plant making base stations and employing up to 700 people. If it comes to
Scotland it will locate in the new Hamilton International site between Blantyre
and East Kilbride.
Sources close to the haggling were gloomily reporting that the Irish were
prepared to offer #18m in grants, while the best Scotland could do was #11m.
But Nokia may be one of those exceptions where money isn't everything. The
latest indications are that the battle may now be between Scotland and Germany.
But, with Nokia's share price sliding recently, the final decision has been
pushed back into next year.
If you set yourself up - in Michael Heseltine's well-worn phrase - as the
enterprise centre of Europe, out to attract as much footloose capital as you
can to replace declining indigenous industries, there is a serious price to be
paid. As yesterday's HCI hospital report from the Public Accounts Committee
reminds us, public money put into such ventures is, at the end of the day, risk
money. You may get your jobs. But, if you don't, there is no guarantee that
you'll get your money back either.
The Scottish Office argued, in evidence to the committee, that the #18.6m in
selective assistance paid to HCI has not been ``lost'', since the completed
Clydebank hospital is there for anyone to see, albeit now operated by the Abu
Dhabi Investment Company and not the original start-up company. What was lost
was Scottish Enterprise's #5.4m package of loans and equity, together with #3m
of associated interest.
Scottish Enterprise was saying very little yesterday. But it might reasonably
have argued that, while it took a bath on HCI, it has returned multi-million
pound gains to the Treasury on a whole series of other risk-equity investments,
from Inveresk Research, Dunclair Dispensers, and Stagecoach to Calluna, Exacta,
and Spider Systems. The sale of Spider to American interests alone generated a
gain of some #7m on SE's original stake, almost enough to offset the HCI
liability, at a stroke.
There is a debate to be had - and the PAC seems keen to have it - about why
more wasn't done earlier by publicly accountable officials to track the warning
signs that HCI, as originally conceived, would turn out to be a turkey. But
risk investment is about both shooting stars and turkeys. You win some. But,
sure as eggs is eggs, you lose some too.
The real debate, surely, is about whether the state has any place in backing
risky or footloose ventures with our money. But most politicians don't seem to
want that debate. Perhaps that's because, through the eighties and into the
nineties, luring inward investment to these shores was all that stood between
us and having no industrial strategy worthy of the name. Pouring millions into
everything from Roche to Chunghwa served an important political objective. It
kept the dole queues shorter than they might otherwise have been.
There is a danger in focusing, as the PAC has done in the HCI case, on why the
turkeys aren't spotted earlier. If that's what really matters, public officials
will become more and more risk averse. In that mood, they will miss a lot of
the shooting stars too.
</TEXT>
