<DOCNO>GH951222-000068</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000068</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Words strewn along the path of broken romance</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766149</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PUBLIC utterances of the royal couple have traced the state of their
relationship over 14 years: early radiance degenerating into public feuding.
In an interview on the announcement of their engagement, Charles said he was
``positively delighted and frankly amazed that Diana is prepared to take me
on''.
The then Lady Diana appeared unable to conceal her happiness too. ``I am
absolutely delighted; thrilled; blissfully happy.''
On the eve of their 1981 marriage, the royal couple already appeared to have
thought out possible pitfalls likely to afflict the relationship.
The prince said he was confident Diana would ``develop her own sphere'', with
family and outside interests of her own.
As rumours mounted that she was bored with Charles's polo playing, the prince
blasted reports as ``absolute rubbish. It's not much fun watching polo when
you're being surrounded by people with very long lenses poking from all
directions at you for the entire time, taking photographs, which it's quite
easy to do, and saying you are bored.''
In 1984, in a rare American television interview, Diana spoke of the couple's
joy at becoming parents for the second time.
She said: ``It's interesting with a second child . . . you're more relaxed as
parents, I think, and therefore able to communicate an atmosphere of greater
relaxation to the child.''
In 1985, during an ITN interview they were asked about apparent public rows
while on holiday skiing. Charles defended his wife. ``I suspect that most
husbands and wives find they often have arguments.'' Immediately, Diana
corrected: ``But we don't.''
In 1986, an ITN documentary called In Person, In Private, featured a romantic
behind the scenes look at the royal couple's life. In one scene Diana's
excitement surfaced when she asked a lady-in-waiting: ``Will my hubby be down
from Scotland then 'cos I'd quite like to go with him?''
In 1992, shortly after publication of Andrew Morton's book Diana: Her True
Story, the couple separated. Embarrassing revelations followed.
In 1994, the gloves were well and truly off.
In Jonathan Dimbleby's ITV documentary Charles, The Private Man, The Public
Role, the prince told 20 million viewers of his relationship with Mrs Camilla
Parker Bowles. He said he had been faithful to Diana ``until it became
irretrievably broken down.''
The princess then admitted on Panorama she too had been unfaithful. She said of
Captain James Hewitt: ``I adored him. I was in love with him.''
Of Charles she said: ``My wish is that my husband finds peace of mind, and from
that follows other things.''
</TEXT>
