<DOCNO>GH951222-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The subject in the street is not amused</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766150</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Queen's intervention in the warring Wales marriage met a mixed reaction in
a straw poll on the streets of Glasgow.
Some said she should not have interfered in such a public manner - but others
said she was right.
Others were not bothered by the prospect of a divorced king.
Ms Geraldine O'Rourke, 31, of Maryhill, said: ``She's interfering and its none
of her business.
``It has now got too public and they should have been left to sort themselves
out in private.''
Mr Brian Cormbie, 54, who lives in the west end of Glasgow said: ``She was
right to do it - after all, Charles and Diana had not managed to sort it out
themselves.''
Ms Freda Leighton, of Newton Mearns, said: ``She is not interfering. Sometimes
you have to put your children right. It was all getting too public and it's
time they both were stopped.''
</TEXT>
