<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jane Scott investigates how the department stores dress up their cafes' festive fare while Anvar Khan reveals what the best-dressed tree will be wearing this Christmas A TASK FOR SPECIAL BRANCH</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANVAR KHAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766151</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN is not a nation of Miss Worlds, bovinely demanding peace, happiness and
goodwill. One of the rights of living in a materialist democracy is being able
to buy what you want and when, and customers all over Europe feel this very
strongly. In the argument as to whether alcohol could be sold on a Sunday in
Scotland, the church lost, consumerism won.
No-one wants to be Scrooge. Fewer citizens, however, now attend any religious
service. The mood is not cynical, consumerism is not the new god, but evidently
few want to conform. While the ideals of joy and compassion still stand proud
and true, there is a major disagreement among the public as to how this
goodwill should manifest itself. The Christmas Tree personifies this combat
between tradition and evolution. Few people, regardless of personal moral
values, are prepared to live with alien decor.
The modern philosophy is that individuality can be forged by what you choose to
buy. One of the easiest ways of expressing self is to be singular about
upsetting the rules. But there is spontaneity, and there is premeditated
commercial nous. The designer responsible for the current non-conformist cheer
of Princes Square, Glasgow, is Malcolm Lochhead, a Lecturer in Design at
Glasgow Caledonian University. He was commissioned by a company called Flying
Colours (Enterprises) Ltd, who produced the heraldry for the Edinburgh Tattoo.
In his opinion, unconventional design can replace any fairy tale. ``Princes
Square is a shopping centre for grown-ups. I wanted the shapes to echo the
architecture.''
The semi-circles of netting above the Food Court hold two and a half thousand
lights. ``At night they look like the night sky.'' This is a personal
interpretation of adult magic, without regression, without the regurgitation of
childhood associations, for, with the right to buy comes snobbery. Evergreens
measled with small, white sparkling lights are trendy. Pine trees with acorns,
gold balls and crimson bows are traditional and safe. A bonsai fir saturated
with fake snow is fun. But those who believe themselves to be ahead of fashion
are convinced that the Christmas tree should blend in with its environment. But
this is a naff compulsion, too close to the idea of buying a painting to match
the living room suite.
It could be the exhumation of stress, that this article is witnessing, via the
camp and careful consideration of colour schemes. ``My tree has a huge bow at
the top,'' says Malcolm Lochhead. ``It's shocking pink with butterflies,
against a pink, silver and gold background.'' And this from the man, who, when
dispensing tree-dressing advice, told me to ``keep it simple''.
But there is a clear and strong demand for Christmas decorations which provide
a means of escaping the yawnerooing ``boredom'' of fat Santa. Condomania in New
York, have allegedly decorated their tree with differently coloured condoms.
And Habitat, the vanguard of good, bourgeois taste, have taken a stand against
the curse of Christmas Tree decoration.
``Habitat have never sold tinsel, never will, and we keep garlands to a
minimum,'' states Manager Susan McEwan.
Hingy things have no place in the homes of the artistically aware. Good
decorations don't droop, like the best of breasts they keep their shape. ``If
we think we are conforming to tradition we change direction. We decide on a
theme each year, last Christmas we used what we call naturals, this year we've
used brights; pinks, oranges, blues and yellows on bright baubles and glass.''
So confident are the public in their own integrity and values, that they don't
want to pollute their domestic territory with vulgar, festive frills anymore.
Habitat are 140% up on their decoration sales last year. The Christmas climate
is changing. The supporting symbols of Christianity, such as angels and
berries, are no longer needed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trashing the law</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>check out</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974766152</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n.SCOTTISH Secretary Michael Forsyth is being urged to leap into action in the
new year to save cities from a ``black plague'' of rubbish bags.
Laws designed to punish householders who dump refuse on the street outside
normal collecting hours have been rubbished by procurators fiscal who are
refusing to take suspects to court.
Recent environmental legislation empowered council officials to impose #10
fixed penalties on persistent offenders - traced through discarded envelopes -
with the threat of heavier fines at the Sheriff Court for defaulters.
But legal experts question whether convictions can be secured without positive
identification of actual offenders, and short-staffed councils can't afford
surveillance operations.
``If a householder blames someone else - a lodger or relative - there's little
we can do about it,'' a senior refuse manager told Check-Out. ``It's become a
dumper's charter.''
In Edinburgh the #10 penalty is now regarded as a ``hollow threat'', although
suspected dumpers are told it can be imposed. ``It's become a matter of
persuasion rather than enforcement,'' said an official. ``In the interests of
health and the environment the matter must be sorted soon.''
n.WHEN a reformed Scrooge marvelled at the prize turkey presented to the
Cratchits - ``that bird never could have stood upon his legs ..... he would
have snapped 'em off like sticks of sealing wax'' - he could easily be
describing today's factory-bred successor.
At least in Dickens' day the hapless creature had only itself to blame for
obesity: the supermarket variety most Scots will be scoffing this Christmas has
little choice, according to animal rights campaigners, Viva!
Sentenced to a brief and painful existence in cramped sheds that restrict
exercise to add extra pounds, turkeys become so top-heavy their bones snap
under their own weight, trapping them in the excreta that's accumulated over
months of captivity.
Ulcerated feet, beaks sliced off with red-hot blades, osteoporosis and heart
failure, with only salmonella to avenge you after your throat's been slit .....
God bless them every one!
n.MARKING the seventh anniversary of the Lockerbie air disaster, pressure group
Disaster Action, is urging public support for a Private Member's Bill proposing
new offences of ``corporate recklessness'' and negligence.
Writing in the influential Consumer Policy Review, published by the Consumers'
Association, spokeswoman Pamela Dix estimates more than 1000 people have died
in non-natural disasters, like the destruction of PanAm 103, over the last 30
years.
Official criticism seldom results in those who could have prevented deaths
being made accountable so prosecutions are rare, says Ms Dix, condemning
``corporate violence''.
Disaster Action wants this treated like ordinary crime with new definitions of
culpability and sanctions like corporate probation to encourage higher safety
standards.
n.AN acute dilemma is facing Princess Anne following Check-Out's disclosure
that Save The Children had aligned itself with the Robertson's golliwog on jars
of Christmas mincemeat.
Among those condemning the unlikely alliance is Prince Pius Nyiam, a Nigerian
leader of Edinburgh's ethnic community, who intends to complain to HRH. She
must decide whether to offend a fellow royal by ignoring the protest, or put
the cat among the pigeons at the London-based charity with a presidential
rebuke.
Not known for mincing her words, will the Princess be giving someone a
dressing-down for this public relations gaffe? You may think that, but we
couldn't possibly comment, was the gist of Buckingham Palace's reply.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Missing patient inquiry prompts toilet checks</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766153</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SHERIFF yesterday accepted medical evidence that no treatment would have
saved the life of ex-docker John Ross, 86, a patient who lay for 30 hours
unconscious in a lavatory in a doctor's surgery in Fife because of a failure to
check them.
The elderly man went missing on August 1 after going to Muiredge Surgery at
Buckhaven in Fife to collect a repeat prescription for his 83-year-old wife
Mary. Despite a police search, he was not found until surgery staff checked the
toilet the following night.
He died eight days later without regaining consciousness and the two-day
inquiry at Kirkcaldy Sheriff Court heard medical evidence that prior to his
collapse he was ``living on a knife edge'' and could have died at any time.
Referring to the fact that a receptionist and cleaner failed to make earlier
checks of the toilets, Sheriff Gail Patrick said: ``Naturally it is of
considerable distress and anguish to Mr Ross's family that he was denied both
treatment and the comfort of professional nursing care immediately after his
collapse.''
She added: ``The evidence of doctors, however, was that for Mr Ross (a
remarkable gentleman, uncomplaining in spite of serious illness) there would
have been no difference to the outcome had he been discovered immediately, as
neither of his life-threatening illnesses could have been successfully
treated.''
In the light of that, she said, it would be inappropriate to make any findings
other than a formal verdict that Mr Ross of Sea Road, Methil, died at 2.30pm on
August 9 at Victoria Hospital, Kirkcaldy, as a result of a blood clot on the
lung and a massive stroke.
Stating that the inquiry had disclosed a ``tragic combination of
circumstances'' which resulted in Mr Ross lying unconscious and undiscovered
for 30 hours in the surgery's disabled toilet cubicle, the sheriff endorsed a
new checking and security code sent by Fife Health Board to all GP surgeries
following the incident.
Mr Ross's son Jackie declined to comment on the findings and referred inquiries
to the family's lawyer, Mr David Ritchie, who said on their behalf: ``The
family is very pleased that a full canvassing of all the issues involved was
carried out at the fatal accident inquiry.''
He added: ``I am of the view that the family's options are still open following
the sheriff's decision and they are taking stock of the situation over the next
few weeks before deciding what, if any, action to take.''
Yesterday, at the surgery - which has tightened up checking procedures, the
inquiry was told - a spokesman said: ``The practice appreciates the thorough
investigation into the circumstances of the death of Mr Ross. We are content
with the determination of the sheriff and have no further comment.''
Fife Health Board's director of primary care, Dr Gavin McBurnie, said:
``Following this incident, we ordered an immediate investigation. In the light
of the findings, we advised every medical practice in Fife of strict new
checking and security procedures which should be adhered to."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Traditions which can't be imitated</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JULIE DAVIDSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766154</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CLYDESDALE District Council is a bad loser. Having squandered #350,000 of
public money on its inept harassment of the Lanark Blue cheesemaker Humphrey
Errington, it has finally decided to leave him in penurious peace; but not
before telling the world it knows best. Cheese Wrong, Council Right - despite
four court hearings, an exhaustive scientific investigation, and a judicial
verdict which liberated the suspect cheeses and vindicated their maker.
Lanark Blue, meanwhile, has become a big cheese among small food producers, the
Che Guevara of their heroic struggle against the hegemony of mass production
and the tyranny of bulk buying. We can expect tee-shirts soon: In the Pink with
Lanark Blue, or suchlike slogans. Humphrey Errington's imaginative enterprise
at Dunsyre has been cheered on, too, by consumers - not only those who enjoy
his cheese but those who instinctively value the qualities which specialist
food producers bring to the market-place.
There are any number of vacuum-packed, orange-tinted so-called Cheddars on the
supermarket shelves. There is only one authentic Roquefort, or Gorgonzola, or
Lanark Blue, and Humphrey Errington intends to protect its distinction. His
cause celebre and the successful outcome have brought the kind of publicity he
couldn't buy; some compensation, you might think, for the #120,000 spent
defending his cheese.
But there is no return on the marketing side effects of this undesirable
investment. I had a telephone conversation with Mr Errington recently, and
asked him if sales of Lanark Blue had benefited from the public interest and
general sympathy the case attracted. ``No,'' he said, ``because we sell all we
make anyway, and I can't increase production without increasing our flock of
400 ewes, which I'm certainly not in a position to do at the moment.''
And he added, ``I could make more cheese by buying in supplies of frozen milk
from other sheep. But I'm producing a cheese called Lanark Blue, which gets its
name and its character from the milk of sheep which graze on the South
Lanarkshire hills. If I made it any other way it would be a different product.''
There speaks a food craftsman, and I wish there were more like him. How, for
example, has the famous name of Cheddar come to be represented in the popular
imagination by a peculiarly nasty shade of orange, the colour of something
which might be used to treat a fungal skin condition? My husband, who knows the
way to my heart is through my stomach, once brought me an authentic huckle of
Cheddar cheese from its home gorge; the texture of its moist crumbs and the
subtle strength of its flavour caused me to forswear forever the waxy wedges of
the supermarket shelves, dyed or undyed.
Something good does, occasionally, come out of the EC, so often the enemy of
traditional foods. (An EC directive on listeria in dairy products compounded
Lanark Blue's troubles, although it wasn't in force when Clydesdale seized the
cheeses.
In fact, the directive contains a derogation which, if used, waives the
listeria standards for specialist cheesemakers, but it was only the Lanark Blue
case which encouraged MAFF officials, prompted by Humphrey Errington's
supporters, to apply for the derogation for British cheeses.) The EC has also
become the guardian of the gastronomic pedigree.
I'm not much of a sherry drinker, but I applauded the news that as from January
the sickly beverages called British, Irish, and Cyprus sherry cease to exist.
There is only one country which produces decent fino and amontillado, albeit
with the historic co-operation of British families, and that's Spain. From the
beginning of 1996 only fortified wine produced in the region of Jerez de la
Frontera will be allowed to call itself sherry.
Which is as it should be. If you pronounce the name Jerez like a
French-speaker, rather than a Spanish one, you discover how the libation of the
suburban tippler came to be christened, and if you ever visit the bodegas of
this civilised corner of Andalucia you glimpse something of traditions which
can't be imitated. The wines of Jerez de la Frontera go with fine horses and
fighting bulls, as whisky goes with king salmon and royal stags. If it weren't
for the EC we might find Jameson calling their whiskey Scotch.
Its directives unfortunately don't extend to America, otherwise the great
champagne houses of Pol Roger and Bollinger might rest more easily in their
foundations. I once had a bad experience on a cruise ship which, although
British, sailed the Caribbean with a cargo of US citizens. As we left the
embarkation port of Fort Lauderdale the cruise director stood on deck and
shouted ``Bon Voyage'' to the spectators on the quay, just like Sam Goldwyn.
Such phoniness should have served as premonition.
At the poolside bar I picked up the drinks menu and looked at the prices.
``Wow! They're doing champagne at three dollars a glass!'' (In France the
average price of une coupe de champagne is 60 francs, over #7, and here you
might pay a fiver.) This thrilling discovery was followed by bitter
disappointment or, more accurately, sweet disappointment. The tepid pool of
sugary bubbles served in plastic beakers was not champagne, but one of the
lesser Californian fizzes. Anything that jumps about in a glass gets called
champagne in America, although the French producers have tried to outlaw the
practice.
There is craft in food and drink but they aren't works of art, which arguably
should remain in their country of origin, only to be exposed to the wider world
on touring exhibitions. Export helps the food industry, large and small, but it
carries the risk of hijack - the careless or cynical expropriation of
distinguished names, and the imperfect mimicry of production values which
should be unique.
As I walk round our cornucopian British supermarkets with their astonishing
range of produce, by no means all synthetic Cheddar and pot noodles, I feel
glad that the crop farmers of Zimbabwe and Mexico have found overseas markets
for their mange-touts and chilis; but I can't help regretting that foreign
travel holds few gastronomic surprises these days. There are few national
dishes or regional delicacies you won't find chill-cooked on the shelves of
Marks and Spencer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000074</DOCNO>
