<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The wrong snow puts an end to British polar trek</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766155</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN Antarctic expedition has been abandoned because of the ``wrong type'' of
snow, it was announced yesterday.
A hi-tech sled being used by explorer Roger Mear in his solo unsupported
crossing of the Antarctic sank into snowdrifts and caused so much delay he had
to radio for help after 41 days on the ice.
The 45-year-old Derbyshire- based explorer admitted that the sled, which
carried his supplies for the 100-day walk across the sub-continent, and which
was propelled by a specially built kite, had not been tested in Antarctic
conditions. During the walk, which began on November 4, he experienced
temperatures of minus 34C and winds of 60 knots.
On his return to Britain yesterday, he commented: ``We had not tested in that
kind of ice and I had not experienced conditions like that before.
``What we had were two different types of snow. One, sustrugi, gets eroded by
wind and is very rough. On top of that, we had hoar which you get in still
areas.
``The sled kept sliding and sinking and I was losing time and wasting energy.
``I thought I could deal with the conditions and it was a real disappointment
but it was a rational decision.''
He had set out to race Norwegian Borge Ousland, a former commando, who began
the 1657-mile journey a week before him.
Mr Mear used a radio beacon to contact his expedition headquarters to send a
plane to pick him up on December 16 - after he had travelled less than 500
miles.
He used a special kite to help pull him and had hoped to set up 100-mile,
single-day journeys if the sled had worked properly.
``I was approaching an area with lots of crevassing and I didn't want to get
caught in that.
``I was in a vulnerable position in an area where winds reach up to 100mph. I
knew that if my tent was destroyed I couldn't survive for long.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Warning over mobile phone transmitters</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766156</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
USING a mobile phone may ``cook'' your ear, a scientist warned yesterday.
According to Ole Svane, a senior physician in Denmark, the transmitter inside
the instrument generates an electromagnetic field similar to that of a
microwave oven.
In a Danish Government report into health and safety at work, Mr Svane says he
fears the phones may damage ears.
In an extract from the report, published in this month's National Association
of Health Authorities and Trusts health and safety newsletter, he reasons:
``You would never dream of sticking your head in a microwave oven.
``What happens to the delicate cartilage and bone of the ear when it is heated
time after time, in exactly the same way, as meat in a microwave oven?''
Mr Svane goes on to urge further research into the possibility of locating
nerve damage through mobile phone use.
However, a spokesman for mobile phone network operator Cellnet said: ``There
have been extensive tests on the effects of these electromagnetic fields and
none of the research has come up with evidence to suggest there are any ill
effects from using mobile phones.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
