<HEADLINE>Abtrust Emerging hit by peso crisis</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN McCONNELL, Andrew Mullins</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766158</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE dramatic effect of the Mexican peso crisis is well illustrated by the fact
that, even though Abtrust Emerging Economies Investment Trust's net asset value
was slashed by 18.6% to 82.87p in the year to end-September, the trust
significantly outperformed its benchmark index.
During the 12 months, Abtrust Emerging's benchmark International Finance
Corporation composite index tumbled 24.8%.
Abtrust Emerging suffered its worst losses in Latin America, as the shockwaves
from last December's peso crisis hit equity markets.
During the second half, its net asset value actually rose by 10.6%.
Abtrust Emerging, which last year paid a 0.20p Ordinary and 0.40p special
dividend, announced a 0.40p payout this time round, which it will at least
maintain in future years.
The #41m trust said, in spite of attractive valuations in Latin America and the
fact that stable and market-orientated governments had been in place for
several years in most countries, the ongoing strength of Wall Street continued
to divert funds away from the region.
It believes Brazil, Chile and Peru look attractive in terms of economic
fundamentals, and expects Argentina and Mexico to bounce back from the Latin
American financial crisis as interest rates fall.
Abtrust Emerging is invested in 22 countries, with 11.1% in Thailand, 10.6% in
Brazil, 9.1% in Indonesia, 7.5% in Malaysia, and 7.2% in Mexico.
Meanwhile, a poor showing by its substantial holdings in other investment
trusts' income shares saw Abtrust Preferred Income miss out on the recent
advances enjoyed by the UK stock market, writes ANDREW MULLINS.
Net asset value per Ordinary income share fell 4.2% to 86.38p during the six
months to end-November. The trust declared a second interim dividend of 3.25p,
for a half-year total of 6.5p.
Fund manager Paul Reed said the trust had performed well against a range of
internal benchmarks but declined to disclose what these were.
The remainder of the portfolio consists of Preference shares, bonds and
convertibles, which advanced with the UK stock market.
He is cautiously optimistic about the fund's immediate future and said he was
quite comfortable with the outlook for markets in the second half.
</TEXT>
