<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Allianz sees higher profits but slowdown in premium growth</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766160</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EUROPE'S largest insurer, Allianz AG Holding, said yesterday it was on track
for higher earnings for 1995, although the strong mark and weak domestic
business had slowed its premium income growth this year.
The Munich-based insurance giant said premium income rose 5.1% in the first
nine months of 1995 and lower catastrophe claims and costs as well as the
downward trend in global interest rates had boosted earnings.
``In general one can expect a further improvement in total earnings in 1995 for
the entire Allianz group, barring any large claims such as from a natural
catastrophe, amid just slightly higher premium income growth,'' it said in a
statement.
Allianz said its underwriting earnings had improved significantly at home and
abroad in the first nine months of 1995 and non-underwriting earnings were
boosted by lower interest rates and higher stock prices worldwide.
The insurer reported group net profit of DM1340m (#604m) in 1994 and premium
income of DM66.1bn (#30bn).
Allianz said group premiums totalled DM52.2bn (#23.5bn) in the first nine
months of 1995, up from DM49.7bn (#22.4bn) a year earlier.
Income growth was curbed by strength in the mark. Consolidation of new
subsidiaries added DM4000m (#1801bn) to its premium income total.
``On a mark basis, the losses of key currencies against the mark were evident.
In original currencies, premium income rose 8.2%,'' Allianz said.
The insurer also said its German business was hurt by weak demand, while
premium income fell 41% in its North American life insurance business.
German insurers have been hit this year by a round of tax increases which have
cut consumers' disposable incomes.
``In Germany, growth in property and casualty insurance of barely 2% was the
result of clearly weaker new business. In life insurance also the number and
sums insured in new contracts were significantly reduced,'' the group said.
Allianz also said intensive competition led to muted premium income growth in
other European markets.
US life business was hit by weaker demand for pension funds, sending premiums
at Allianz Life of North America down 41% to DM2500m (#1126m).
However US property-casualty business rose 11%.
Allianz said its industrial and corporate business in the United States was
boosted by its Fireman's Fund unit's allocation of $800m to its reserves to
cover environmental legal costs claims. - Reuter.
</TEXT>
