<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>We won't go away warns Brown. Fight for change continues.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ken Gallacher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766163</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish League Management Committee decided yesterday to take no further
action on the suggestions submitted to them for reconstruction by the first
division clubs.
But the fight is still on to change the present set-up. And St Johnstone
chairman Geoff Brown warned that some of the clubs who have maintained a
full-time policy - as his own has done - may have to end that if a bigger
premier division does not soon become a reality.
Initially it had seemed that the debate had ended when League secretary Peter
Donald emerged from the three-and-a-half hours long meeting to announce the
management committee's verdict.
It was only after the official statement that Brown insisted the fight was far
from over and that a formal proposal was likely to be made to the League.
Donald said simply: ``The management committee this morning were discussing the
first divison suggestion for league reconstruction which would increase the
premier division to 16 teams.
``It was discussed fully and it was felt that it would not attract the
necessary support to warrant the calling of an extraordinary general meeting
and therefore no action will be taken.
``We realise, of course, that fresh proposals may come forward, but there was
no suggestion that the present plans would be supported by the 75% of the votes
which are required for change to take place this season.''
However, minutes later, Geoff Brown, who had been one of the main backers of
the discussion paper which had been presented, insisted that the clubs in
favour of a 16-club premier division would return with a fresh look at the
current set-up.
Brown argued powerfully for change, and pointed out that the most recent
alterations to the league had been carried by only a single vote.
``That, he said,``is why the fight for change will continue. There has been no
enormous support in the recent past for changes which have taken place and,
therefore, that encourages us to go forward.''
The main objections yesterday from some of the bigger clubs represented at the
management committee - the likes of Rangers, Aberdeen and Hibs - appeared to
centre around changes to the League Cup competition.
Donald explained: ``The way the tournament has been played over the past few
seasons has been exciting and it has been popular with the clubs and with the
supporters. There was also concern expressed at the reduction in league games
to just 30 each season.''
Brown, however, made a spirited defence of the first division case. He claimed:
``Some of the clubs who have maintained full time playing staffs will not be
able to continue to do so unless there is change.
``Many of us have built new stadiums and now we have to look at the oncost. It
is not easy. We have been tottering along for the last 20 or 30 years but we
cannot keep going in the same way.
``Playing each other four times every season is a recipe for staleness. I don't
think that it helps our game develop in the way most of us want to see it go.
Ask any of the managers and they will tell you.
``The first division was unanimously behind the discussion document which was
presented today. Now we shall go back and think again and look at modifications
which may be made. We are not giving up on this because it is too important to
do that.
``I cannot say whether any club will go to the wall, you would have to ask the
bank managers about that one, but we have all been living above our means and
that cannot go on.
``There is one club now which supports this move who were recently relegated
and their experience has changed their view of what is right for the game in
this country.''
Brown's reference was obviously to Dundee United whose chairman Jim McLean is
now fully supportive of the move for change after previously backing the status
quo.
The big guns remain lined up against any alterations, along with most of the
second and third division sides. Much lobbying requires to be done by Brown and
his allies before they can gain the support they require.
One thing seems sure. The people behind this current demand for a 16-club
premier division will not go away.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Townsend is given his chance at fly-half Chalmers has to sit out the A team test</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Derek Douglas</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766164</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND will use the A game against Italy early in the new year as a dress
rehearsal for the Five Nations' Championship, and despite 11 changes in
position and personnel from the line-up which drew with Western Samoa, there
still is no place for stand-off Craig Chalmers.
Although he won his forty-sixth cap in the 15-15 draw against the Samoans last
month, Chalmers is relegated to the bench, with Gregor Townsend taking over the
pivotal fly-half role.
The revamped side for the game at Rieti, near Rome, on January 6, which SRU
director of rugby Jim Telfer said yesterday had taken on fresh importance in
view of the Five Nations opener against Ireland a fortnight later, also sees a
first A cap for 19-year-old Edinburgh Academicals' lock Scott Murray, and a
recall to No.8 for Bath's Eric Peters.
Telfer said the selection - made by mutual consent by the senior team
management - reflected his disappointment with the Scotland display against
Western Samoa.
Nevertheless, it was, he said, not necessarily the strongest combination
Scotland could field at the moment and included ``one or two'' tactical
experiments. The Italians now represent a ``fairly formidable force'' and that
had been reflected, too, in the selection.
Despite this being very much a front-line Scotland side full caps will not be
awarded by the SRU.
The only survivors from the Scotland side which played Western Samoa are Rowen
Shepherd, Kenny Logan, Bryan Redpath, David Hilton, Stuart Reid, and Rob
Wainwright, who will captain Scotland for the second time.
With Townsend moved to stand-off and Graham Shiel omitted from the squad, Scott
Hastings and Ian Jardine provide a more physical presence in the centre,
something which Telfer said yesterday was an absolute necessity in
international rugby.
Craig Joiner and Kevin McKenzie return after injury as does Peter Wright after
his suspension. Stewart Campbell, who was on the bench against the Samoans,
partners Murray in the second row, and the back-row unit - with Stuart Reid at
blindside flanker, Peters at No.8, and Wainwright at open-side - offers the
kind of blend that some had sought before the Samoan game.
The preference for young Murray to Doddie Weir at lock undoubtedly will act as
a spur to the Melrose man - he was dropped after the game against South Africa
a year ago, but came back to feature in at least part of the Five Nations'
campaign and the World Cup. Similarly, the selection of Townsend ahead of
Chalmers - criticised by Telfer after the Samoan game - offers the kind of
competition for specific places which the management are keen to foster.
Telfer said that the decision to pitch Murray into the big-time had not been
taken lightly. ``He's a very good player who has proved himself with Scotland's
under-21s and in the district matches, but this is a big step up for him.''
The director of rugby said that Townsend had been preferred to Chalmers - as he
had been a couple of seasons ago - because they wanted to look anew at the
Northampton man as a stand-off. ``Gregor is a stand-off. He was brought up as a
stand-off. It's unfortunate from our point of view that Northampton have the
new English stand-off there and Gregor is playing in the centre, but we know
what Craig can do.''
The omission of Gary Armstrong from the squad is also a talking point. Derrick
Patterson returns to the bench. ``We feel that Gary Armstrong is not back to
the kind of form that people had hoped he would be. He is still not as sharp as
he was before his injury.''
Scott Murray's elevation to top-grade international rugby has been rapid by any
standards. The 6ft 7in, 15-stone youngster has played just two and a half
seasons of serious rugby, first with Preston Lodge for a season and the rest of
the time with Edin-burgh Academicals, where he came under the tutelage of David
Sole and Jeremy Richardson.
Scotland A - R J S Shepherd; C A Joiner (both Melrose), S Hastings
(Watsonians), I C Jardine, K M Logan (both Stirling County); G P J Townsend
(Northampton), B W Redpath (Melrose); D I W Hilton (Bath), K D McKenzie
(Stirling County), P H Wright (Boroughmuir), S J Stewart (Dundee HS FP), S
Murray (Edinburgh Acadedemicals), S J Reid (Boroughmuir), E W Peters (Bath), R
I Wainwright (West Hartlepool), captain.
Replacements - M Dods (Northampton), C M Chalmers (Melrose), D W Patterson
(West Hartlepool), G W Weir (Melrose), A P Burnell (London Scottish), J A Hay
(Hawick).
Scotland under-21 (v Italy U21, January 6) - C M Sangster (Stirling County); G
M O Smith (Orrell), C A Murray (Hawick), M P Duncan (Edinburgh Academicals), S
Reed (Nottingham); K A McKee (Cardiff Inst), G Beveridge (Boroughmuir); D
Massey (Currie), G C Bulloch (West of Scotland), B D Stewart (Edinburgh
Academicals), S Begley (Glasgow Academicals), G C Perrett (West of Scotland), T
A McVie (Heriot's FP), G I Heyter (Dundee HS FP), G F Dall (Heriot's FP)
Replacements - C K Aitken (Heriot's FP), A J Bulloch (West of Scotland), E J W
Weston (Watsonians), C Cottrill (Langholm), P Holmes (Loughborough), D Jamieson
(West of Scotland), G W Scott (Dundee HS FP).
</TEXT>
