<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jockey Club probe call-off</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766165</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHELTENHAM'S controversially late abandonment earlier this month is to be
investigated by the Jockey Club disciplinary committee.
Having studied reports prepared after racing was called off at the track on
December 9, the Jockey Club stewards have decided the committee should hold an
inquiry to determine whether acting clerk of the course Edward Gillespie
complied with the rules of racing.
Jockey Club spokesman John Maxse explained: ``It has yet to be clarified which
rules are in question, just that there is a case to answer.
``There are a number of instructions issued to clerks which they are asked to
follow, and a clerk should at all times act in a professional manner.
``The most obvious similar case was at Newcastle two years ago on Fighting
Fifth Hurdle day, when racing was abandoned and clerk of the course David
Parmley was fined #600.''
The late decision to abandon the Cheltenham meeting, which featured the
Tripleprint Gold Cup, caused controversy as no warnings that the fixture was in
jeopardy had been issued.
Some 8000 racegoers had been admitted to the course when the abandonment was
announced at 12.55pm, 35 minutes after the scheduled off time for the delayed
first race.
No date has been set for the inquiry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Senior coaches given the vote</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766166</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DESPITE Scotland's indifferent international results last season, the Scottish
Basketball Association's new management board have given a vote of confidence
to their senior honorary coaches.
Allan Turner and Lesley Beaton again will take on the unpaid tasks of coaching
the Scottish senior teams later this season.
Turner, who no longer coaches regularly at senior level but has led the
Scottish team on their last two European campaigns, beat off opposition from at
least two coaches with senior Scottish club teams.
The Cumnock Team Corsa club man from Ayrshire, and his assistant from Troon,
Tom Campbell, will now be responsible for taking Scotland to the Promotions Cup
in San Marino in June.
As far as the financially impoverished SBA is concerned, however, the San
Marino event offers two positive aspects: the international governing body,
FIBA, funds the accommodation costs, leaving Scotland only to cover the travel.
Originally, the senior and under-23 coaching posts were to be combined, but the
under-23 programme looks like being restricted not least due to England
withdrawing from the proposed first Home Countries championship which Scotland
was to host.
Scotland have now been offered the Under-18 championship instead and that will
go on in April, but there is one major embarrassment - there is at present no
coach for the Scottish junior men's side.
John Grant from Arbroath Musketeers, who led the side in last April's European
qualifying event at the Kelvin Hall, has moved down to coach the Scottish cadet
(under-16) schoolboys team, although he is still willing to assist the juniors.
But there were no applications for the junior position and the SBA's
performance and excellence convener Bob Brewer is keen to hear from anyone with
the appropriate qualifications interested in taking on the job.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Deficit tops #1300m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE City Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766167</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S overall third-quarter current account trade deficit, which includes
``invisible'' earnings from financial services and tourism, proved at #1343m to
be more favourable than the #2000m or so many in the market had been expecting
though along with the accompanying third-quarter GDP it made little impact in
financial markets except, perhaps, to provide some underpinning for sterling.
The visible deficit balance of #3371m was offset by estimated invisible
earnings of #2028m. Moreover, previous quarters' deficits have been revised
downward - the second quarter from #2400m to #1176m - to paint a much brighter
UK trading picture.
As usual it was invisibles which saw the major revision, particularly the
figures for investment income.
On the basis of the latest figures, which take the total for the year to
#3400m, the Chancellor's forecast in his Budget last month for a balance of
payments deficit of #6500m for the current year may prove to over-cautious.
The Central Statistical Office says that changes to the current account data
for previous quarters were largely due to the results of annual 1994 inquiries,
the receipt of late and revised returns to quarterly inquiries and
re-assessment of seasonal adjustment.
Looking ahead, securities house James Capel's Adam Cole expects a modest
deterioration in the UK's external position in the fourth quarter of the year
taking the total to #5000m, or just 0.7% of GDP.
Next year is thought likely again to see only modest deterioration as a
worsening trade position is offset by an improvement in invisible trade, not
least because sterling's decline this year will push up sterling-based earnings
on the UK's overseas assets.
Meanwhile, there were no major surprises in the third-quarter national account
data. A 0.4% quarterly increase in GDP leaves it up 2.1% on a year earlier.
Consumers' expenditure growth, at 0.6%, was slightly weaker than previous
estimates but still well ahead of retail sales.
The detail of the figures shows the strongest increases in leisure
services-related expenditure, with catering up by 2% on the quarter and
transport by 2.1%.
Real personal disposable income (RPDI) fell by 0.2% in the third quarter so
that the increase in consumption was more than accounted for by a fall in the
saving ratio (down from 9.3% to 8.6%).
Adam Cole considers that the figures are further confirmation that the gloom
over consumer spending is overdone. Capel's interpretation remains that the
weakness of the housing market has been diverting consumer spending away from
durable goods and towards services.
However, with the housing market showing signs of recovery and real income
growth picking up, consumer spending growth is expected to accelerate next
year, while the unwinding of manufacturing stocks after their build-up is
expected to depress GDP growth significantly to the middle of 1996. For the
full-year growth expectations have therefore been lowered to 2.5% from 3%
previously.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Earle pounds better off</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766168</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Earle pounds better off
JOCKEY-turned-trainer Simon Earle is looking forward to Christmas in his new
role. He has high hopes of landing a yuletide success with Dextra Dove at
Wincanton on Boxing Day, but win, lose or draw, he has no worries about the
scales this year.
For the first time since he launched his career as a jockey in 1982 he will be
able to enjoy a Christmas dinner with no concern about his weight for the
action the following day.
``I used to think it was crazy to have racing the day after the biggest
festival of the year,'' said Earle. ``In the past, I might get drunk on
champagne, but I wouldn't be able to eat anything. But the galling thing is
that I'm lighter now than when I used to diet.
``It's because I'm working harder. I don't have time for much breakfast or
lunch and I just fit in dinner when I can.''
The 31-year-old trainer has no regrets about his decision to turn his back on a
riding career which brought him nearly 150 winners. ``It was a very big change
and training is a totally different job, but I've been really lucky the way
things have gone,'' he said.
``I've got a state-of-the-art training centre with fantastic all-weather and
grass gallops set in the wonderful Dorset countryside. There's stabling for 29
horses and we've got one of the best sponsorship deals in the country with
Dextra Lighting Systems.''
Earle's backers have had a quick return on their investment through their own
Dextra Dove, unbeaten in four runs and set to bid for a five-timer in the Lord
Stalbridge Memorial Gold Cup at Wincanton on Boxing Day.
``The aim is run at Wincanton, although he is also in at Kempton the following
day. We're gearing his season towards the Ritz Club Chase at Cheltenham and the
Grand National.
``As a jockey on Boxing Day I generally went to Wincanton, which is one of my
favourite courses. It would be wonderful to have a winner there in front of a
big local crowd as a trainer.''
</TEXT>
