<DOCNO>GH951222-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Eastern markets beckon MLC sees unlimited potential for British meat exports</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>VICTOR ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766169</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FAR East markets promise virtually unlimited potential for British meat exports
although competition is fierce, according to the Meat and Livestock Commission.
One of the key players in the field, the United States, is gradually shifting
its pork production enterprises westwards to tackle the growing markets in Hong
Kong, Japan, China, Korea and the Pacific Rim.
But British Meat export executives Ken Jones and Bent Windahl, who will be
leading a party of eight meat plant operators on an outward bound mission east
next March, are confident the British message is getting through.
``I feel we are winning respect in these markets but we cannot sit back. We
have to build on this success and this means continuing to go out there to sell
our products,'' says Bent Windahl.
The latest figures bear out the success story. Exports of pig meat to Hong Kong
for the first half of this year at 1670 tonnes compare with 740 tonnes for the
whole of 1994; for Korea the figures are 4704 tonnes (3728 tonnes); and for
Japan 2348 tonnes (477 tonnes).
The potential can be shown by Japan's total imports of 468,000 tonnes.
During the export mission to Hong Kong, Korea and Japan, the party hopes to
make a day trip to China for a first-hand assessment of the state of the
industry there.
The MLC's latest International Meat Market Review says that all factors point
to an increased Chinese meat demand.
``Pig meat will remain by far the largest meat production sector but feed
limitations may restrict substantial growth and therefore slow up gains in per
capita consumption.
``Poultry consumption is expected to show the greatest growth and is the sector
likely to make the most significant inroads into the export market.
``Demand for both beef and mutton is expected to grow and production volumes
will inevitably be huge on a worldwide scale. But equally actual per capita
consumption levels are likely to remain small.''
But Britain, and the rest of Europe, will not have things all their own way, as
Dr Mildred Hay of the United States Department of Agriculture recently pointed
out to an international meat conference in London.
US meat exports had more than doubled to 20% of the country's total production
in the past 15 years. This had resulted from a reshaping of the industry with
more vertical integration, better corporate management and the adoption of new
technologies.
The Gatt round had also opened up tremendous export possibilities, allowing
low-cost US producers to compete more effectively. Pressure was growing for
more freedom to farm in the States and this would provide more low-cost feed
cereals from set-aside land taken back into production.
Pork exports to Japan had risen 60% in volume terms this year, aided by the
ability of the US to supply fresh product as opposed to the frozen EU offerings.
The country expected to be a net exporter of beef from next year with a large
proportion of this aimed at South-east Asia.
At the same time, she expected to see more constraints on production building
up in some EU countries.
</TEXT>
