<DOCNO>GH951222-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fees for coaching essential - Higgins</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766170</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PLAYERS' associations throughout Europe are ready to react to the Bosman
verdict, and Scottish Players' Union secretary Tony Higgins said yesterday:
``All associations agree there is a need for a system which gives clubs
compensation for training and developing young players.
``But that system will have to have a more scientific approach than there is at
the moment. I don't know what the exact system will be, but it must be able to
answer questions such as how many hours are young players coached and how many
hours are put in on their education. Steps are already being taken towards this
kind of approach with the apprenticeship scheme.''
Hamilton manager Iain Munro revealed that he has suggested a new approach to
Scotland manager and technical director Craig Brown.
Munro said: ``I would like to see clubs take schools and youth associations in
their own area under their wings.
``It would be laid down in players' contracts that they must spend a certain
number of hours a week coaching. All of this would be overseen by the SFA. At
the end of the day the club would get the chance to sign any of these players
and pay a small fee to the SFA. If the boy did not wish to sign for the local
club but opted for a club in another area, that club would pay part of the fee
to the SFA and part to the local club who had done all the coaching work.
``If that boy was a success and was either capped or transferred on to a bigger
club a small portion of the fee would go to the SFA and to the local club to
compensate them for a job well done.''
Meanwhile, Reinhard Rauball, former chairman of German champions Borussia
Dortmund who has wide experience of legal disputes in sport, said the Bosman
ruling eventually would sink transfer fees for good.
``It is only a question of time when there will be no more transfers,'' he
said. ``The football authorities have got to get ready for it now . . . It is
no good when a decision is made in Europe and the countries then ask `What do
we do now?' People have to be ready with solutions
</TEXT>
