<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Old Firm memories</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766171</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHAT is the best way to re-live the atmosphere, tension and emotion of an Old
Firm match? Easy, of course. Buy The Herald Book of Old Firm Games, an
exciting, new publication which is on the shelves in time for Christmas.
It is a book not just about any Old Firm match, but about every meeting since
the war between football's greatest rivals - match reports of all the clashes,
no matter the competition, which have appeared in the sports pages of The
Herald down through the years.
We have opened our archives to help you capture the mood, the passion, and the
excitement of each era, from the forties to the nineties. Stunning pictures
also will bring back great footballing memories.
What Celtic fan would not take a great delight in being given the chance to
take himself back to the club's greatest ever victory in an Old Firm match, the
League Cup final of 1957 when they beat Rangers 7-1 at Hampden?
Billy McPhail scored a hat trick, Willie Fernie turned in one of the best
individual displays ever seen in the fixture - and the fans wrote songs and
poems about the day.
Celtic supporters also will relish looking back to 1979 when the two clubs met
at Parkhead in what was a championship decider and Celtic won a dramatic match
by 4-2.
For the Rangers fans, there is also the chance to re-live some famous
victories. Two, which came against all the odds, spring to mind.
The League Cup final of season 1970-71 when a 16-year-old Derek Johnstone took
the trophy back to Ibrox with a stunning header, and the Scottish Cup final
replay of 1966 when Danish international full-back Kai Johansen grabbed the
only goal of the game with a spectacular strike.
There is an Ally McCoist hat trick in another League Cup final, and easy 5-1
and 4-1 wins in the league during season 1988-89.
I was pleased to make a modest contribution to the book, providing
decade-by-decade summaries.
I was also given the unenviable task of choosing the 25 best players from each
club since the war. That alone is bound to spark off heated argument as so many
outstanding players had to be left out.
Every Old Firm fan has his, or her, particular memory of a Celtic-Rangers match.
No matter the memory, if it happened after 1945 it will be recorded in this
publication, which has forewords by John Greig and Billy McNeill, arguably the
best-ever captains of the two Glasgow giants.
The Herald Book of Old Firm Games (Canongate).
</TEXT>
