<DOCNO>GH951222-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mixed day for Forte</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766172</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BESIEGED Forte received both bad and good news yesterday as the City was
relaxing further into pre-Christmas torpor.
The full Takeover Panel upheld the ruling of the executive that hostile bidder
Granada was fully entitled to set out its claim that it could increase the
on-going profits of Forte by over #100m a year, before reorganisation costs.
Forte had argued that the express inclusion of this figure in its offer
document of December 14 and without a detailed breakdown failed to met the
standards relating to the provision of information as stated in the Takeover
Code.
But the Panel executive has been asked to investigate whether there may be a
need for new specific requirements covering statements where merger benefits
are quantified. However, Forte's advisers putting together the formal defence
document against the #3200m bid due by January 2 will seize upon an
authoriative hotel industry study to boost its armoury.
Britains' hotel industry is in a period of strong profits growth which is
expected to continue for another three to four years according to Pannell Kerr
Forster Associates.
They said the balance in supply and demand of hotel rooms and overall economic
growth in Britain are fueling the growing profitability of the industry.
Granada also had some encouragement.
ABN AMRO, BZW and Chemical Bank have completed the sub-underwriting of the
#2500m banking facility with 16 major banks having subscribed in addition to
the three leaders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Business digest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<FLAG>business digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974766173</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
French tighten
grip on water
THE French grip on the English water industry appears to be tightening after a
#75m bid for a water group supplying 525,000 customers in South-east England.
Mid Kent Holdings, based in Maidstone, has received an offer from a partnership
of French groups General Utilities and Saur Water Services.
The offer at 440p a share is subject to approval by the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission.
Mid Kent is one of the 28 smaller statutory water companies. In the year to
March it made profits of #8.3m on turnover of #38.1m.
The two French companies already had a 39% stake in Mid Kent also own
individual companies supplying 4.4 million customers in Kent, Essex and Sussex.
The French bidders predictably promise to cut water shortages and improve
efficiency. More pertinently, they propose splitting the company into two and
merge the parts into their respective operations.
Optimism falls
THE number of exporters reporting higher sales rose slightly in the third
quarter, according to a Royal Bank of Scotland survey. But the survey, carried
out in September and October, showed a decline in optimism about future
prospects. Royal Bank said 61.3% of exporters had experienced a rise in orders
over the previous 12 months, up from 60.1% in its second-quarter survey. But
the number of smaller firms who said they were more optimistic about the year
ahead fell to 42% from 44%.
Courtaulds sells
INTERNATIONAL chemicals group Courtaulds has sold its Amtico flooring
subsidiary for #49m to a management buy-out team with the backing of Electra
Fleming which is acting on the behalf of clients. Courtaulds will retain a 10%
equity stake in the business and may also be entitled to a further
consideration totalling up to #3.8m.
Pay boost
BURTON chief executive John Hoerner received a pay rise and other benefits last
year totalling #362,00 to boost total emoluments to #1,001,000. The
performance-related bonus jumped from #60,000 to #387,000, while his pension
fund was topped up by an extra #20,000 at #177,000 with his salary #15,000
higher at #437,000. Mr Hoerner is currently sitting on a paper profit on the
options he can exercise of #3,226,000 with Burton shares closing unchanged at
133p last night.
Concrete move
BUILDING and construction materials group Redland has acquired 29.99% of the
voting rights in Nottingham-based aggregates and ready-mixed concrete company
Ennemix. The #2m total acquisition of 5,481,840 Ordinary shares, together with
844,857 Preference shares appear to have come from the holdings of
non-executive director E A P Sells.
SmithKline buys
SMITHKLINE Beecham is buying the leading supplier of medicines in the German
supermarket sector in a #92m deal. The healthcare giant's purchase is Abtei
Pharma, which is the leader in the mass-market sector of the German food and
vitamin supplement business. SmithKline said the acquisition of Abtei would
make it the leading consumer healthcare group in Germany when added to its
existing pharmacy business.
</TEXT>
