<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Furniture showroom has diversity of styles</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Wendy Jack</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766174</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VOGUE is celebrating the opening of its splendid new 52,000 sq.ft furniture
showroom on Boxing Day, with a massive sale which will see everything reduced
in price. Located at 2129 London Road, Glasgow, the superstore is the
long-awaited replacement for the ``tester'' store at Baillieston, in which
Vogue put a first, tentative foot into the West of Scotland market.
The success of the exercise is obvious. The new showroom shares with Vogue's
main store in Edinburgh, flagship status, while Falkirk and Kirkcaldy each have
a smaller showroom.
Every conceivable taste has been catered for within three main halls, at London
Road. Whether you favour the traditional, modern or something quite out of the
ordinary, Vogue's diversity can fill the bill.
Managing director Robert Bremner, son of the founder Harry Bremner, began the
Vogue chain 22 years ago, said: ``The new showroom is roughly twice the size of
our last Glasgow shop, and is in a much more prominent position. There are no
parking problems, with space for more 200 cars.
``Our last showroom was a `toe in the water' exercise to see how we went down
in Glasgow; if it worked we planned to move somewhere else. It certainly did
work, but it's taken nearly two years to find this site, get planning and start
trading.''
How did the company find the Glasgow market?
``Very different to that in Edinburgh,'' Mr Bremner reports. ``People in
Glasgow are much more adventurous and style conscious - it's more enjoyable to
be buying for this market. We can buy something a little bit different; and we
are covering a wider scale here than we do in Edinburgh, in traditional and
modern as well as going a bit more avant-garde on the foreign side too. We buy
from around the world, from Europe to America, China to the Far East.''
Wander through the halls, and be amazed at the diversity of styles, the scope
for developing ideas, the range of fabrics available, and find your imagination
stimulated by lots of different room settings. There are accessories too, such
as lamps, mirrors and pictures. ``We do the more unusual ranges of lamps,''
explains Mr Bremner. ``We try to find ideas which are different.''
Vogue in Glasgow carries all home furniture with the exception of that for
kitchens and bathrooms. There is soft and leather upholstery, cabinet
furniture, beds, carpets and rugs, and customers will find too, a custom-made
curtain service offering a good range of fabrics.
Walk into the main hall on your arrival and be greeted by pine displays and a
fine selection of more modern furniture designs in lots of different finishes,
painted, metal and wood, highly lacquered Chinese pieces, marble, Spanish
furniture . . . fresh and appealing. The central area of this hall is given
over to a broad range of soft-hued luxurious leather suites.
The second hall houses the more traditional cabinet furniture in teaks,
mahogany, yew and the increasingly popular cherry, admired for its lighter
looks. Upholstery here will appeal to a broad range of tastes so much of its
design being attractive to many tastes and age groups.
``Very traditional, middle-of-the-road upholstery is probably the mainstay of
our business,'' explains Robert Bremner. ``Older people still tend to buy
upholstery and say they want it to last 15 years. By and large they are more
careful with their money, they don't tend to take things on credit, preferring
to pay in cash.
``We did a survey, and found that the majority of our customers up to about 40,
looking for upholstery, said they'd expect it to last eight-10 years. However,
they said they'd be looking to change it in four years, because they'd be bored
with it. It becomes a fashion item.''
Fashion is certainly an established part of the furniture trade now. Take black
leather, or black cabinet. ``The former is no longer normal domestic, and the
latter which, five or six years ago there would have been lots of on the floor
you couldn't give away now. We are seeing more variety. If you went back 10
years, many suites were still being bought in browns, mink, grey, autumny
shades, and in dralon. Then flat weaves came in, and now there's a big market
for them. Chenilles too, are in and selling very well. Machine washable covers
in 100% cotton on upholstery are popular too, while leather, very much a niche
market a decade ago, now accounts for 20%-25% of our upholstery sales.''
Currently fashionable, are co-ordinate suites, perhaps in blue with yellow
cushions, ethnic designs which are fairly trendy and tartan and plaids which
similarly take a trick with some people. ``Look at this revolutionary new
material,'' smiles Mr Bremner. ``It's called Buffalo.'' He points to a suite
covered in what looks and feels like soft suede . . . ``it's tremendously
practical, one of its major advantages. You can take a ballpoint across it, rub
the two pieces of cloth together, and the stain comes off. That's very new on
the market.''
Beauty of course, is in the eye of the beholder and so too is perception.
``We've tried to separate tastes here to a degree, but what one consumer sees
as being traditional, another will see as modern,'' says Robert Bremner. ``The
shabbily chic is perhaps the ideal example. We sell a lot of these in Edinburgh
to the New Town, big houses with traditional furniture, the West End of Glasgow
would be a similar market. Yet, we also sell a lot of the more compact shabbily
chics into new, smaller modern houses.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Arena</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Brian Whittle</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<FLAG>arena</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766175</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is difficult for me to write this article without sounding like a bitter and
twisted old has-been. However, I would just like to point out that I am not an
old has-been.
If you want to be a successful sports person then you could pick better places
to explore your potential than Scotland. I am fiercely patriotic, but
throughout my career it has been an undoubted drawback trying to succeed in
Scotland.
The basic problem is a fundamental lack of understanding of what it takes to
reach the top in international sport. It has become a cliche but we as a nation
are too eager to chop the feet from under our heroes and heroines when they do
not fulfil expectation - which in the main is media led.
It never ceases to amaze me that so many top sports persons cite intense media
pressure as a major problem, yet the media always shouts ``humbug!'' and does
its impression of an ostrich, sticking its head in the sand. It is time for
pundits to assume a certain responsibility and look at a brighter side to
sport. This does not mean they cannot report the news, but if they could try to
emphasise the positive rather than negative opinions, it would do us all a
favour. Remember that in reporting sports news most journalists are giving an
opinion based around facts. Sports news is not black and white.
As a nation we are all too willing to participate in the country's successes,
and rightly so, but we are less willing to help sports people achieve their
goals. Sport in Scotland is grossly underfunded and most success is achieved
despite the system. Everyone has to earn a living and being an international
competitor can be a definite hindrance when looking for employment.
When I got my first permanent job I refrained from telling my prospective
employers that I ran for Scotland. In previous interviews there was a
consistent view that athletics would detract from my ability to do the job.
Consequently I spent most of the interview trying to persuade them that being
an internationalist showed a high degree of commitment and self-discipline, but
to no avail. Yet as soon as I omitted my sporting achievements I landed a job
with one of the world's biggest chemical firms.
However, attitudes soon changed. I used to train in my 44-minute lunch break,
and my boss never failed to get a dig in: ``You may run for Scotland but don't
forget where your bread and butter comes from.'' This happened every day.
Eventually, just after helping Britain win the European Championships 4x400
metres relay title I was informed that much as the company applauded my
achievements, I must choose between athletics and my career. I chose my sport
and left.
The above experience is by no means isolated, as I know from talking to many
other sports people. Little wonder that overall we are falling further behind
the rest of the world.
We still produce as much talent as ever, but other countries have found better
ways of developing and supporting their talent. While we have maintained the
status quo, the world has developed facilities and back-up. They recognise the
importance of being seen as successful on the world stage.
Cast your mind forward to June 15, 1996, when Scotland play England in Euro
'96. If Scotland win, the nation's workforce will be delirious, and production
will benefit. But if the Auld Enemy get lucky, employers may as well give them
the month off.
It is all about attitude. Most sport governing bodies cannot deal with their
top personalities. It seems inevitable that the better one gets, the more
alienated one becomes from officialdom. My governing body does not know how to
deal with top athletes. As a consequence there is little dialogue, which is a
shame, because the principal asset of any sport is its competitors. The
athletics hierarchy has become unapproachable and has little understanding of
the needs of the people they are supposed to represent. This is a sad fact in
many sports.
Scotland has a great sporting tradition but if we want it maintained we have to
change our attitude. To persuade our children to participate in sport, parents
must drag themselves from EastEnders and take their sons and daughters to
whatever sport captures their imagination. They must also maintain an interest
in what their children do rather than treat sports clubs as a creche - take an
active interest.
Government, Central and local, must help foster a climate in which the
community can capitalise on the assets of Scotland's many great sports men and
women - and the media should help the nation revel in our successes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hampden may become a monument to neglect Coaching the priority, not a national stadium</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jim Traynor, Chief sports writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766176</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF YOU were one of the in-crowd it was a wonderful day. There was a bout of
preening and back-slapping after the recent announcement that Hampden is to
receive #23m from the Millennium Commission towards the cost of transforming
the national stadium into a facility for the new age. How wonderful.
It is claimed the old ground, a large part of which has already been rebuilt,
will be the finest sports arena in Europe when completed in 1998.
Those who have campaigned for Hampden's survival are entitled to be pleased,
misguided though they are, and undoubtedly they believe they have saved
something of a small nation's heritage. Bah, and humbug as well.
The desire to save Hampden at a cost of tens of millions was fuelled in part by
the idiotic and romantic notion that Scotland's international footballers could
play only inside a huge bowl gouged out of the Mount Florida landscape. If
that's true only God and not Craig Brown can help us when we go to England next
summer for the European Championship finals.
It is always nice to be charitable and I do try, especially at this time of the
year when we should all show a little understanding and work from compassion.
However, it is no more than the content of a Christmas pie - that is, a dollop
of mince - to believe this country needs a national football ground. Scotland
doesn't need a national stadium. What it does need is a rechannelling of
finances into the development of the game.
Nice, shiny stadia look smart, but in football terms they can reflect a false
economy in that the standard of play within these impressive structures whose
banks of stands reach into the skies can be poverty stricken. The
recommendations contained within the Taylor Report forced issues and compelled
clubs to accelerate reconstruction plans, and in many cases confront the
problem for the first time, but we must be careful always to remain in touch
with the priority. Continuous improvement is the only game.
How depressing it would be if we find ourselves in possession of a collection
of splendid grounds which tower above communities as little more than monuments
to our ignorance and neglect.
Many within football digested Fergus McCann's Arena Column in these pages the
other day and reacted in typical fashion. They protested: ``Get him, he's only
five minutes in the game and he's telling us what we need. What does he know
about the Scottish game?''
The Celtic chairmman has managed to put his foot in it a few times since he
took over, but you don't have to be steeped in tradition to realise when
something is turning rotten. You don't have to have had a family connection
with some lowly club which never has and never will go anywhere in the business
to realise somewhere along the line we all were taken down the wrong road.
Football's administration often can state their cases eloquently and forcibly
and in general the country tends to go along with them, but the establishment
are not always correct and we shouldn't always believe something is worthwhile
or necessary because they say so. They are capable of getting it wrong and they
also have been guilty of acting slowly. For years they behaved like ostriches
unwilling to tackle problems which were obvious to many of the people who hand
over their money at the turnstiles.
Hampden is a mistake. It was never a priority in a small country in which clubs
were willing to redevelop their own facilities.
Thought, and all available money, should have been directed towards recruitment
and coaching schemes because nothing is more important in football than an
ability to play. Without good players the game's importance will dwindle and
supporters will pay anywhere to watch class acts.
Of course, the fans cannot be crammed into dilapidated facilities, but they
don't need state-of-the-art accommodation. In an ideal world, one in which
Scottish football was awash with wealth, yes, but not in reality which is a
life of shortages.
No-one is naive enough to think the #23m handed over from the National Lottery
- the single largest payment from that source made in Scotland - would still
have found its way across the Border without the work and effort of the
National Stadium Committee, the SFA, and Queen's Park and, of course, Hampden
as the fulcrum, but millions of football's money have been spent on this one
ground. That is unacceptable and arguments that the SFA are trying to look
ahead and provide what they believe FIFA will want from any country which
applies to host major games and competitions are fatuous.
It is this kind of logic which merely strengthens the notion that we have an
administration which is more concerned with their own image and ability to
lobby in corridors of power rather than the game itself. I would rather see our
players capable of competing with Europe's strong nations than watch others
play finals in our grounds.
Also, can anyone tell me why a quaint little amateur club which occupies a
place in the lower reaches of the Scottish game be owners and the home side of
Hampden Park. They own the 33 acres and all assets and buildings on them, but
Scottish football has subsidised the stadium for almost a century. That cannot
be correct.
That Queen's Park should own the lot, even though they don't make a profit and
money is ploughed back into the game, is incongruous. It is not a case of them
doing the game a favour, it is the sport which has done them the service and
that money supplied by the people, who are not all football fans, should be
used to make the place even more splendid for the Amateurs to play on is a
nonsense.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>IRG tunes into Q96</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766177</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MANCHESTER-based company yesterday announced the acquisition of Q96 FM and
immediately voiced hopes of increasing the Paisley radio station's audience
five-fold.
Independent Radio Group (IRG), which is listed on the Alternative Investment
Market, purchased a controlling stake in Q96 by buying out Peter Ross and his
associates. Mr Ross, chairman of Bowfield Country Club in Howwood,
Renfrewshire, was part of the consortium which founded Q96 three years ago.
IRG paid between #750,000 and #1m for 67.5% of the Paisley station's issued
share capital and as a result has 74.1% of the voting rights.
The group was set up by the three former executive directors of Trans World
Communications. Trans World ran eight radio stations in England and Wales,
including Piccadilly Key 103 in Manchester, but was sold to media group EMAP
last year.
Two months ago, IRG raised #10m through a placing on the Stock Exchange's
Alternative Investment Market for smaller and growing companies to buy nine
local radio stations with a ``popular music'' remit. Q96 is its first
acquisition and suited its other requirement that the target station must have
a ``poor audience'' which can be increased.
Although IRG chief executive Michael Connolly sees significant potential to
expand Q96's audience, he does not envisage a war with Scottish Radio Holdings'
Radio Clyde because he believes it has a different audience.
He said: ``Clyde isn't a target of ours.''
Q96 has a defined marketing area of 758,000 ``adults'', aged 15 and above, in
Paisley and the surrounding districts.
Mr Connolly said of Q96: ``Only 6% of the population listen to them. Within
Trans World, we would have expected in FM to do 30%.
``Q96 was launched in the mists of the recession. We think, with our experience
and the resources we have got, that we will be able to build that from 6%
upwards.''
The ``friendly'' takeover was welcomed by Harry McNab, the Q96 chairman who led
the founding consortium.
He said: ``The (Q96) board was unanimous. We know they have the resources and
know-how to develop, which we weren't able to do previously because of lack of
capital.
``We are in a crowded market and we have cash-rich and established competition.
Now we are going to have the resources available.''
Newspaper group Trinity Holdings has a 20% stake in IRG. The remainder is owned
by institutional investors, including Scottish Amicable, Scottish Mutual,
merchant bank Robert Fleming, Friends Provident and Gartmore.
IRG was established by Mr Connolly, Anthony Dewhurst and Neil Jones, who were
behind Key 103 and Piccadilly Gold, Preston-based Red Rose Rock and Red Rose
Gold, Cardiff-based Red Dragon FM and Touch AM, and Leeds-based Radio Aire FM
and Magic 828 in their former Trans World Communications' days.
It plans to improve Q96's programming and then pump money into marketing, in
the hope it can boost advertising revenues on the back of increased audience
figures.
</TEXT>
