<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Geordie who won hearts of the Irish `Big Jack' restored a nation's pride</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766178</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I could not play, but I was bloody good at stopping the other buggers playing
against us
JACK CHARLTON
WITH the dignity expected of Jack Charlton, the amiable big Geordie decided
yesterday to end his nine-and-a-half-year love affair with the the Republic of
Ireland.
He missed out on his last football ambition, taking the Republic to his native
England for the finals of the European Championship, but history will surely
record the amazing football revolution he started in the Republic.
The Irish people took the raw-boned, irascible ``Big Jack'' to their hearts
after he guided the team to two World Cup finals and one European Championships
final, and in the process restoring a nation's sporting pride.
His uncompromising methods and tactics did not always please the purist's eye,
but they were mightily effective and invariably embarrassing to rivals who
considered themselves much more sophisticated.
Charlton's edge was in persuading good players to perform simple tasks with
dedicated diligence. Put simply, they stopped the opposition playing and
imposed their own will with rugged endeavour and single-minded attention to
detail.
But recently, and quite suddenly, other sides seem to have found the answer to
Charlton's tactics, or was it just that Charlton's workhorses had no more left
to give? Either way, he admitted the game had changed and although he belatedly
tried to change with it, events have shown change is not really in his nature.
New instructions about patience and counter-attacking ploys only seemed to
confuse players who had revelled in Charlton's up-and-at-'em doctrine.
The brave new world of possession football was never meant for Charlton, a
safety-first centre half who would sooner put the ball in row X rather than
risk being robbed near his own penalty box.
As a player, he was always overshadowed by ``wor kid,'' younger brother Bobby,
a football genius with an explosive shot for Manchester United and England,
although he was still good enough to collect a World Cup winner's medal
alongside Bobby in Sir Alf Ramsey's celebrated team of 1966.
While Bobby was the epitome of the English sporting gentleman, blessed with
style and grace, Jack was the kind of rough, tough defender everyone wanted in
their side.
``I could not play, but I was bloody good at stopping the other buggers playing
against us,'' he once said.
He went on to enjoy only limited success as a club manaager at Middlesbrough,
Sheffield Wednesday, and Newcastle. But his impact on the international arena,
after England snubbed his application to succeed Don Revie in the national job,
gave Republic of Ireland fans pride in their team and, ultimately, a high
expectation of continued success that was impossible to deliver.
Charlton built steadily for two years before victory over England in the
quarter-finals of the 1988 European Championships in Germany kicked off a
golden era which shone even more brightly when the Republic reached the last
eight at the 1990 World Cup in Italy thanks to three draws and a
never-to-be-forgotten penalty shoot-out triumph over Romania.
They failed to qualify for the 1992 European Championships, but the fairy-tale
did not end there. Two years later, Charlton's jolly green army was on the
march to the World Cup finals in the United States, and this time they enjoyed
possibly their greatest single triumph, an opening match win over Italy, before
bowing out against the Dutch in the last 16.
Initial optimism that they had picked up the baton again after four splendid
wins and a draw at the start of the current European qualifying trail was
suddenly and startlingly exposed by the embarrassment of goalless frustration
in Liechtenstein, a team seemingly there just to make up the numbers.
Four defeats in five matches, culminating with the 2-0 play-off defeat against
Holland at Anfield last week, was something Charlton had never previously had
to handle in his 93-match reign. He could live with those and even the jibes of
the media, but not disdain from the southern Irish people.
They had, after all, made him a Freeman of Dublin, a city where, legend has it,
he once paid for something with a cheque that was never cashed but framed and
proudly displayed like a Renoir painting. In a reflective moment recently
before his departure, he said: ``I can take losing matches but never want to
lose the warmth of feeling the Irish people have given me. I do not want it to
come to the the point where I'm getting out with them disliking me.''
Thankfully, it has not reached that point. In the end, a predictable man has
followed the script, just as he did when quitting club management spells at
Ayresome Park, Hillsborough, and St James' Park before the natives on the
terraces became too restless in lean times.
For Jack Charlton is, and always was, a man of the people.
Officialdom, functions and media attention got on his nerves and he rarely
bothered to disguise the fact. But his shooting, hunting, and fishing image is
entirely accurate and he is never happier than when knee-deep in a stream with
rod in hand.
Publicly, his instinctive honesty often dropped him into traps with snipers
looking for flaws in an icon. In turn, he could be rude, charming,
bad-tempered, jolly, and belligerent.
Privately, given the chance, he would laugh and joke, swear and cuss with
practically anyone who wanted to sit down and talk about football over a pint
of Guinness.
Much has been made of the way he was snubbed by England when applying for the
manager's job a decade ago, but Charlton would probably not have lasted five
minutes in the politically-correct portals of the English FA.
With the FA of Ireland, his word was law, which was all right when things were
going well, as they almost always did.
Now the game has truly gone for Big Jack, but nobody should ever forget the
vast contribution he made to it.
q CHARLTON'S record with the Republic of Ireland: played 93, won 46, drawn 30,
lost 17, goals for 127, goals against 63 (not counting friendly v England,
February, 1995, abandoned after 28 minutes because of crowd trouble).
1935: Born John Charlton in Ashington, Northumberland on May 8, nephew of
famous Milburn family including `Wor' Jackie, the former Newcastle star.
1952: Signs professional forms for Leeds, his only club.
1964: Wins first medal as Leeds take second division title. Goes on to add
Fairs Cup (1968 and 71), League Cup ('68), League championship ('69), and FA
Cup ('72).
1965: Wins first of 35 England caps, against Scotland at Wembley.
1966: Claimed World Cup winner's medal as centre half in Alf Ramsey's side.
1967: Voted Footballer of the Year.
1970: Makes last appearance for England, against Czechoslovakia in Mexico World
Cup tie, having scored six international goals.
1973: Retires as player after club-record 629 league appearances (70 goals).
Becomes manager of second division Middlesbrough.
1974: Guides Middlesbrough to second division championship and is named Manager
of the Year ahead of old Leeds boss Don Revie. Awarded OBE.
1977: Takes charge of Sheffield Wednesday, then in third division.
1980: Guides Wednesday to promotion to division two.
1983: Parts company with Wednesday.
1984: After short spell back at Middlesbrough, appointed manager of Newcastle,
who had just won promotion to top flight. Upsets animal rights supporters by
fronting controversial TV programme on blood sports.
1985: Quits St James' Park on eve of new season in wake of fans' criticism of
tactics.
1986: Pips Bob Paisley by single vote in Football Association of Ireland ballot
to become Republic of Ireland manager, having been snubbed for England job.
Loses first match 1-0 at home to Wales.
1987: Leads Republic into European Championship qualifying competition which
takes them to finals in Germany a year later, but only after Gary Mackay's late
goal for Scotland stops Bulgaria going instead.
1988: Republic beat England 1-0 in first match of finals in Germany with Ray
Houghton scoring, then draw 1-1 with Russia before bowing out after 1-0 defeat
by Holland in final group game.
1989: Leads successful World Cup qualification campaign.
1990: Republic draw with England, Egypt and Holland before beating Romania in
penalty shoot-out to reach World Cup quarter-finals. Beaten 1-0 by Italy, but
return to massive celebrations in Dublin.
1991: Calls England counterpart Graham Taylor ``a lucky sod'' as England pip
Republic for a place in the European Championship finals after both finish the
qualifying competition unbeaten.
1993: Steers Republic to World Cup finals again, a 1-1 draw against Northern
Ireland in Belfast finally earning the passage to America.
1994: Afforded rare honour of Freeman of Dublin as Republic clinch first win in
World Cup finals, beating Italy 1-0. But things go sour as Charlton is fined
and censured by FIFA after bust-up with linesman in 2-1 defeat by Mexico.
Reach second round by drawing 0-0 with Norway but then lose to Holland.
1995: Republic make solid start to European Championship qualifying campaign
with runaway wins against Latvia, Liechtenstein, Northern Ireland and Portugal.
But hopes are hit by humiliating draw in Liechtenstein and successive defeats
by Austria and Portugal. Lose European Championship play-off against Holland at
Anfield and eight days later he announces his resignation.
</TEXT>
