<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Super charge to pep up the Merc</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ross Finlay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<FLAG>motoring</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766180</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MERCEDES tends to lose the place a little when what it does ceases to be
engineering-led, writes ROSS FINLAY. Engineering is the Stuttgart company's
real area of expertise, and when it returns to a line of technical development
abandoned something like 60 years ago, it is time to sit up and take notice.
This is what has happened with the new C230 Kompressor range, Kompressor being
the German for supercharger. Mercedes used supercharging in racing,
sports-racing and massive touring cars in the Twenties and Thirties, but gave
it up for production cars even while its grand prix cars were obliterating all
opposition towards the end of that period.
Mercedes is heading for a record UK sales year, expecting to have delivered
32,500 cars by the end of this month. One curious feature is that the
performance-modified AMG models have noticeably higher sales in Scotland than
in the UK as a whole, which suggests that the supercharged cars will be of
particular interest here.
Although turbocharging is currently more popular, it and supercharging have
exactly the same purpose. An internal combustion engine works better the more
air that can be crammed into it, especially high-density cold air, which is why
the Mercedes also has an intercooler. Not just air on its own, of course, but
the air/fuel mixture which maintains the combustion process.
When going back to forced induction petrol engines, Mercedes ignored
turbochargers, because these exhaust-gas driven machines have an inevitable,
however slight, turbo lag. The belt-driven supercharger makes for better
throttle response, and it is ``with'' the engine all the way, helping
acceleration from low revs, whereas a turbo usually wafts in with useful boost
perhaps a third or halfway up the engine's rev range.
The C230 Kompressor comes at prices from #25,300 for the Classic and Esprit
models, via #28,000 for the Elegance to #28,400 for the lowered-suspension
Sport. I would happily trade the Sport's firmer handling for the better ride
quality of the Elegance. And the interior appearance of the Elegance was a
reminder that, although I am no great admirer of the C-class fascia, Mercedes
has at last decided to style in its walnut trim, rather than just slap it on as
a token luxury item.
Mercedes is keen to compare the 193bhp 2.3-litre four-cylinder Kompressor
engine with the 2.8-litre six-cylinder unblown C280 which peaks at the same
figure. The Kompressor's on-road performance, with power sweeping in from low
engine revs, is formidable. It will accelerate to 60mph in just over eight
seconds, provide an autobahn maximum above 140mph, and give instant access to
tremendous reserves of torque.
But the car is completely untemperamental, easing down to pottering speeds
without any sign of being muscle-bound. On light load, the supercharger
disengages. And, since a forced induction engine is a more efficient engine,
both fuel economy and exhaust emissions benefit.
The Kompressor is far more economical than the C280. It will put up fuel
returns like 46mpg at 56mph, 36 at 75 and 25mpg on the urban cycle. Or 34mpg on
the new Euromix calculations. Oddly enough, until next August, when the new
Mercedes five-speed electronically controlled automatic transmission becomes
available, all Kompressors sold here will have manual gearboxes, despite the
known preference of UK customers for easy changing.
Old-style superchargers howled or whined. Some modern types retain those noise
effects. Mercedes says it has done its best to cut the noise levels right down,
but the cars available during the Scottish test session seemed to be rather
variable.
A mechanically-driven supercharger will never be entirely silent. To me, part
of the appeal in driving a supercharged car is being aware of, but not
disturbed by, the blower at work.
I hardly noticed, from the sound effects, that the Sport I tried was
supercharged at all. In the Elegance the rising hum during hard acceleration,
and the background sigh which accompanied a release of the throttle, were
enjoyable. On the other hand, one colleague insisted that a third car's blower
was definitely rattly under full acceleration.
This is something which will have to be sorted out, and may well be on the
showroom cars. But the C230 Kompressor is generally a most impressive car. If
supercharging can boost performance while retaining a crisp throttle action,
increase economy and reduce emissions as this Mercedes demonstrates, the
response to its reappearance in executive-class cars must be welcome back!
</TEXT>
