<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Defensive moves</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766182</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUTCH international defender Johan de Kock gave what local observers described
as a ``solid performance'' in Breda on Wednesday as Roda drew 0-0 with NAC, a
game watched by Celtic manager Tommy Burns.
The 31-year-old de Kock, who has also attracted the interest of Graeme Souness
in his role as manager of Turkish side Galatasaray, coped well with most of
what the home team could conjure up in an attacking sense.
However, there appears to be a strong possibility, acording to Dutch sources,
that a much younger man at a much more attractive price could be a serious
contender for any Celtic move.
The 22-year-old centre half of NAC, Dick van Burik, who was injured and unable
to play on Wednesday, has also been watched by the Parkhead club and has been
impressive.
Van Burick is a graduate of the Ajax school and, although the Amsterdam club
let him go for #150,000 after he had spent a year on loan to Breda, his form
has been such that the Ajax training has reputedly not been wasted.
A former Dutch youth cap, van Burik suffered a slight hamstring injury last
week when he was watched by Celtic but, as his team will not play again until
after the New Year, will have plenty of time to recover.
The former team-mate of Pierre van Hooydonk is priced at #350,000 as against
the #1.6m for the very much more experienced de Kock.
q NOTTINGHAM Forest manager Frank Clark last night insisted justice had been
done after Liverpool striker Stan Collymore's bid to win a #400,000-plus claim
against his former club was thrown out by Premier League officials.
Collymore maintained he was entitled to 5% of the British record #8.5m fee when
he left Forest during the summer, declaring the payment was due because he had
not requested a transfer.
But an FA Premier League board yesterday announced they had not been
``persuaded'' by Collymore's version of events and that Forest were therefore
not obliged to pay up.
Forest have, however, been instructed to pay an outstanding signing-on fee of
#150,000, agreed when Collymore moved to the City Ground from Southend for
#2.2m in 1993.
It was a decision Clark feels fully vindicated Forest's refusal to bow to
Collymore's demands, with the midlands club insisting the striker had
engineered his transfer, even though a formal request was never put in writing.
The Premier League board said they were ``not persuaded Mr Collymore was sold
at the club's request, which was the requirement to trigger the 5% of any
transfer fee under the terms of the player's contract with Nottingham Forest.''
</TEXT>
