<HEADLINE>BT and Oftel at war</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766183</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BATTLE was joined yesterday between BT and its regulator Oftel as the latter
unveiled details of its plan to assume a broader approach to combating
anti-competitive behaviour.
Rejecting what some took to be a more conciliatory move by Oftel's
director-general Don Cruickshank when he welcomed BT's decision to set up a
compliance department, BT declared that any extension to his powers should be a
matter for the Government and Parliament.
``The new powers which the director-general proposes to take for himself would
give him virtually unchallengeable power to decide that anything done in the
British telecommunications industry was anti-competitive,'' said Alan Rudge,
deputy managing director of BT.
Mr Cruickshank said he could not see why BT should object in principle to his
plan as it was less broad than a similar condition in its licence that BT had
already accepted in respect of its Concert international telecoms operation.
Oftel released a consultation paper on the proposed licence changes which also
include deleting many existing ones. BT objected that it would have no right of
appeal against Oftel's decisions.
Mr Butler was particularly concerned that the new rules would largely determine
whether BT would be allowed to reduce prices on certain services or introduce
new ones. For example, BT would be required to warn rival operators of planned
new services ``sufficiently far in advance to enable them to respond with their
own offering''.
If agreement cannot be reached between Oftel and BT the matter will go to the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission for a definitive ruling, which would probably
take the best part of 1996 to be forthcoming.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000103</DOCID>
