<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<FLAG>Sports digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974766184</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Olympics
RUPERT Murdoch's News Corporation has intensified efforts to add the Sydney
2000 Olympic Games to their sporting portfolio by forming an alliance with the
organisers to win European television rights, according to Australia's leading
financial newspaper.
``The innovative deal involves a bid by a News-led consortium for European
rights to both the Sydney Games and the Winter 2002 Games in Salt Lake City in
the US,'' said a report in the Australian Financial Review.
``The move is seen by media observers as an aggressive attempt to wrest control
of Olympics coverage from the powerful European Broadcasting Union, which
represents national broadcasters across Europe.''
News Corporation are behind rugby league's new Super League, the European arm
of which starts in March.
OLYMPIC doubles champion Boris Becker yesterday announced he won't defend his
title in Atlanta next year. ``I have personal reasons,'' Becker told said. The
three-times Wimbledon champion, 28 today, teamed up with compatriot Michael
Stich to win gold in Barcelona in 1992.
``With Wimbledon and the US Open, I would be traveling eight weeks in a row. I
can't do that,'' added Becker, who is ranked fourth in the world.
Boxing
LONDON-based promoter Frank Warren confirmed last night that Scotland's Drew
Docherty will challenge Daniel Jiminez of Puerto Rico for his World Boxing
Organisation bantamweight crown on January 20 in Mansfield.
This will be the 30-year-old British champion's second bid to land a world
title, having lasted only four rounds against former holder Alfred `Cobra'
Kotey of Ghana in February.
Football
BRAZIL'S World Cup striker Bebeto gave John Toshack a hat trick Christmas
present as Deportivo of La Coruna humbled Spanish champions Real Madrid 3-0 in
the storm-tossed north-west port city last night. The win kept Toshack's club
in the hunt for the title but left Real trailing in mid-table.
Tennis
DEFENDING champion Michele Mair was beaten 6-3, 6-2 by British No.11 Claire
Taylor in yesterday's semi-final of the British Women's Tennis Association
Christmas Tournament at Queen's Club. Russian Julia Lutrova went on to clinch
the title with a 6-3, 6-3 victory over Taylor in the final.
Speedway
BERWICK Bandits promoter Mike Hope has been banned from Berrington stadium by
landlord Ian Fraser following a dispute over the removal of property. Fraser
had threatened a complete lockout, but at a meeting with representatives of the
supporters' club he has agreed to allow them to remove specified items in
preparation for their proposed move to Shielfield Park.
Squash
SCOTLAND'S Peter Nicol, the No.1 seed, has been drawn to meet Hadrian Stiff
(Devon) in the first round of the QM British National championships in
Birmingham from January 9 to 15. Nicol, who is expected to become the first
Scottish winner, is due to meet Simon Parke in the semi-finals, and another of
England's world championship winning team, Del Harris, in the final.
In the women's event, Scottish champion Senga Macfie is a 5/8 seed and has
drawn Carol Page (Cambridgeshire) in the first round.
Volleyball
PAISLEY Trailblazers have been drawn away to Balerno NUVOC in the second round
of the Royal Bank Scottish Men's Plate. Draw:
Telford SP101 v DV Phoenix, 3rd Kilmarnock or 2nd Jets v 3rd Bellshill
Cardinals, Balerno NUVOC v Paisley Trailblazers, MCT Brannock v Finnegans Wake,
2nd Pentland NUVOC v Grange. Ties to be played on Januray 14.
Curling
Summit Centre. Brunton Miller Trophy - I Hamilton 11, P Orr 5.
Scotia Ladies - M Russell 7, V Browning 4; S Robson 5, E Semple 4; S Fleming
11, A Deacon 5; N Steven 12, L Gow 3; R Paton 11, E Harden 4; B Young 7, R
Meyer 5.
Ice hockey
STRUGGLING Murrayfield Royals yesterday signed Finnish forward Olli Tarhonen
and he will make his debut tomorrow against Swindon Wildcats.
Athletics
CITY of Glasgow's Alison Murray-Jessee broke the Scottish national pole vault
record for the third time this year when competing in the KSM Challenge at El
Paso, Texas. The American-based athlete won with a vault of 3.32 metres,
bettering her own previous record of 3.00m set last July.
Law and District AC 5-mile road, at Carluke. 1, J Muir 27min 12sec; 2, A Ramage
28-00; 3, C Barber 30-53. Veteran - D McCarthur 31-46. Super veteran - T Ramage
33-01. Handicap - C Barber.
Hockey
A DOUBLE from Hounslow's Rob Thompson helped Britain beat hosts Egypt 3-1
yesterday in Cairo. Despite feeling unwell, the centre forward came on as a
substitute to transform the match, scoring within 30 seconds of his entrance
and later sealing victory by netting again.
Yesterday's defeat of the African Games silver medallists was much more
convincing than Wednesday's 2-0 success. Russell Garcia, player-coach at
Barcelona's Polo Club, struck for the second time in two days to put the
tourists ahead after nine minutes.
Egypt equalised after 15 minutes through Ibrahim Tawfik, but Thompson came on
six minutes later and deflected Chris Mayer's long corner into the roof of the
net. The clinching goal came from an inch-perfect pass by Thomson's namesake,
Nick.
Ski-ing
MARTINA Ertl of Germany, fastest in both legs, recorded her third World Cup win
of the season yesterday with a giant slalom success at Veysonnaz, Switzerland.
Ertl clocked an aggregate 2min 0.06sec for a 1.49sec victory over Italian
Sabina Panzanini.
Austrian Anita Wachter, second fastest on the first leg, lost time towards the
finish of the second run to come home third in 2-01.79. Her compatriot, overall
leader Alexandra Meissnitzer, finished sixth to retain the overall World Cup
lead with 488 points. Wachter improved to second from third overall with 439.
</TEXT>
