<HEADLINE>Getting back to the Roots of forced induction</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ross Finlay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<FLAG>motoring</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766186</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SUPERCHARGING has a long, zigzag history, writes Ross Finlay. The Roots-type
Eaton supercharger on the Mercedes C230 Kompressor works on a mechanical
principle established before there were any suitable vehicle engines to use it.
In the 1860s Francis Marion Roots and the fabulously-named Philander Highley
Roots from good old Cornersville, Indiana, patented a pump-cum-blower with two
rotating figure-of-eight shaped lobes. The Roots system could ``sook or blaw''
most fluids. It has remained the type name for this kind of action, although
the Roots brothers are sometimes confused with the founders of the Rootes Group
here.
Aero-engineers first realised the advantages of forced induction, especially at
higher altitudes where the air is thin. The American manufacturer Chadwick
pioneered supercharged car engines during 1908.
In 1922 Mercedes raced two supercharged sports cars in the Targa Florio, and a
year later the first blown formula car at Indianapolis. But Fiat scored the
first supercharged grand prix victory, in France that same season.
Mercedes entered the Le Mans 24-Hour Race in 1930 with a massive seven-litre
240bhp blown sports model. It could spin its wheels in any gear, and even the
great Rudi Caracciola was warned never to give it full power for more than 15
seconds at a time.
By the end of the decade, Mercedes grand prix cars were using two-stage Roots
superchargers, one blowing into the other, which blasted the mixture into the
engine at previously unheard-of pressures.
It was not all German expertise, however. During the Second World War the
Merlin aero-engine never changed its capacity or rev limit, but the power
output doubled from the original figure. Rolls-Royce was showing its mastery of
supercharger technology.
</TEXT>
