<HEADLINE>Top players ready to sign</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Derek Douglas</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766189</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Rugby Union expect to have the country's top 23 players under
contract by the weekend in a deal which will cost the union more than #500,000
and which will gross the players a potential #25,000 apiece.
Eventually, the union will have the 42 players in the full international and A
squads signed up, with details of the shadow squad deal yet to be worked out.
Details of the top team contract were revealed yesterday at a Murrayfield press
conference by SRU senior vice-president Fred McLeod who said it was the result
of detailed negotiations between the players, their representatives, and the
union.
``The contract, which Rob Wainwright, Craig Chalmers, and Scott Hastings as the
players' representatives have recommended to the other players, is extremely
fair and represents a sensible balance between what the union can afford and
the realities of the new age of professional rugby,'' he added.
Players have been asked to sign the contracts by tomorrow and the union do not
expect any dissenters. If a player does not sign then he will no longer be
considered a member of the squad.
The players each will receive a #5000 retainer plus #3000 apiece for each Five
Nations' match in which they appear. A #2500 fee will be paid retrospectively
to those who appeared in the game against Western Samoa last month.
There also will be bonuses ranging from #1100 to #5500 per individual depending
on Scotland's ranking at the close of the Five Nations' championship. The Scots
will be paid #1100 for finishing last. A separate contract will be negotiated
for the tour to New Zealand next summer.
Yesterday McLeod indicated that the SRU's preference had been for bonuses to be
dependent on individual match results. The players, however, have been against
that. ``That is where the SRU came from originally but it came down to a
negotiating situation,'' he said.
The #25,000 which the SRU is offering Scotland's internationalists is small
beer compared to the #100,000-plus which Antipodean stars can expect and falls
short of the #36,000 deal signed by England last week. However, it compares
favourably with the reported #20,000 - #24,000 available to players in Wales
and Ireland.
McLeod said that players would still be able to earn money from off-field
activities and he expected that there were some members of the Scotland squad
who would be able to make around #40,000 in total this season.
The SRU - which yesterday dismissed as ``lies'' some newspaper reports
suggesting that the contract banned players' wives and girlfriends from trips -
is still exploring additional means of raising the extra revenue required to
pay the new breed of professional players.
``In the short term the money is not available but we have a variety of
commercial opportunities available to us. We are not, though, as some reports
have suggested, in dire financial straits and we are still examining the
possibilities.''
McLeod seemed to indicate initially that European Cup cash might enter the
equation but then qualified that by saying that it would, indeed, go primarily
to the clubs who supplied players for European competition.
There was, he said, a limit to what they could do with Murrayfield ticket
prices and the clubs had already indicated that they did not want prices to
rise. The possibility of a sponsor's logo on the Scotland shirt, however,
remained a possibility.
``That will not be given away for a small sum, though. Any potential sponsor
would have to pay an appropriate amount and at the moment nobody has offered a
sum which is acceptable.
``However, Famous Grouse, as the team sponsor, have certain options which they
have a right to take up
Continued on Page 32
From Back Page
at the right price. It would be difficult to offer it to anybody else,'' said
McLeod.
One unfortunate player who will not figure in the new deal is the Currie hooker
Graham Ellis. He was scheduled to sit on the bench for the Western Samoan game
but was injured in training just a couple of days beforehand.
``The money has to go to players who were on the field or on the bench on the
day. Regrettably Graham Ellis is an unfortunate casualty through force of
circumstance,'' said McLeod.
Players who have been offered contracts are: Gary Armstrong (Jed-Forest), Paul
Burnell (London Scottish), Stewart Campbell (Dundee HS FP), Craig Chalmers
