<HEADLINE>Descending from summit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Charlie Woods</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766190</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Descending
from summit
Charlie Woods, chief executive of Scotland Europa, examines the second report
from the Competitiveness Advisory Group which was established by European
leaders at last December's summit in Essen
THIS month's summit in Madrid was dominated by major issues covering the
expansion of the EU into Eastern Europe, Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) and
next year's Inter Government Conference (IGC) to review the Maastricht Treaty
on European Union.
At the summit, leaders agreed on a name for the single currency (the Euro) and
reaffirmed the commitment that a single currency would be launched on January
1, 1999, between those countries that were ready and who had not opted out.
The summit also agreed to begin enlargement negotiations in early 1998,
although the precise details were a little vague. Agreement was also reached on
starting the IGC in Turin on March 29 next year.
Also on the summit agenda was the second report from       the Competitiveness
Advisory Group which was established by European leaders at last December's
summit in Essen. This group was given the remit to investigate the
competitiveness of European industry and to advise European leaders what they
could do to improve it, particularly in relation to the USA and Japan. The
group is chaired by former Italian Prime Minister Carlos Ciampi and its members
include David Simon, chairman of BP.
The Ciampi group report submitted to the Madrid summit makes interesting
reading and its recommendations are as fundamental to the peace and prosperity
of Europe as the other headline-grabbing issues at Madrid. The danger is that
it will not get the attention it deserves.
The report's main recommendation is that priority has to be given to improving
Europe's transport, power and telecoms infrastructure. This involves extending
the single market as quickly as possible to cover utilities, transport and
telecoms and ensuring that genuine European-wide competition exists in these
sectors.
The report sees greater competition as essential to boosting investment and
efficiency. Without this Europe's infrastructure is likely to act as a
constraint on the ability of companies in Europe to compete in the global
market place.
The completion of the single market still has some way to go. At the moment
full liberalisation of voice telephony is planned for 1998 and an opening up of
domestic airline routes to outside carriers is planned for 1997. However,
attempts to open up energy markets are on hold because of French reluctance to
act.
Further work is also required to ensure that even when a free market exists in
theory it also exists in practice. In some countries there are still many
elements of the single market that have already been agreed yet have still to
be implemented in full.
Denmark, with 96% of the legislation implemented is the best performer, while
Greece, with only 80% implemented, is the worst. Some areas of legislation are
also worse than others, eg only 51% of the public procurement legislation has
been implemented across the EU.
As well as freeing up markets, a competitive infrastructure also requires that
the necessary investment is made in the trans-European networks. These are the
key transport links across Europe that have been identified by the EU to speed
movement of goods and people throughout Europe and improve the functioning of
the single market. At the moment there are delays in agreeing funding for some
key projects which is holding up progress.
To improve competitiveness the Ciampi group report also identified the need for
improved links between new and developing businesses and sources of finance,
along with more effective schemes involving companies, teaching institutions
and unions to bring about a culture of lifelong learning and better equip
people for job mobility. They have already indicated that they will look at
skills issues further in their third report.
Practical measures which genuinely improve the functioning of the single
market, which provide Europe with a modern infrastructure, which help give
entrepreneurs the space and means to grow new businesses and which make the
most of the talents, skills and experience of Europe's citizens will have as
great an impact on the prosperity of Western Europen as many other issues under
discussion at the moment.
The competitive advantage from such measures will help European firms compete
with the best in the world. They will also give the EU the confidence to
further champion the removal of barriers to trade across the world. The
economic vitality they will engender will also give the EU the wherewithal to
more enthusiastically embrace the emerging democracies in eastern and central
Europe.
In a world dominated by what happens at the summit, the importance of the base
camp should not be overlooked.
</TEXT>
