<HEADLINE>To carry on opening is still the target set by Stewart</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766191</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALEC Stewart looks set to carry on opening for England after arguing his case
at the crease for four hours yesterday.
Vice-captain Stewart responded to speculation that he might be dropped down to
No.3 for next week's fourth Test by scoring an unbeaten 89 against the South
African Students at Pietermaritzburg.
``I'm not fussed where I bat but I'm not one for making a change for the sake
of it,'' he said after an innings containing a 6, twelve 4s plus plenty of care
and concentration.
Stewart was not prepared to take too many chances yesterday. When he wafted
outside off stump early on, his body language indicated real annoyance and no
one was more disappointed to see play called off soon after tea because of
torrential rain.
It seems as though new recruit Jason Gallian will find himself filling
England's ``jinxed'' No.3 spot at Port Elizabeth next week, despite having made
only three runs from that position yesterday.
Manager Ray Illingworth and captain Mike Atherton could promote either Robin
Smith or Graeme Hick, but appear reluctant to consider either option. Here,
Atherton outscored Stewart during a first-wicket stand of 86 before top-edging
an attempted sweep against fourth Test candidate Nicky Boje two balls after
completing a half-century.
Following Gallian's dismissal, Graham Thorpe - twice dropped at slip - shared a
stand of 84 with his Surrey team-mate until rain ended proceedings with England
186 for two in reply to the Students' 269 for eight declared.
