qAUSTRALIA were in record-breaking mood at the Sydney Cricket Ground yesterday
as they beat Sri Lanka by five wickets with two balls to spare in their World
Series match.
Michael Bevan hammered a boundary off the fourth ball of the final over to lift
the Australians to their third successive victory in the triangular tournament.
Chasing Sri Lanka's 50-over 255 for nine, Australia scored 257 for five, the
highest winning total for a side batting second in a one-day international on
the ground.
Australia captain Mark Taylor laid the foundations with a methodical 90 off 115
balls before being run out in the forty-first over.
Australia lead the competition with six points, four ahead of Sri Lanka, who
have played two games. West Indies have lost their opening three games.
</TEXT>
