<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Team that Jack built seeks new leader</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766192</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
REPUBLIC of Ireland football officials will embark today on what many in the
country consider an impossible task - replacing Jack Charlton as manager of the
national team.
The former England defender resigned as the Republic's manager yesterday,
ending a memorable reign spanning almost 10 years, and which took in two World
Cups.
Speculation over his successor - a talking point since the defeat by Holland in
a European Championship qualifying play-off eight days ago sparked strong
rumours that Charlton would quit - immediately went into overdrive.
Bookies' favourite Mick McCarthy said he was ``flattered'' at being linked with
the job, while first division Millwall confirmed they would give the Football
Association of Ireland permission to talk to their manager.
But the former Republic defender is just one name in a catalogue of reported
candidates, which also includes Blackburn director of football Kenny Dalglish,
Manchester United manager Alex Ferguson, his assistant Brian Kidd, Wimbledon's
Joe Kinnear, and former internationals Kevin Moran and Liam Brady.
The FAI would only comment on the man who led them to victory in 46 of his 93
games in charge - only 17 of which ended in defeat - and their praise was
lavish.
``Jack has steered our team to levels of success never before achieved,'' said
president Louis Kilcoyne. ``In doing this, he has helped to expand the game
into every corner of Ireland in a way which could hardly have been predicted 10
years ago.''
Charlton, who spoke to his bosses for 45 minutes before announcing his
decision, said: ``I have been walking around with a lump in my throat these
past two weeks. That lump has now gone. I am 60 now. It's time for someone
else. They have been a magnificent 10 years. Why spoil it all now?
``The country is in my blood now and I intend to spend a lot of time here in
the future among my friends. It was a dreadfully difficult decision to make,
but I felt it was in the best interest of the Irish team.''
Charlton's name will go down the history books. Republic midfielder Roy Keane
commented: ``I think everyone should give him a pat on the back because he has
done a fantastic job. Everbody knows that when Jack took the job nine years
ago, no-one had really heard of the Republic of Ireland as a footballing
nation, but now it is the No.1 sport in Ireland and obviously Jack and his team
are known all over the world.
Amid claims by supporters that the FAI had ousted Charlton, Kilcoyne confirmed:
``We will start our whole selection process within the next few days and hope
to have a manager appointed by the time we go to Liechtenstein for our World
Cup fixtures meeting in late January.
</TEXT>
