<HEADLINE>Scandinavians are well ahead</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Joseph Dillon</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766195</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN it comes to indoor hockey, the Scandinavian countries leave Britain
standing, particularly in the men's game.
They will be represented by Stockholm (Sweden) and Slagelse (Denmark) in the
finals in Vienna on February 16 to 18 of the European Club Championship, while
the Dundee side, Insights Menzieshill, will be the sole British representatives.
The Scottish champions have been placed in the stronger of the two groups, but
their coach, Harry Byres, at least will take some comfort from the order of
play.
The tournament organisers, WAC Vienna, see Menzieshill as the most likely
challengers in their group to last season's beaten finalists Pocztowiec with
the result the two teams will meet in the third and final series of group
matches.
This will give the Taysiders the chance to seal their place in the semi-finals
before they come up against the Poznan based Polish champions, as their two
other opponents, CD Terassa (Spain) and Bohemians Prague (Czech Republic), do
not appear to be in the same class as the Poles.
These two games will be played on the first of the three-day event with the
Terassa encounter likely to give them a perfect start to their campaign.
Unfortunately, the domestic season is not geared to Menzieshill's venture into
Europe and their quest for a medal. The league campaign is now over and they
have only a maximum of three cup-ties remaining.
The Taysiders, however, have arranged their own seven-team round-robin
tournament at the Dick McTaggart centre in Dundee on December 27 to 29, and
then, along with MIM, they will contest the DTZ Midlands international
invitation tournament at Kidderminster on January 6 and 7 to help them prepare
for the more demanding assignments that lie ahead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wolves bid #500,000 for Mikhailichenko</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766196</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RANGERS midfielder Alexei Mikhailichenko is set to join Wolverhampton Wanderers
in a #500,000 transfer deal. The clubs have agreed terms and it is now up to
the 31-year-old Ukrainian internationalist to decide his future.
Last night Wolves' new manager, Mark McGhee, said: ``Everything has been worked
out with Rangers. I want Alexei here, but at the moment I don't know when that
will happen. I may travel to Glasgow in the morning or I may wait and have him
down to look around Molineux next midweek.
``I don't want to rush things and throw him into the team for Saturday with no
preparation.
``He's the kind of player I need to turn this club round. I am sure he can do
that, especially as I am bringing in other players already.''
McGhee has taken Vinny Samways on loan from Everton and will finalise his
signing early in the new year, and last night he was agreeing a #1m deal for
Queen's Park Rangers midfielder Simon Osborne.
Mikhailichenko made only a handful of appearances for Rangers last season and
this year it has been the same story. His appearances have been few, although
he did play at Fir Park on Tuesday night in the 0-0 draw with Motherwell.
He joined Rangers four years ago from Sampdoria in a #2m deal. At that time he
was captain of the Russian national side and joined up to be alongside his
team-mate from Dynamo Kiev, Oleg Kuznetsov.
Now Mikhailichenko, always a favourite with the fans in spite of his infrequent
first-team appearances, is poised to leave. His contract at Ibrox ends in the
summer and this move by Wolves will suit the Ibrox club and should suit the
player, too.
Wolves are certain to move upwards under the guidance of McGhee and
Mikhailichenko can become part of that revival.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
