<HEADLINE>Lo Stregone's yuletide date with Jodami</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WHITE and GOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766197</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IMPROVING chaser Lo Stregone, a probable absentee from the Welsh National, is
set to test the mettle of Jodami on Boxing Day.
Trainer Tom Tate admitted yesterday the weather would play a part in the next
assignment for the nine-year-old, but at present his preferred option is to
stay close to home and tackle Wetherby's Rowland Meyrick Chase, where the
top-weight is 1993 Gold Cup hero Jodami.
``We definitely intend to run either at Wetherby or Chepstow, but who knows
what's going to happen as the weather forecast is poor,'' he said.
Unless top-weight Miinnehoma is a defector Lo Stregone will have to race from
out of the handicap in the Welsh National on Wednesday. ``We don't think that
he will be suited by a slogging match at Chepstow, and assuming both meetings
went ahead, the choice would be Wetherby, even though it looks a hot race,''
said Tate.
Lo Stregone appears to have progressed this season, judged on his defeat at
Wetherby last time of Unguided Missile, who has since gone on to land the
Betterware Cup at Ascot.
q FROST, which put paid to yesterday's scheduled cards at Uttoxeter and Kelso,
looks the main threat to Boxing Day's busy programme.
A spell of milder weather is in the offing today and tomorrow, but the clerks
of the 10 courses scheduled to race on Boxing Day will be keeping a keen eye on
conditions with the Met office predicting a spell of colder weather on
Christmas Eve and Christmas Day night.
Mark Kershaw, secretary at Ayr (Tuesday) and Edinburgh (Wednesday), gloomily
reported: ``We could not have raced at either course today because of frost. We
are just going to have to sit and wait until Sunday night before looking
again.''
q CONDITIONAL jockey Guy Lewis is to step into Diane Clay's recently hung up
riding boots and ride for Bill Clay.
Lewis, 21, who claims 3lb and has ridden eight winners this season, is
delighted that his agreement with Clay will allow him to continue his
association with Paul Nicholls and Milton Bradley.
He rode Viaggio to victory at Southwell on Tuesday, a result which both ended a
173-day drought for Clay and prompted the Stoke trainer to offer Lewis the
contract.
q JOCKEY David Bridgwater takes time off from his title tussle with Tony McCoy
today to get married. He and fiance Lucy Phelps-Brown will tie the knot in the
Cotswolds and spend their honeymoon and Christmas in Rome.
The couple were introduced three years ago by amateur jockey Alex
Charles-Jones, who is to be best man.
``It was a blind date really,'' said Lucy. ``Alex is a mutual friend and David
had told him he wanted to meet a girl who knew nothing about racing and would
like him for what he was.
``Alex put us together at a dinner party. My first thought was who was this
funny little man, but we really hit it off.
``I've ridden horses myself and done some eventing, but the only two names in
racing I knew were Lester Piggott and Willie Carson.
``Since going out with David I've had a real crash course in racing.''
</TEXT>
