<HEADLINE>Your cash in their hands</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Duncan Black</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>HCI Report</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766198</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n THE Public Accounts Committee expressed concern about Scottish Enterprise's
representatives on the HCI board.
It stated that it was surprised the board did not meet more frequently than
once every three or four months, and added that it was ``especially concerned''
that the board members appointed by Scottish Enterprise did not attend all of
these meetings.
While it was taking evidence, the committee heard that the first representative
was Mr John Laydon. He was Scottish Enterprise's HCI director for only a few
months and attended one meeting - in February, 1992, - before being given leave
of absence to join HCI as director of international marketing, a post he held
for less than a year before returning to Scottish Enterprise.
Mr Laydon, currently on secondment to the Scottish Financial Enterprise
organisation which promotes the interests of Scotland's financial community,
declined to comment on the report last night.
He was succeeded as Scottish Enterprise's HCI director by Mr Donald Patience.
Mr Patience, who died last month, was widely regarded as a brilliant operator
in the field of equity investment in his years at Scottish Enterprise and its
predecessor body, the Scottish Development Agency. He left Scottish Enterprise
in May, 1993, for various consultancy posts but continued to act as Scottish
Enterprise's nominee on the HCI board.
The committee said Mr Patience had attended only four HCI board meetings during
the 22 months between September 1992 and July 1994, but it was told in evidence
that all meetings, ``with the possible exception of three'', had been attended.
The committee asked Scottish Enterprise why Mr Laydon, after he had become
international marketing director, had not communicated the failures of the
international marketing effort to Mr Patience.
But the agency said it had its own director on the HCI board, ie Mr Patience,
and that marketing and other reports flowed through him to the agency.
Mr Crawford Beveridge, chief executive of Scottish Enterprise, told the
committee that he was satisfied that Mr Patience had represented the agency's
interests adequately and properly.
DUNCAN BLACK
</TEXT>
