<HEADLINE>Legacy of Ataturk faces challenge in Ankara polls</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766199</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BTURKEY goes to the polls on Christmas Eve in an election seen as crucial for
the country's future. For the first time in the 71-year history of the Turkish
Republic, a serious challenge to the legacy of Kemal Ataturk, the founder of
the state, is being mounted.
It comes from the Welfare Party, a pro-Islamic force intent on reversing the
secular and pro-Western course Turkey has been on since the era of the Ottoman
sultans ended after 1918.
In the 1920s, Turkey witnessed one of the great revolutions of the century,
which has proved more enduring than that attempted by Lenin in Russia. Ataturk
drove all foreign forces from Turkish soil and then made a radical break with
the Ottoman past and Islamic civilisation and culture.
Religious schools were abolished, the Arabic script was replaced by the Latin
alphabet, and women were emancipated as furious efforts were made to create a
modern state on the European model. Turkish nationalism became the new
ideology, with Ataturk himself as the father of the nation.
A colossal personality cult surrounds Ataturk, whose martial expression stares
down at Turks from statues and portraits throughout that sprawling land. He
undoubtedly saved the country from extinction but, for the first time, his
doctrine of Kemalism is being challenged openly by forces who argue that Turkey
can only move forward if it is in harmony with its religious roots.
The seeds of the Islamic revival were planted in the 1980s by Turgut Ozal who,
by the time of his death in 1993, was widely seen as the most important Turkish
leader since Ataturk.
He moved a state-run, centralised economy towards a market system, unleashing a
torrent of social change. Between 1981 and 1992 the economy grew at between 6%
and 8% (except in 1991, the year of the Gulf war), the highest rate in the West
except for Japan. A huge influx of peasants into the cities occurred so that
Istanbul and Ankara soon contained one-quarter of the population.
Ozal also seized the opportunities brought by the collapse of Soviet power to
turn Turkey into a regional power. The new states of former Soviet Central Asia
were encouraged to look to Turkey as a protector on account of shared culture
and language. Turkey also promoted economic links between the states bordering
the Black Sea and played a key role in the Gulf war.
But the economy was stretched by runaway inflation and one of the highest
external debts in the world. The chaotic boom left many social casualties and
huge infrastructural problems in cities whose populations doubled and then
trebled in the space of a decade.
Peasants tried to make sense of their lives in the strange big city by
increasingly turning to Islam. The Welfare Party, financed by Saudi Arabia and
committed to restoring Islamic law and rolling back secularism, captured their
loyalties.
In 1993, the secular middle-classes received a shock when it won local
elections in Istanbul and Ankara. But the lack of any credible alternative, as
much as its religious message, explains the success of radical Islam.
Personality disputes have split the centre-right while the radical left has
been shipwrecked by the fall of communism. Between 1993 and this summer, a
fragile coalition of left and right-of-centre parties was presided over by Mrs
Tansu Ciller.
In the macho world of Turkey, women enjoy surprising influence in professional
life and the elevation of Ciller was probably greeted with less surprise than
that of Mrs Thatcher here in the 1970s.
q Tom Gallacher is reader in peace studies, University of Bradford.
</TEXT>
