<HEADLINE>Son of transport union president travelled to robberies by train `Anorak Man' admits raids</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766200</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE son of a transport union leader travelled by train to rob banks and
building societies throughout the country, police said yesterday.
Matthew Loughlin - the son of Rail, Maritime, and Transport Union president Don
Loughlin - became known as The Anorak Man because he pulled the hood of his
coat over his face to hide his identity during a two-and-a-half-year robbery
spree.
Loughlin, 37, of Mount Street, Derby, was captured by transport policeman John
Dickinson, who recognised him from a security photograph taken during one raid,
as he stood next to him on a railway platform.
Loughlin's holdall was found to contain a replica gun and #1600 from a robbery
he had committed in Wakefield.
Yesterday, at Sheffield Crown Court, Loughlin admitted 11 robberies, one
attempted robbery, and one firearms offence. He also asked for four robberies
and an attempted robbery to be taken into consideration.
He denied a further nine charges, which were ordered to lie on the file.
Judge Alan Goldsack adjourned the case for reports until January 26, remanding
Loughlin in custody.
Police described Loughlin as a Mr Average, who they believe could have been
responsible for up to 84 offences, involving up to #100,000.
He confessed to robberies in Nottingham, Long Eaton, Tamworth, Sheffield,
Doncaster, Newark, Crewe, Grantham, and Wakefield, between July 1992 and
October 1994, which brought in #17,000.
After the hearing, Detective Inspector Chris Barnfather - who co-ordinated
Operation Trojan which involved 12 police forces hunting Loughlin - said the
former public schoolboy had turned to crime four months after losing his job as
a British Rail fitter.
``He was given #13,000 redundancy money and spent it very quickly. Effectively,
he went out to steal to maintain his lifestyle,'' Mr Barnfather claimed.
``If he got a good haul, we didn't get a robbery for a month. If it was a small
amount, we got another a couple of days later. It was his income.''
Mr Barnfather said that immediately after a robbery, Loughlin, who used the
money to buy cars, motorcycles, holidays, and presents for his girlfriend,
would go shopping.
On January 31, 1994, Loughlin raided the Midland Bank in Doncaster and the
Coventry Building Society in Sheffield, stealing #5855, and also tried to rob a
Sheffield branch of Midland Bank.
Loughlin - a Star Trek enthusiast - then returned to Derby and bought a
Vauxhall Cavalier for #5000.
The officers tracking The Anorak Man discovered that he had travelled around by
train when they found a left luggage locker he was using at Derby Central
Station which contained lots of used rail tickets.
Loughlin's parents, who are said to be ``very close'' to him, were in court
yesterday but refused to comment.
</TEXT>
