<HEADLINE>Clyde-based battle starts for Britannia</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS STARRS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766202</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BID is being made to bring the Royal yacht Britannia to Glasgow when the
vessel is decommissioned in 1997.
City architect Geoffrey Jarvis has applied to the Cabinet Office to sail the
yacht up the Clyde one last time and give it a permanent home in a dry dock
next to the former Garden Festival site.
Mr Jarvis believes his plan for Britannia would help boost tourism in the city.
He said: ``This would be a tourism Mecca.''
Clydebank District Council is one of more than a dozen other organisations
which have applied to the Cabinet Office to give Britannia a home.
Chief executive Jim McNally said two sites had been proposed as a location for
the vessel, one opposite the HCI hospital and another near Rothesay Dock, where
the ship was built.
He expressed doubts about the viability of the Glasgow bid for the yacht. ``I
am not a marine specialist but I would have thought it was extremely difficult
to organise because of the depth of the water.''
Britannia was built at Clydebank and launched in 1953. It is due to come out of
service in 1997, when the Government is also expected to announce if a
replacement is to be built.
A Cabinet Office spokesman declined to comment on individual applications for
the Britannia. He said: ``We have received between 12 and 20 bids and we are
expecting a decision in the new year.''
Mr Jarvis is a director of The Clyde Festival Gardens 1999 Ltd, which made an
unsuccessful bid for Millennium Fund money to give the derelict garden festival
land a facelift.
Site owner Glasgow Development Agency is also bidding for Millennium funding
for its own plans for a National Science Centre on the land.
Announcements on the latest round of Millennium fund projects are expected
today.
</TEXT>
