<HEADLINE>Pakistan leader vows to find killers. Car bomb blast claims 32 lives</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ISMAIL KHAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766203</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Peshawar, Thursday.   A CAR bomb exploded outside a department store in the
northwestern Pakistani city of Peshawar today, killing at least 32 people and
wounding 117, doctors and witnesses said.
Hospital doctors said they feared the death toll could rise as some of the
wounded were in critical condition.
There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the attack, described by
Prime Minister Benzir Bhutto as terrorism, and authorities said they did not
know who carried it out.
Provincial police chief Masood Shah said he suspected an Afghan group because
of a series of recent smaller blasts in the region for which he blamed Afghans.
Peshawar has a large population of Afghan refugees from the war that has raged
in neighbouring Afghanistan since 1979.
Police said the bomb went off in a busy street in Peshawar's Saddar Bazaar
district at 6.30pm when the area was crowded with shoppers ahead of the Muslim
weekend tomorrow.
Government officials said at least 27 people were killed but hospital doctors
said the toll had risen to 31 after recovery of more victims from the Wadood
Sons department store.
Bhutto denounced the bombing as terrorism and said in a statement that ``the
culprits will not go unpunished and every effort will be made to bring them to
book''.
The blast set several cars on fire and wrecked nearby shops.
``I cannot say right now who was responsible,'' Aftab Sherpao, Chief Minister
of North West Frontier Province, of which Peshawar is the capital, told
reporters at the scene. ``We will fully investigate.''
A senior police official said the blast appeared to have been caused by a 55lb
time bomb. ``This is the worst bomb here for a long time,'' said the official,
Ghulam Hussain.
A suicide car bomb wrecked the Egyptian embassy in the Pakistani capital
Islamabad on November 19, killing 16 people and wounding more than 60.
The Muslim militant group Jihad, one of three Egyptian organisations which
claimed responsibility for the embassy blast, warned Pakistan last week to stop
extraditing militants to Egypt.
``We warn the government of Pakistan that it will pay a heavy price if it
continues to hand over Islamists living on its territory,'' said a December 14
statement signed by the Vanguard of the Conquest in Egypt, a revival of the
Jihad group which assassinated President Anwar Sadat in 1981.
Egypt and Pakistan signed an extradition treaty in July 1994. Islamabad says it
has extradited 10 of the 11 people wanted by Cairo. The 11th is on the run.
There was no immediate evidence to link Jihad with today's blast.-Reuter
</TEXT>
