<HEADLINE>Your cash in their hands.  The curious saga of the funding of a private hospital is examined by Herald writers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGregor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>HCI Report</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766204</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The Scottish Office and Scottish Enterprise have been criticised for failing to
do their homework. Stephen McGregor reports
FEW of those concerned with the setting up of the controversial HCI hospital
project in Clydebank escape criticism in the damning report on the handling of
investment published yesterday by the powerful Commons public accounts
committee.
Starting with the confirmation that there has been an outright loss to the
taxpayer of #8.4m, it strongly criticises both the Scottish Office Industry
Department and Scottish Enterprise and states bluntly: ``We consider that all
concerned should have taken a tighter grip on this project.''
The committee, which monitors how public money is spent, conducted a lengthy
inquiry into the multi-million pound project, which went into receivership
after only four months.
On the positive side, the committee notes that following the sale of the
business to HCI Holdings, the hospital is continuing to function, that its new
backers have provided #20m, and that the department will release a further
#4.4m in Regional Selective Assistance when 400 jobs have been maintained for
at least three months.
It also notes that projections indicate the business will get close to
providing the 1800 jobs originally envisaged, and that the new owners are
prepared to give it ``some years'' to break into profitability, mainly in
overseas markets.
Elsewhere, however, the conclusions are overwhelmingly critical. The committee
makes clear that the majority of the #37m spent on the project was provided in
the form of Regional Selective Assistance and that the department did not
regard this as a loss because there now was a well-equipped hospital in being
which was providing jobs.
However, the committee states: ``We are nevertheless disturbed that so much
public money was spent in support of a project undertaken by a company which
went into receivership only months after the building had opened for business,
that there has been an outright loss to the taxpayer of #8.4m, and that the
hospital is operating at a level much below that envisaged when public funds
were committed.
``We consider the whole scheme should have been initiated on a less ambitious
scale if it were to attract public funds.''
The committee notes that only 761 people were treated in the hospital's first
four months, many from the National Health Service, and describes the
expectation that there would be a throughput of 5000 patients a year from the
private sector as ``wildly optimistic''.
It says there should have been analyses of the sensitivity of the project to
varying levels of market success and adds: ``Assumptions about patient numbers
are crucial to assessments of the viability of projects like these, and we are
concerned that neither of the two appraisals of this project carried out by
public-sector bodies addressed the hospital's market prospects.
``We consider the department placed too much reliance on assessments carried
out by others, who may have had differing reasons for investing in the project.
Given the gap between projected and actual patient numbers we question whether
the department carried out a sufficiently rigorous review of the appraisals of
others.''
The committee notes evidence from the Scottish Office Industry Department that
risk is involved with all Regional Selective Assistance, but it states that in
this case the risks were ``major''. HCI as a company had no experience of
running a hospital, let alone one that would depend for its success on a
little-tried patient referral system and which would operate novel prescribing
arrangements that would need to be validated.
The committee states: ``We consider the department's evaluation of the risks
was insufficiently thorough. In addition we are concerned to note that only
three of the 12 members of the Scottish Industry Development Advisory Board
positively supported the grant of RSA to this project.''
Pursuing the point on RSA, the committee notes that this was given to HCI in
part to compensate the company for its VAT liability on construction costs.
However, it says the company then managed to spread #10.4m of the liability
over 10 years and so far had avoided paying any of it. ``We consider it
unsatisfactory that the additional RSA was not similarly phased.''
The committee also expresses concern that #9.4m was spent on providing a site
for the hospital on land which was known to be heavily contaminated. ``We are
disturbed that it is not yet entirely clear of gas seepage and look to Scottish
Enterprise to conclude successfully their claim against the contractor
responsible.''
On the monitoring of HCI's operations, the committee says that in the light of
the increasingly serious problems of the HCI project it is surprised that its
board did not meet more often than every three or four months. It states: ``We
are especially concerned that the board member appointed by Scottish
Enterprise, and his successor, did not attend all of these meetings. As a
result Scottish Enterprise and the department were not kept fully in the
picture about the project's growing    difficulties.
``We are particularly disturbed that the nominee director failed to alert them
to HCI's worsening cash position until April 1994 when he had known about it
for some time. It is also unsatisfactory that the Scottish Enterprise and the
department were not sufficiently aware, until the hospital was coming on
stream, that there had been marketing shortcomings, notably in Greece and
Italy. ``As marketing was critical to the project's success and as the
department did not see the marketing reports available to Scottish Enterprise,
we regard this as a serious failing.
``We consider that all concerned should have taken a tighter grip on this
project and we note the department's acceptance that they need to deal better
with projects where the leadership is not clear.
``This is an important lesson for the future. We consider that it was for the
department to ensure that a nominee director was able to fulfil his duties as a
board member involved in the oversight of a large sum of public money, the
effectiveness of which was increasingly in question.''
In conclusion, the committee notes the department's view that they would
ultimately be judged by whether the project was successful, free-standing,
making money, and providing good patient care, and that the end of the decade
would probably be the right time to reach a judgment. It adds, however: ``We
consider that, in the meantime, they should set about implementing the lessons
we have drawn attention to.''
</TEXT>
