<HEADLINE>Fire chief cleared over woman officer's claims</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766205</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FIRE chief has been cleared of allegations involving a female firefighter and
is to return to his post.
Mr George Fraser, 54, the officer in charge of Duns Fire Station, in the
Borders, was cleared by a special tribunal of failing to deal effectively with
sexual harassment claims made by the station's first woman fire officer, Mrs
Sharon McKenzie, 23.
He was cleared of nine allegations, which also included accusations of neglect
of duty.
His lawyer, Ms Shona Simon, said: ``The majority of these charges were in fact
based on the allegations that he failed to exercise sufficient management
control rather than suggesting that he himself had been involved in any alleged
misconduct.''
Mr Fraser had also said he was willing to undergo counselling ordered by fire
chiefs for both him and Mrs McKenzie before returning to his job.
The chairman of the joint Lothian and Borders fire board, Councillor Bill Axon,
said both firefighters were free to return to their posts.
Mrs McKenzie has been on special leave from the brigade since the claims
emerged in September last year.
A second fireman, Mr Ronnie Burnett, 34, is reported to have been reprimanded
for using threatening behaviour, while charges against a third man, Mr Andrew
Burns, 33, have been dropped.
Mr Axon said the tribunal had concluded there was no case to answer on any
charge of a sexual nature.
It is the first case of sexual harrassment to be handled by the brigade, which
has nine women fire officers.
</TEXT>
