<HEADLINE>Pain of scrutiny for boys with lives beset by negative factors</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jennifer Cunningham</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>Feature</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766206</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The troubles ahead for the two princes
are assessed by Jennifer Cunningham
ALTHOUGH the Queen believes a swift divorce would put an end to some of the
problems caused by the unresolved separation of the Prince and Princess of
Wales, it is probably not be the best option for her grandsons.
There is rare agreement among psychologists that divorce is painful for
children whatever the circumstances which have led up to it.
``Divorce is not terrific news for these boys,'' confirmed Laura Galbraith,
co-ordinator of psychology services for children in Fife. Their first problem
is that they are boys. There has been a belated recognition of boys' greater
vulnerability. ``One of the things we do know is that boys tend to be more
affected than girls by their parents divorcing,'' she said.
Particular factors, however, can improve things. One is a very good
relationship with one parent or a good relationship with another adult, such as
a teacher or grandparent.
Despite the public aspects of this particular split, we don't know a lot about
the quality of the individual parent-child relationships but it is difficult to
see any of the three surviving grandparents stepping into the void.
Another negative factor is that although divorce is the final legal step in a
process already under way, there is no avoiding it being played out in public.
Being at boarding school could be an advantage or disadvantage. ``It may be
that the information does not come to them directly from their parents and it
may be difficult for them to check it with the people they are most emotionally
attached to, although there may be other protective factors,'' said Ms
Galbraith.
Princes William and Harry can expect support from their schoolfriends. Ms
Brenda Robson, a chartered psychologist specialising in child and family work
for the courts in cases where custody and access are disputed, is a school
counsellor in a boarding school. She runs groups there for children who are
going through the turmoil of parental divorce and finds that they will often
give each other tips about how to cope.
``It is very helpful for a child who is at the height of the emotional battle
to speak to a boy who went through it two years ago and to see that he has
managed to keep a relationship going with both parents,'' she said. She thinks
it is likely that 25% of the boys at the princes' schools will have experienced
divorce.
``Divorce is always a painful experience for children, even when the parents
are handling it in the most civilised manner. If the people happen to be well
known and in the public eye with a lot of acrimony going on in public, it is
particularly traumatic,'' said Margaret McAllister, a child psychologist in
Lothian region and secretary of the Scottish branch of the British
Psychological Society.
She suggests there may be some parallels, despite the different culture, with
the case of Macaulay Culkin's parents in the US, another high-profile example,
which Mrs McAllister describes as ``an upside down case where the child is the
gold mine''.
The boarding school life combined with the variety of houses at their disposal
will avoid the humiliation of a battle royal over custody and access but it
seems the luckless little princes will be fought over one way or another by the
adults.
Being scrupulously even-handed and avoiding criticism of the other parent is
enormously difficult, according to Laura Galbraith, who describes it as ``an
arena fraught with difficulty even when parents start out with good
intentions''.
</TEXT>
