<HEADLINE>A painful chord outside the Royal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766207</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE article concerning parking in Glasgow (December 9) struck a painful chord
with me. The day before, while visiting my daughter in the Royal Infirmary, I
received a ticket for parking in enclosed ground which is described as Stirling
Road, opposite the old hospital. I was only just in time to prevent my car
being impounded - others were not so lucky.
This area, partly used as a taxi-rank, allows free parking all down one side
except, according to a policeman, for a small part at the south end where there
is space for some four cars. There are double yellow lines at this point which
seem very old and would appear to be remnants of the former use of the road.
Within minutes of the arrival of the policeman, there were three transporters
there to remove these vehicles.
The point is, what has the removal of these cars got to do with ``keeping the
traffic flowing''? Why were these officers not in the city where their
employment might have been more useful?
David B Lee,
14 Amochrie Drive,
Paisley.
</TEXT>
