<HEADLINE>Clydebank shambles.  Embarrassed silence over HCI</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766208</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE conduct of the Scottish Office and of Scottish Enterprise in the affair of
the Health Care International hospital at Clydebank was nothing short of a
disgrace. There should be apologies, and full ones at that. What we have had
instead is embarrassed silence and dissimulation. Scottish Office Minister
George Kynoch was put up yesterday to provide some sort of early excuse for
what went wrong. Although Mr Kynoch is not personally culpable his response
was, to use one of his own words, a disappointment.
The report into the shambles by the Commons Public Accounts Committee would
have to be reviewed ``very carefully'', he said. That should be a painful
exercise, bearing in mind that the report points out that the Scottish Office
Industry Department's evaluation of the risks was insufficiently thorough; that
the board of this limping enterprise met only every three or four months; that
Scottish Enterprise's nominated board member and his successor did not attend
all of the meetings and that as a result the Scottish Office and Scott
There is no point in mincing words here. Mr Ian Lang must carry a heavy
responsibility for this affair, especially as he continued with protestations
of confidence when it was abundantly clear that HCI was a disaster in the
making. He might ponder the Public Accounts Committee's conclusion that there
should have been a tighter grip on the project. Ultimately, that was Mr Lang's
task: he failed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
