<HEADLINE>The Communists' credentials</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766209</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TYOUR editorial of December 19 on the Russian elections more than once
describes the victors as, in the same breath, ``the Communists and extreme
nationalists''. You also continue: ``The simple fact that the Government is
unpopular with the people, and that Russians have been able to register their
disapproval, is a sign that Russian democracy is working''.
The truth is more complex. It has been the Yeltsin Government that has pursued
a chauvinist war in Chechenya - with support from Zhirinovsky's Liberal
Democrats. It has been the Russian Communist Party that has consistently led
the mass opposition to it.
It was the Yeltsin Government that bombarded the old Parliament in 1993. It was
the Communist Party which defended it.
It was Yeltsin who seized virtual dictatorial powers for the Presidency after
the dispersal of the previous Parliament. It is the Communists who today call
for  the restoration of powers to the Duma and, no less important, to local
elected bodies.
If there is mass support for the Communist Party in Russia, it is not because
it somehow represents dark forces of reaction. On the contrary, it is because
people see the Communists as the one organised force that stands between them
and a semi-dictatorial regime enforcing the most rapacious of capitalist values
and practices.
The scale of support for the Russian Communists should encourage socialists and
democrats everywhere.
John Foster,
Secretary, Scottish Committee,Communist Party of Britain,
845 Govan Road,
Glasgow.
T
</TEXT>
