<HEADLINE>Holiday firms to use credit schemes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766210</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNDER a new scheme announced yesterday, travellers can complete payment of
their 1996 summer holidays months after they get back.
In an effort to boost the flagging holiday market, travel agent Lunn Poly is
launching an easy-to-pay plan.
From next Wednesday, the company is inviting holidaymakers to pay for their
summer 1996 breaks in up to four instalments. This means that a holiday booked
early next month need not be completely paid for until January 1997.
The instalment option is one of three being offered by Lunn Poly. The other two
are a 10% discount off summer 1996 brochure prices, or free insurance.
The company, and the rest of the travel industry, is hoping for a boost in
bookings in the vital post-Christmas period.
A lack of consumer confidence has caused bookings for summer 1996 to dip by as
much as 30% compared with this time last year.
Thomson, the UK's biggest holiday company, announced it was introducing a
``fluid pricing'' policy from next Wednesday that will mean reductions of up to
#100 per person off some holidays in the company's main summer 1996 brochures.
Early bookers will get discounts but those booking later will have to pay the
brochure price. Those who have already booked now-reduced holidays will still
get the discount
</TEXT>
