<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>What Diana wants defined</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766211</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE four things the Princess of Wales will want defined in the divorce
settlement are her status, her income, how her wish to be a Queen of Hearts can
be met, and her future relationship with her children.
The negotiations about her future role began in the wake of her Panorama
interview and are likely to continue for some while yet. Although they arenot
part of the divorce settlement as such, are complementary to it.
The Queen's wish that the pair divorce gives them fresh impetus because it is
vital for the princess, even though she was refusing yesterday to respond
immediately to the Queen's request, that they move smoothly to a conclusion.
If she is seen to be being simply obstinate, especially given the Prince of
Wales's decision to do as his mother wants and his announcement that he will
not be marrying again, her image will be damaged and for the princess image is
all.
Her status. This is important because she is the mother of a man born to be
king and, if royalty means anything in British society, the mother of the king
must have the right social position. However, her future title is important to
the princess because it is what makes the former Lady Diana Spencer,
paradoxical though it may seem, a somebody in her own right.
After their divorce, she will cease to be Princess of Wales but she will want
to retain the title of Her Royal Highness. The royal family are jealous of the
title, which is not bestowed lightly, as the Duchess of Windsor found to her
cost and the fury of her husband. In this instance, it would seem rash to deny
the princess the right to remain an HRH, so HRH, Princess Diana it will very
probably be.
Income. Prince Charles is very wealthy but he is not actually as cash rich as
he is land rich - the Duchy of Cornwall owns around 133,000 acres, mostly in
the South-west of England, as well as shops and office buildings. Its assets
are said to be worth more than #90m, and his annual income from the duchy is
estimated at more than #3m.
He has no claim on the duchy's capital, however, which is held in trust for
future Princes of Wales. His income from the duchy estates - he does not
receive any money from the Civil List - is used to finance his household and
the performance of his public duties, but that still leaves him with around #2m
income to which she could lay claim. Were it an ordinary rich man she was
divorcing, she would probably seek a third of his income, or about #600,000 a
year.
If allowed to continue to play a role in public life, she will need enough
money to support her own household. A clean-break settlement would probably
have to total around #15m to allow her that sort of income and there is no way
the prince can come up with that kind of money. The Queen, however, wants the
divorce for the good of the family and can be expected to help.
Her future role. Princess Diana's expressed wish to be a queen of hearts cannot
be set aside. She may not be able to play the diplomatic role that she appears
to aspire to, as her visit to Argentina last month suggested she does, but
there is no reason why she should not prove a successful ambassador for Britain
on trips on behalf of her favourite charities.
The Princess Royal manages this, although with less attendant self-publicity,
in her work for the Save the Children Fund and, given the proper advice, there
is no reason why a divorced Princess Diana should not be able to do the same.
However, proper advice is the important factor, which brings us back to the
composition of her household and her finances.
If she is to remain part of the royal family firm, she has to be provided with
the right professional support to do her job, which costs money. Giving enough
money in the settlement to fund the role from her own resources might be the
easiest solution, although it would leave her in control of her advisers, which
may not be in the overall interests of the monarchy.
Clearly, since she is a media star the like of whom the Windsors have never
known, it would be foolish to jettison her completely. At the same time, she
cannot be allowed to compete for public attention and affection with her former
husband, whom she has upstaged regularly.
Access to her children. This is unlikely to present a major problem since in
this respect the divorce is really no different from any others. They are
expected to divorce by consent and are both self confessed adulterers, so,
there being no guilty party, as parents they would expect to have equal rights
of access.
As both princes will be at school for most of the year, it is primarily a
question of where they spend their holidays and there need be no arguments
about that. They will be expected to attend the grisly royal house parties at
Balmoral and Sandringham, their birthright, which could mean not seeing their
mother at certain times of the year, but the assurances required on sharing
their children fairly she and Prince Charles will seek will be no different
from those in any other divorce by consent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Divorce request.  Queen's action simple common sense</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766212</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was a long time coming but, after enduring frustration and anger to a degree
which we can only guess at, the Queen has taken action to bring some sort of
order to her unruly family. Her request that Prince Charles and Princess Diana
move quickly to a divorce is simple common sense. As an attempt to deal cleanly
with a situation which has deteriorated shockingly it can be received with no
emotion other than relief. Prince Charles will probably share that feeling.
Whatever his fitness to be King it is clear that he ardently wants the
position. What other explanation could there be for his announcement that he
will not remarry? He is well aware that the Church of England would have no
problem with crowning a divorced King but would baulk at one who had married a
divorcee or who was involved in extra-marital relationships. This would appear
to suggest that we could have a celibate Prince of Wales, or at least a very
careful one.
Princess Diana is less likely to be pleased and is obviously not prepared to be
bounced into making a quick decision. She has said that she does not want a
divorce and by holding her hand on a decision she has managed to retain the
initiative in a tricky situation. Most probably, though, she will have to agree
to the Queen's request. At this point her hold on the situation, and quite
likely on a good deal of the extraordinary fascination felt for her by the
public, could begin to drain away. She will have to cope with this as best she
can, although in common decency the royal family should do their best to ensure
that she retains a meaningful role in public life.
Although it is sad to admit as much, the royal family in all of this reflects
the difficulties many in our society face in sustaining marriage. There are a
variety of reasons for this and it would be wrong to attempt a facile analysis.
Nevertheless it is impossible to contemplate the present situation without
recognising the strains it will put on the young princes. Their parents come
from families which were either broken or which did not appear to enjoy much
love. In these circumstances behaviour patterns can be established which are
repeated later and we can only hope that this is not so in their lives. For his
part, Prince Charles may be seeing a good deal of his sister, Princess Anne. If
he pays close attention he may learn much to his advantage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000132</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000132</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>How dream turned sour</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alison Daniels</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>HCI Report</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974766213</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Alison Daniels looks at the project that was plagued by problems from the start
CONTROVERSY and heated debated surrounded every aspect of the conception,
planning, and building of the glitzy Health Care International hospital on the
unglamorous site of an old steelworks in Clydebank.
Just six months after opening, the project had met with financial disaster.
HCI, part funded by #37m of public money, was in the hands of the receivers
amid recriminations over the waste of taxpayers' cash.
Four months of negotiations with potential buyers saw a number of cliffhangers
before the hospital was finally saved when a deal was struck with the Middle
Eastern-based Abu Dhabi Investment Company.
But rescue did not mean the end of controversy. This year the hospital has come
under fire over the treatment of NHS patients, occupancy rates, revelations
about #220,000 roof repairs, and the departure of over 25 staff.
Yesterday, HCI's current management kept quite, distancing itself from
pre-receivership problems and pointing only to a recently signed contract with
the Algerian Government to treat around 300 heart patients and the steady
stream of patients, mainly from the Middle East, seen since February.
The long-term goals articulated over the past few months in measured terms by
Abu Dhabi Investment's chairman, Mr Harab Ali Darmaki, contrast all too sharply
with the picture of a thriving international 260-bed centre of medical
excellence painted by HCI's American founders, Dr Raphael Levey and Dr Angelo
Eraklis, when they unveiled their ambitious scheme in 1987.
Speaking in Glasgow eight years ago the former Harvard surgeons expressed
surprise at the hostility vented by health unions and MPs but promised to forge
ahead with the five-star hospital designed to cater for the wealthy foreigners
from Europe, North Africa, and the Middle East if backed by the Government.
In October they got that backing when the then Scots Secretary, Malcolm
Rifkind, gave the official go-ahead for the hospital, attempting to soothe
misgivings over private health care with the promise of 4000 permanent jobs,
including 1800 at the hospital, for depressed Clydebank.
The decision met with almost universal condemnation. There were fears over a
drain on NHS staff, trained at public expense and now to be lured away into the
private sector, the impact on the health services in the Glasgow area, and,
ironically, in the private sector a concern over further competition.
As the debate raged on, practical problems had already arisen. Following
Rifkind's announcement it emerged that the proposed site was an asbestos dump,
prompting a public-safety row. The original Scottish Development Agency
estimate of #1m to clear the site became #5m. A further #3m was later added to
the SDA's bill by severe land engineering problems.
By the summer of 1989 the project had failed to secure the necessary private
financial backing amid rumours that the banks were reluctant to commit
themselves to the project. Months later, though, it was back on track after US
and British private investment was topped up with a Government offer of
Regional Selective Assistance totalling #22m.
Finally in March 1994 the state-of-the-art hospital, with its 21 operating
theatres, opened its doors to its first Middle Eastern patient. But trouble was
brewing. One of the hospital's leading surgeons, Dr Gerald Lawrie, returned to
America for ``personal reasons''. West Midlands Regional Health Authority
cancelled its contract. While the public debate centred over whether HCI could
and should be used to cut NHS waiting lists, behind the scenes the hospital was
already in dire financial straits.
By June, round the time of the official opening, HCI was asking its
international syndicate of banks for more cash to the tune of #15m. In
September the Royal Bank stepped in with loans to pay wages and keep the doors
open but within another two short months it was all over. HCI went into
receivership.
Salvation for the hospital's 350 staff came in February when the Abu Dhabi
Investment Company agreed to a #20m deal with the receivers, leasing the
hospital and its adjacent luxury hotel.
The American dream metamorphosed into a more modest Middle Eastern strategy of
long-term survival, concentrating on Middle Eastern and UK private markets as
well as NHS contracts.
The past 11 months have been a struggle. While the management, now headed by
the recently installed chief executive, Mike Hall, and a new development
manager, Douglas Trigg, has put occupancy rates at between 60 and 85%, the
actual number of beds occupied at any given time has fluctuated from between
about 20 and 60.
But against the backdrop of continuing bad publicity over public funding ADIC
has soldiered on to attract new patients, announcing the creation of around 100
new jobs, publicising a pioneering heart operation - on an NHS patient - and
last month finally clinching a deal with the Algerian Government under
negotiation since the summer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000133</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Drink-drive figures falling</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766214</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO men have been charged in Strathclyde with a drink-drive offence even though
they were not behind the wheel. Both were supervising a learner when police
stopped their vehicle.
Chief Inspector Jim Neill, head of Strathclyde Police traffic specialist
services, said: ``Some drivers may think they can get round the law by
arranging for a sober driver holding a provisional driving licence to pick them
up from the pub and allowing the learner to drive home under their so-called
supervision.
``However, drivers should be aware that there is no hiding place as far as
drinking alcohol and being in charge of a vehicle goes.
``There are other cases where this happens though it is unusual that we have
detected them. These people should realise that they are ultimately in charge
of the vehicle.''
According to figures released yesterday by the Association of Chief Police
Officers in Scotland (ACPOS), the number of people drinking and driving in
Scotland during the festive season is decreasing.
Offenders face three months in prison or up to a #2500 fine as well as an
obligatory 10-point penalty.
A total of 746 positive tests have been recorded from 56,762 drivers stopped
since the drink-driving campaign was launched on November 24.
That represents a total of 1.3% compared to 2.1% from almost half as many
drivers during the same period last year.
Mr Ian MacKinnon, secretary of the traffic standing committee of ACPOS and
assistant chief constable in Strathclyde, said: ``I am pleased that the
drink-driving figures are showing a general decrease but the fact that nearly
750 drivers in Scotland have been caught driving over the limit must remain a
cause for concern.
``All eight Scottish police forces will remain dedicated to rooting out the
people who are prepared to put their lives, and those of others, at risk by
driving with too much alcohol.''
He said police needed help from the public to catch drunk drivers.
In Strathclyde, 301 drivers have tested positive from a total of 38,874,
representing just 0.77% of the total compared to 1.67% for the same period last
year. Thirty-five people have refused to take a breath test.
Officers called the fall in positive tests as a ``heartening'' sign that the
anti-drink-drive message was getting through.
Chief Inspector Neill said: ``It seems that our campaign of high-profile
policing and the message to motorists not to drink and drive is getting through
to the public.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Festive greetings.   It's now too late to send cards</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766215</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOO late now. You should have thought about the Christmas cards weeks back and
today there isn't any point at all unless you don't mind the holly and the ivy
and the nativity and the scattering of silver tinsel over the pieces of
cardboard turning up a week after the Christmas festivities. You are simply too
late. Christmas cards were of a recent date really, made out of Victorian
scraps and a Germanic sensibility. Prince Albert and his Hanoverian entourage
invented it really. Prior to Prince Albert, Victoria's subjects were content to
spend Christmas feeding themselves to apoplexy if they were financially secure;
dying of starvation if they were not. It took a Saxe-Coburg to turn Christmas
into trees, Father Christmas, cards, and commercialism. Today Christmas cards
have two functions. One is to sting you with the notion that you haven't
bothered keeping in touch with old friends, best men, bridesmaids, aunties, and
the other you shouldn't care about. The other is to show off with bigger and
more expensive cards than people you despise and dislike. We have discovered in
the editorial department cards which come from the BBC and public relations
companies which would suggest that The Herald's writers and correspondents were
a combination of H L Menken and Mr Russell of the Times. In short we, as many
other recipients of Christmas cards are being horribly flattered.
We even have a writer of our own who eschews Christmas cards on the basis that
he doesn't like people, let alone Christmas. Yet even he sent off a few
desultory cards for this newpaper had a Christmas card of its own. It displays
a cheery Santa Claus, looking rather like the editor of this paper in fact.
Come to think of it, the editor is a trifle Germanic in appearance himself, and
horribly liberal at Christmas parties. But what the postal service is not is
liberal. You are too late for Christmas cards to arrive in time. But the
posties have spent - and never mind about the recent industrial dispute - a lot
of effort and time in getting these dods of card across to you, telling you how
many people you know and how many whose names you can't remember. We sympathise
with our colleague who never sends a card. But our sympathy goes out more to
those who have left it too late. New Year dawns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000135</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000135</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Govan and Kelvin</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766216</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HE intervention by George Galloway, MP, into the controversy surrounding the
Glasgow Govan Labour candidacy selection is as egregious as it was predictable.
While the democratic selection process in Govan resulted in the election by due
process of Mike Watson, MP, Mr Galloway faced the prospect of a similar process
in the new Kelvin constituency.
Despite the nomination of a challenger by party branches and affiliated
organisations, his acolytes denied Labour Party members a vote on the candidacy
and declared him elected.
The man who, in his present Hillhead constituency, was trounced in a members'
ballot, then bailed out by block votes, described this travesty as ``very
convincing''.
If anyone ``has no credibility and must not be allowed to stand'' it is the man
who simpered about the ``indefatigability'' of Saddam Hussein before the
smirking mass-murderer himself. Even Saddam Hussein's subjects got a ballot
paper, if only with one name on it. Kelvin Labour Party members didn't even get
a vote!
Mike Watson met his challenge and won by the rules. George Galloway ran away
and hid behind the same rules he now denounces. We need no lectures on
democracy from such a source, let alone crass and cynical demagoguery inflaming
spurious racial division. And Mohammed Sarwar needs this type of advocacy like
a hole in the head.
Stewart MacLennan,
64 Terregles Avenue,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Girl takes her first steps into a whole new life</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766217</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GIRL born without hip sockets yesterday took her first steps thanks to an
American hospital and her best friend's inspiration.
Holly Ashford, 13, faced the prospect of spending her life in a wheelchair but
has now become the $500,000 girl, the cost of a series of pioneering operations
by a US hospital.
However, there was a sad aspect to the joy. Her best friend Claire John, who
had persuaded her to try the operations after six attempts to cure the trouble
in this country failed, died last year from an asthma attack.
Holly, from Yeovil, Somerset, said: ``I was determined to make it work in
tribute to her: she helped and encouraged me so much.
``It's just so sad that she's not here to see me walk. She would have been so
pleased. I kept her photograph beside my hospital bed to keep me going when
things got tough.''
In September, Holly flew to Salt Lake City to have the two 18-hour operations.
They involved surgeon Sherman Coleman carving hip sockets into her pelvis.
Now Holly is able to walk with the help of crutches and leg braces. She has
been able to return to Britain to spend Christmas at home.
She hopes to discard the final brace in four months' time and play with her
sister Harriet, seven.
``It's great, so different from this time last year and now I'm pain free,''
said Holly, who wants to be a veterinary surgeon.
``Now I have a whole new life ahead of me and I want to be able to dance and
horse ride.
``I won't ever be in a wheelchair again. It is the best Christmas present
ever.''
The hospital performed the operations free of charge but the family still need
financial help to pay for follow-up costs. An appeal fund headed by a local
woman raised #11,000 for initial bills.
Holly's mother, Pauline, said: ``It is the greatest Christmas present we could
have wished for. I can hardly take it all in that she will be able to walk.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000137</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000137</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The cruel reality of housing budget cuts</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766218</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HEALTH spending to be slashed by a third. Investment in education to be cut by
38%. Imagine the headlines. Imagine the outpourings of the leader writers.
Imagine the rage of the political parties.
While as yet, fortunately, a distant prospect for schools or for hospitals,
there is no such consolation for council tenants. Such cuts are a cruel reality.
The full outline budget for council housing for the next three years was
announced on December 20 by the Scottish Housing Minister, Raymond Robertson.
By 1998-99 actual investment in council housing will have declined by 38% in
real terms compared to the current year's plans.
The Scottish Office will undoubtedly argue that the right to buy has led, and
will lead, to fewer council houses requiring money to be spent on them and that
this justifies cuts. But it is well-known that the right to buy has
cherry-picked the best houses; the houses which remain are those which require
disproportionate repairs and improvements.
There is also a need to replace those affordable homes which have been lost.
Investment should have been maintained for those tasks.
In past years, faced with such cuts to public-sector housing, we have at least
had the consolation of seeing housing associations pick up some of the need to
provide new and improved homes.
Not so from now on: next year Scottish Homes' budget for funding housing
associations and other independent developers will fall from #321m to #280m, a
cut of 15% in real terms?
Even this calculation depends on some rather optimistic assumptions from
Scottish Homes about how much they will raise from selling off their own homes.
We face the real prospect of any new developments from housing associations
being still born.
In anyone's terms this represents the deepest trough in the housing crisis. But
where are those headlines, those leader columns, those outcries of political
rage?
People who are homeless have every right to feel cheated. So too those on long
waiting-lists for housing and those tenants waiting patiently for repairs and
improvements to their homes.
But the failure goes deeper. It is a failure to realise the central role that
good, secure and affordable housing plays in individual lives; and so, the need
to place housing at the heart of public policy. After all, is there any point
in sending people straight from hospital to cold, damp homes; or much value in
giving a child a new book to haul around from one insecure temporary address to
the next?
Liz Nicholson, Director, Shelter Scotland; Alan Ferguson, Director, Chartered
Institute of Housing in Scotland; David Alexander, Policy Manager, Scottish
Federation of Housing Associations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Julia Carling wins libel case</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766219</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JULIA Carling yesterday accepted a public apology and ``substantial'' libel
damages over allegations in the Daily Mail that she cynically cashed in on the
publicity generated by her separation from her England rugby captain husband
Will.
A High Court judge heard that the first of two articles published in October
accused Mrs Carling, presenter of Capital Woman on Carlton TV, of being
prepared to use the services of publicity agent Max Clifford in a calculated
bid to further her own career and hurt her husband.
The ``offensive and distressing'' allegation was wholly untrue, said her
solicitor Peter Crawford.
``On the contrary, she wishes it to be known that she has declined to accept
numerous offers from many national newspapers to sell her story in return for
substantial sums because she does not wish to sell information about her
separation or her private life to the press,'' he told Mr Justice Morland.
She had never met or spoken to Mr Clifford and had no intention of ever using
his services.
The second article, published the following day, compounded the damage by
accusing her of skilfully manipulating the media on the back of her separation
and of revelling in the resulting publicity.
Mrs Carling hoped that the outcome of the libel action would call a halt to the
allegations and to ``the continuing press fascination with the state of her
marriage and intrusion into her (and her husband's) private life''.
Solicitor Liz Hartley, for the newspaper, which also agreed to pay legal costs,
apologised for the distress and hurt caused by the stories, published in
reliance on false information from third parties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
