<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Head man heads for Scotland to find the king's head</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766220</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THEY are the kind of things that generally go in threes.
First Ravenscraig closed, then Motherwell FC hit the bottom of the table. Now
it seems an African chief is coming to Motherwell to dig up the decapitated
head of an ancestor in an attempt to bring peace to South Africa.
Chief Nicholas Gcaleka, who also practises as a witch doctor but unfortunately
for Motherwell FC not as a centre forward, is due to fly in from South Africa
next month along with six tribal healers.
He is refusing to reveal where exactly the head is buried in Scotland but it is
thought he could be heading for the Lanarkshire town. The chief is based in
Motherwell, the one that is a Port Elizabeth suburb.
He maintains his Xhosa tribe has been cursed since King Hintsa Kaphalo was
decapitated and his head carried off as a trophy by a British soldier 167 years
ago. His tribe say the king lost his head in a battle with British forces,
colonising what is now South Africa.
Chief Gcaleka has been told that if he returns the head and buries it with the
rest of the king's body, peace will come to South Africa.
The trip is said to have the backing of South African President Nelson Mandela
while a Government lawyer is expected to join the trip to help resolve any
legal problems.
His quest has aroused interest in the South African business community: around
30 firms have helped raise #10,000 for expenses.
No exact date for the trip has been revealed but the chief has told friends the
quest must be completed by January 25. It accords with the time that manager
Alex McLeish has told his players that Motherwell FC must dig themselves out of
the relegation zone.
A spokesman for the chief said: ``This is very important to him and he's very
excited about going to Scotland. He believes that reuniting King Hintsa's head
with the rest of his body will bring peace and end corruption in South Africa.''
However, the British High Commission in Cape Town has taken issue with the
chief on the historical accuracy of his story. The commission claims King
Hintsa was never decapitated and that his head was never taken back to Scotland.
According to its records, the king was gunned down by a renegade British
soldier who opened fire during a peace conference. The soldier sliced off his
ears and was later punished at a court martial.
Meanwhile, Motherwell is bracing itself. A council spokeswoman said: ``We have
an excellent historical records department which will be only too happy to help
with any historical research.''
If the chief fails in his quest, he may find the odd head or two rolling free
if the king of Motherwell FC is not obeyed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
