<HEADLINE>Lockerbie relatives' cemetery protest</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766221</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington, Thursday
RELATIVES of some of the 270 people killed in the Lockerbie bombing seven years
ago were turned away from Arlington cemetery today when they tried to leave
wreaths at the memorial there.
The cemetery has been closed because Congress and President Bill Clinton are
locked in battle over the budget.
A memorial cairn to the dead was unveiled by the president on November 3.
When the families arrived this morning, they discovered the gates locked.
Arlington, though a military cemetery, is administered by the parks service, so
it is closed, like almost all the other national parks, monuments and museums
in the US.
The relatives were furious. One said that the anniversary of the worst day of
her life, the day on which her daughter and only child was killed, was always a
horrible occasion.
To find that she could not put flowers on the monument was to add insult to
agony, and she blamed the government for playing silly Washington games.
The Pentagon then intervened and sent a military team to escort the relatives
into Arlington. They are, of course, not the only disappointed visitors. There
are scores of thousands of veterans buried there, including President Kennedy
and his brother Robert, and a steady stream of people goes there every day, as
tourists or private pilgrims.
.q.The United States today called for tougher United Nations sanctions against
Libya for refusing to hand over two Libyan suspects in the bombing.
</TEXT>
