<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nothing can illustrate the foolishness of the princess more than her free admission of adultery Diana's fatal mistake is made</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Macleod</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766222</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
John Macleod casts an unrelenting eye over the options left open to two
sparring erstwhile partners
NO-ONE emerges well from the sorry wreck of the Prince of Wales's marriage. He
himself has been exposed as an inadequate, insensitive husband, who neglected
his wife for the favours of another woman, who was herself married to someone
else. The princess seems addicted both to publicity and victimhood, greedy for
the privileges of her rank but loth to wear the yoke of duty, daft enough to
sleep with a cad and admit it to the world.
The Queen herself put absurd pressure on the prince many years ago to marry and
to marry well, to marry a virgin, to marry someone of appropriate standing.
There was outrageous interference in his private affairs then; over the last
three years, she has dithered and dallied, while Diana and her nasty little
alternative court pumped her position and claims for all they were worth. The
Queen's action now is drastic but eminently justifiable and comes not a moment
too soon.
Before we consider further the principals of this drama, let's outline the
constitutional issues involved and assess the impact of divorce on the future
of the Windsors and the monarchy.
First: divorce is not unlawful, and facility for it has long existed both in
the laws of Scotland and England, though until the Victorian era each divorce
required a specific Act of Parliament. Second: divorce is not unBiblical. In
the Mosaic law, it was suffered on the grounds of adultery or desertion ``for
the hardness of men's hearts''. Christ in the Gospels recognised this but
implied that the remarriage of at least one party would be adulterous. In
divorce on Biblical grounds one party is always guilty and their remarriage
will be sinful.
Many evangelical Christians regard remarriage after divorce as always and
necessarily sinful for both parties. (Many others, though, do not; when
Princess Margaret sought to marry Group Captain Peter Townsend, she found an
unlikely ally in the Free Presbyterian Church of Scotland, who recognised that
Townsend had been an innocent party.) However, the Roman Catholic Church, which
views marriage as a sacrament, regards true marriage as indissoluble. Marriage
can be ``annulled'' - normally on the grounds of some technical inadequacy in
the marriage rite or marital relationship. Civil law here also permits
annulment, on one ground: that of a marriage which has not been physically
consummated.
The Roman Catholic view has also significantly influenced thinking in the
Church of England, of which the sovereign is supreme governor. (Oddly enough he
or she need not be a church member: James VII was a Roman Catholic.) Anglicans
do not regard divorce in and of itself as sinful and divorced parties are still
eligible to take Communion, for instance. Remarriage after divorce is frowned
on and very few Anglican vicars will grant a church wedding if one or both
parties are divorced. (When the Duke of Windsor married Wallis Simpson, in
1937, he had great difficulty in finding a clergyman prepared to officiate.)
The issue, then, is simple. The divorce will have no constitutional impact
whatever unless, at future date, the Prince of Wales decides to remarry. Much
might turn on who the happy woman might be; but he would be well-advised not to
seek a wedding service in the Church of England. He could marry in Scotland, as
the Princess Royal did some years ago, the Church of Scotland having a more
Biblical view of divorce and remarriage (Anne could claim to have been the
innocent party in her split; her former husband had fathered a child on another
woman). Or he could marry in a civil register office, as his cousin the Earl of
St Andrews did, when he took a Roman Catholic bride.
When the divorce is through, Charles will be perfectly entitled to succeed his
mother to the throne, in due time, and there is no reason in law or precedent
why he should not. (King George I was divorced but still ascended the British
throne in 1715.) Likewise, his sons remain in their proper places of
succession. He will retain his church privileges in the Anglican Communion and,
like George I, would be accepted as supreme governor. Once the divorce is
through, what his former wife chooses to do, and with whom, and how publicly,
will be irrelevant.
Diana, in strict precedent, should retain her present rank, though as ``Diana,
Princess of Wales'' rather than ``The Princess of Wales''. More likely she will
be sent off with some grandiloquent title: Duchess of Windsor, perhaps? If she
remarries she would of course shed that rank and any children of that marriage
would, I need hardly say, be without royal status or any claim to the throne.
In that regard, the Windsors might already be sweating over their malicious
refusal, in 1937, to recognise the Duchess of Windsor as Her Royal Highness and
of equal rank with her husband, formerly Edward VIII. It was argued then that
the title of Royal Highness, once granted, could not be removed; and even if
the Windsors divorced, and the duchess remarried, she would retain that rank
and further pass it on to children of her second marriage. Somewhere in
Frogmore, one hears wild American chuckles.
There are three difficulties on the horizon.
The first is the Princess of Wales herself. She has given no response to the
Queen's request that she concur in a rapid divorce. Diana might be stupid
enough - and some of her circle are certainly desperate enough - to resist.
With her consent, a divorce could be processed in a matter of weeks (and the
Queen is no doubt mindful of the impending new legislation from Lord Mackay,
with its absolute mandatory ``cooling off'' period of 12 months. If Diana
contests the divorce, it could be delayed for three years. This would be a
great embarrassment.
The second problem is the marital future of the Prince of Wales. He has
declared he does not intend to remarry. However, he declared a good deal on
July 29, 1981, that he has since broken, and the word of an adulterer may
readily change with circumstances. Besides, he could find it hard to reign
without someone to act as consort: true, there might be a daughter-in-law but,
on what they have seen of heterosexuality, his sons may decide they prefer boys.
If the prince does make a second bid for marital bliss, and if his bride is
deemed fit by the public, and if he does not seek an Anglican wedding, this
could be accomplished readily enough. But what if he decides to marry Camilla
Parker Bowles? She is widely viewed as Diana's heartbreak, as the scarlet
woman, as the ageing adventuress who saw off the young and innocent bride. On
that ground alone there would be riots in the streets.
Further, Mrs Parker Bowles is herself now divorced, and she is of Roman
Catholic background (though her present relationship to that system is
unclear). Marriage to a Roman Catholic, by any in line to the throne, is
forbidden under the 1701 Act of Settlement.
The prince's marriage would also require, in his position, the permission of
the Queen. She would be bound to take Cabinet advice and that advice would
certainly be, at the present time, that he could not marry this woman and
remain heir apparent to the throne.
Charles will almost certainly weather the demands widely made, at present, that
he step aside from the succession and leave the way clear for his elder son. As
long as he wants to be king that will remain the position. But if he tries to
marry Mrs Parker Bowles he will be denied the choice.
The third difficulty is more delicate: is Charles the father of his sons?
Nothing shows the stupidity of the princess more than her free admission of
adultery. (It was, in strict law, an admission to high treason by herself and
for the wretched fellow involved.) Apart from the anguish caused to her
children, it raises the obvious question of their paternity. Prince William is
obviously the son of his father and of the true Teutonic line. In Prince
Harry's case, a resemblance is less evident.
Only a few weeks ago, we were exhorted to marvel at the courage, dignity, and
bearing of the princess in her sensational Panorama interview. In hindsight, it
already appears mawkish, embarrassing, and rehearsed. It has also proved a
major political blunder. By admitting her own adultery and by declaring openly
that she did not believe her husband would be king, she committed the
unforgivable in the eyes of the Queen.
The princess showed both malice and wilful ignorance of her position. She
pushed beyond bounds the great tolerance granted her these three years past. It
was also an astonishing blunder to predict she herself would not be queen -
that future contingency, however tenuous it appeared, being the strongest
weapon in her armoury.
When the divorce comes - and come it will, whatever she might now try - the
princess will be visibly devalued in rank and standing. Her looks are already
fading. Her sons are growing up and away from her influence. People, I think,
are beginning to laugh at her, as they whooped at Rory Bremner's wonderful
panda-eyed parody of her broadcast.
There has been, for 40 years, an insistent tradition of prophecy in the
Hebrides that Charles will never reign. That remains to be seen. But his wife's
role in the drama is over. She has written herself out of the script and, at
the last - for all her miseries - has only herself to blame.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
