<DOCNO>GH951222-000142</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000142</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nato chief lays down peace rules to Bosnia rivals</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766223</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sarajevo, Thursday
NATO moved quickly today to stamp a peace strategy on the ruins of Bosnia and
told leaders of the former warring factions that its 60,000 troops would go
where they pleased.
Units of the biggest peace-time force the alliance has ever mustered fanned out
across the country, tearing down roadblocks and passing frontlines which its
United Nations predecessor never crossed.
``I am an optimist.......I am just tickled pink with what I seee already,'' the
overall Commander of the Nato's Implementation Force (IFOR), Admiral Leighton
Smith told CNN television 24 hours after it took over from the UN.
Smith met military leaders of the Muslim, Croat and Bosnian Serb communities to
tell them how he planned to enforce the peace which their political leaders
signed in Paris last week.
He said he had told them at ``very succesful'' talks that his multi-national
force from more than 30 nations would exercise complete freedom of movement and
go ``wherever we need to go''.
Smith laid down his plans at a heavily-guarded meeting with the one-time
warring faction chiefs at the first meeting of a Joint Military Commission set
up to monitor implementation of the Paris peace accord.
Britain's Defence Minister Michael Portillo said the 13,000-strong British
contingent would use force if necessary against anyone who tried to break the
pact ending the worst conflict in Europe since the Second World War.
He said that the Nato force, better armed than UN troops and backed by a strong
international resolve, would try persuasion and argument first but back it up
with firepower.
``.......it is perfectly clear that they (British troops) are armed in such a
way to defend themselves and they have the authority to use force if that is
necessary to implement the peace agreement,'' he said on a brief visit to
Sarajevo.
``You'll find that the forces are much more prepared to defend
themselves.......but also take action against anyone who may try to break the
peace agreement,'' he said.
Meanwhile, the commander of US ground troops in Bosnia said in Tuzla today he
planned to put forward bases in Serb-held territory, where foreign troops were
barred during 43 months of war, to enforce the peace accord.
Major General William Nash told reporters all 20,000 US troops in the
60,000-member Nato peacekeeping force should be deployed in Bosnia by the end
of January.
He said US Army engineers are expected to complete a temporary bridge next week
across the Sava River, marking the border between Croatia and Bosnia north of
this northeast Bosnia US base. This would allow the First Armoured Division now
massing in Hungary to roll south into Bosnia.
Nash said he had been meeting with military leaders of all the parties to the
peace accord and ``their words and deeds are positive''.
The Bosnian Serbs have been the most critical of the peace agreement and are
regarded by US officials as harbouring factions that are most likely to break
the peace.
``They have pledged their support,'' Nash said, adding that the Serbs had
started to clear minefields and withdraw to boundaries laid down in the
US-brokered peace deal signed in Paris on December 14.
Nash said the first units of the Armoured division, driving Abrams tanks and
armoured Bradley Fighting Vehicles, would be met near the Sava crossing and
would then head south to Tuzla.
Later units would move directly to forward bases set up to run patrols along
the dividing lines between Bosnian factions.
A US military official said a Russian airborne brigade would be stationed in
Serb-held territory around Bijeljina, northeast of Tuzla. It will be the first
US-Russian military operation with combat potential since the Second World
War.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Skier relives snow ordeal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974766224</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SKIER who survived three nights of blizzards while lost in Glenshee is to
relive his experience on television tonight. Mr Andrew Wilson eventually walked
out of the mountains during a lull in the weather after spending two nights
entombed in a snow-hole in February.
The 45-year-old from East Kilbride, a cashier with a plumbers' merchants in
Glasgow, will tell of his ordeal on the LWT documentary Missing, to be screened
at 9pm on Scottish.
Second tragedy
A WOMAN whose husband was killed in the Piper Alpha disaster has been hit by
another tragedy. Mrs Christine Richard's son, Brian, 22, was found dead in a
flat at Linlithgow, West Lothian. Police have ruled out suspicious
circumstances. Mrs Richard, of Polmont, Stirlingshire, was widowed when her
husband, Bob, died in the 1988 North Sea oil rig disaster.
Pleasant shock
TWO thousand electricians in Scotland's building industry are to get a 3.5% pay
rise from January, their union, the AEEU said yesterday.
Park stabbing
POLICE in Edinburgh are treating as attempted murder the stabbing of a
15-year-old boy in Corstorphine Park. The boy, from the Corstorphine area,
suffered a punctured lung and last night was said to be ``serious but stable''
in Edinburgh Royal Infirmary.
Tory choice
THE Scottish Conservative Party have chosen their candidate to oppose Labour
front-bench spokesman John McFall in his Dumbarton constituency at the next
General Election. He is Mr Peter Ramsay, 40, of Helensburgh, a personal banking
manager with the Clydesdale Bank in West Dunbartonshire.
Hospice grant
SCOTTISH Secretary Michael Forsyth yesterday gave a #500,000 Christmas present
to support the new children's hospice, Rachel House, currently being built at
Kinross. The move follows a meeting between Mr Forsyth and representatives of
the Children's Hospice Association Scotland (CHAS). The Government has already
contributed #750,000 to the project
Bogus sales
POLICE last night issued a warning to elderly people in the Kirkintilloch area
to be on their guard after a bogus door-to-door sales team robbed a pensioner
of a three-figure sum of money on Wednesday. The incident follows a spate of
similar calls by a number of women to pensioners' homes over the last month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nig-nog training did not offend recruit</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766225</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I HAVE just read the item in Tom Shields's Diary about Councillor Buchanan and
the use of the expression ``nig-nog'' (December 19). This was an expression
constantly used in the Army during the days of National Service. It never had
any racial connotation.
I recall one morning in July, 1949, when my training platoon was being marched
down to the dining-hall at Fort George when the drill corporal stopped the
platoon suddenly; he put his face close to mine and stated loudly: ``Doig, you
are a f****** nig-nog! What are you?''
I was then required to roar as loudly as possible in the affirmative. One
rendition was never enough, nor was the volume ever satisfactory.
We would then continue our progress towards the dining-hall by which time
another platoon had passed us which brought the platoon's invective upon me as
this would mean that there was now a much longer queue at the cookhouse waiting
for the ATS girls' watery porridge.
The culprit was not necessarily told what his offence had been. It was all part
of the game and afforded the corporal or sergeant some wry amusement. I do not
recall that I was offended thereby. He was probably right!
Thousands of graduates of the Highland Brigade Training Battalion at Fort
George will remember such occasions.
Bill Doig,
6 Douglas Drive East,
Helensburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
