<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Story that gave the tabloids their fifteen minutes of fame, not shame</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766227</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
``GOT a story?'' is the start of a little white-on-black box which usually sits
on page two of the Sun newspaper. It then tells you to phone the Sun's news
desk. On Wednesday afternoon, according to the paper's editor, someone did that
with devastating effect, and gave the paper what it quite rightly calls the
``royal scoop of the year.''
However, such scoops are transitory. What the Sun had to itself at 10pm that
night was by midnight a far more in-depth three-page study of the Queen's
intervention in her eldest son's marriage in The Herald.
The point though, is that once again one of Britain's tabloids, often so
sleazy, crass, and embarrassing, was spot on in its coverage of a royal story.
While the tabloids embellish so many stories, their track record on the Prince
and Princess of Wales in recent years has been praiseworthy. Perhaps, of
course, it is because to readers interested in the royals, the truth is so
compelling that embellishment is not required.
As the Wales's marriage deteriorated, both sides used the tabloids to wage
megaphone diplomacy of the loudest kind on each other to try to win public
sympathy. All it really won was newspaper sales.
In 1987, the harder edge of royal reporting began as the rift between Charles
and Diana became obvious. The media was desperate for details. Eventually the
details came, often from friends of the couple. That was for two reasons.
Either to give their side of the story a bigger airing, or purely for money.
Even Sloane rangers require the occasional injection of hard cash into their
bank accounts.
Then in 1992 came the biggest eye-opener so far - Andrew Morton's book Diana:
Her True Story, which revealed that the princess felt ``trapped in a loveless
marriage'', suggested she suffered from bulimia nervosa, and that she made a
number of suicide attempts in the early 1980s.
It was followed by the ``Squidgygate'' tapes, giving details of an telephone
conversation between Diana and James Gilbey. Then ``Camillagate'', another
tape, this time a highly personal conversation between Charles and Camilla
Parker Bowles.
The palace was appalled and covert attempts were made by the Queen's senior
aides to involve the Press Complaints Commission in somehow curbing the
tabloids. Lord McGregor, the chairman of the PCC, was told that newspaper
claims that the Princess of Wales and her friends had co-operated on the Morton
book were lies.
Lord McGregor attempted to censure the press. Unfortunately, he was soon to
discover that he had been misled by the palace.
Thoughts of official complaints to the PCC dissipated. Instead, the palace
withdrew to the sidelines as the confirmation finally came in television
interviews by Prince Charles and Princess Diana that both had indeed committed
adultery. The tabloids had been right all along.
Mr Stuart Higgins, editor of The Sun, believes the Queen's intervention in the
marriage saga is a courageous one.
``I think the Queen took it upon herself, very bravely, to intervene and decide
out of commonsense this can't go on any longer, to have the whole thing played
out day after day, the public bickering, the tit for tat. The interviews after
each other, hitting at each other, he said.
Very magnanimous from a journalist whose paper has depended so much on the
public warring for selling papers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951222-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951222-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Plea for realism on fishing deal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766228</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FISHERIES Minister Tony Baldry appealed for realism from Britain's fishermen
last night as he prepared to accept a Euro deal on catches which will mean
belt-tightening for trawlermen.
Whatever the scale of concessions he wrings out of marathon negotiations in
Brussels, national catch quotas in British waters will be cut drastically in
the name of conservation.
Reductions of up to a half in permitted catches of main species have been
tabled by the Brussels Commission, relying on scientific evidence that EU
fishing waters are desperately depleted and need a respite.
The negotiations were adjourned last night and a final deal is not expected
until later today.
Mr Baldry insisted he was out for the ``best possible deal'' for fishermen and
added: ``We have to strike a balance between conservation and ensuring the
industry can bring in a decent catch to sustain them.''
Of the industry's reaction, he said: ``At the end of the day, my ability will
have to be judged by them. It is their livelihoods, it is their futures which
are at stake and I think and hope that they will make a realistic judgment on
what we will be able to achieve here.''
The Commons defeat for a Government motion supporting cuts made little
difference to Mr Baldry's bargaining position but he hopes to limit the
reduction in the planned British North Sea plaice quota to 30% instead of the
suggested 47%. He is also arguing for smaller cuts than recommended in hake and
mackerel quotas.
The outcome will determine the future prosperity of the UK fleet, with
fishermen warning that some trawler owners will go out of business.
</TEXT>
