<HEADLINE>Reuter honours Herald writer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766229</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Herald journalist Chris Holme has won the first Reuter Foundation
Fellowship in Medical Journalism at Oxford University.
Mr Holme, 41, a news reporter at The Herald's Edinburgh office since 1987, will
spend three months next year at Green College, Oxford, studying aspects of the
campaign against the worldwide resurgence of tuberculosis.
The Reuter Foundation is the news agency's charitable and educational arm. It
was set up in 1982 to promote high standards in international journalism.
Its new fellowship in medical journalism is intended to offer specialist
writers and broadcasters an opportunity to carry out personal research. A
second fellowship is now being offered at the Columbia Graduate School of
Journalism in New York.
Mr Holme has written extensively in The Herald on medical issues, including the
development 40 years ago of the first 100% cure for TB by an Edinburgh team led
by Sir John Crofton.
</TEXT>
