<HEADLINE>Yes, he's a jolly good fellow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Allan Laing</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766230</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Rikki Fulton's calling has proved an uplifting experience for all, so it should
come as no surprise that he is a religious man. But he is also one of the most
popular in Scotland, or so it seems to Allan Laing
FUNNY things, jokes. But they're really only funny things when you hear them
the first time. After that, they tend to lose a bit in the telling. It is the
law of diminishing returns, I suppose.
``The trouble is they're not like songs,'' explains a thoughtful Rikki Fulton,
a man who over the years has delivered more gags than you could shake a stick
at. ``Kenneth McKellar can stand up on stage and say `Ladies and gentlemen, I'd
now like to sing a beautiful number - and one of my own personal favourites . .
. Aye Fond Kiss.' And the audience will burst into wild applause. As a
comedian, I always used to think how lucky singers were because you could never
do that with a joke.''
Well, actually, that is not strictly true. If you're Rikki Fulton and Jack
Milroy masquerading as Francie and Josie, then it can happen. During a recent
performance at the King's Theatre in Glasgow, the pair were in full comic
flight when Francie said ``Tell them the one about Arbroath, Josie.'' And, as
if they had announced an old familiar song, the audience clapped and cheered
like there was no tomorrow, a roar of approval in anticipation of the pair's
best-loved routine.
The origins of the joke (anyone who has ever seen Francie and Josie will be
familiar with this particular Arbroath declaration) are worth examining in some
detail for they illustrate perfectly the symbiotic relationship which exists
between the two old rogues of Scottish variety. Stripped bare, it is a
wonderfully silly wee gag about a chap who chaps on a door and it's answered by
another chap and the chap who chapped the door asks ``Is your grannie in?'' And
the chap who answered the door to the chap who chapped the door says ``No,
she's at Arbroath.'' Then the chap who chapped the door says ``Well, I'll just
wait till she's finished.''
But the real beauty of the gag (think ``soup'', then read it out loud and
you'll get it) is the fact that it is only the skeleton key, its funny bones
inspirationally fleshed out by Fulton and Milroy's brilliant ad-libbing. Off
they go into a truly hilarious routine - different every time they do it -
which can last as long as 10 or even 15 minutes.
Rikki Fulton recalls that the gag came into being many years ago during a Five
Past Eight Show at the King's. ``We were doing this sketch where we were locked
out of a bed and breakfast; it was supposed to be a haunted house in the middle
of nowhere. And Frankenstein monsters and mummies would appear as we were
standing on the steps of this house.
``So there was this mummy standing over us and Jack, typically, said `Tell them
the one about Arbroath, Josie.' And I took it from there.''
You had to feel sorry for the poor mummy. There he was, standing there like a
ham sandwich at a Jewish wedding, while Fulton and Milroy launched into this
totally unscripted routine. He didn't know whether to stay, join in, or walk
off for a cup of tea and a fag.
``I do have this terrible habit of ad-libbing,'' explains Fulton, with an eye
for the understatement. ``I've done Moliere and Shakespeare and I've found that
certain members of my profession - classical actors - don't like it. But it is
what I do. Jack is exactly the same. I noticed when we first started to work
together that, on first nights it sometimes didn't work too well. But on the
second night we got roars of laughter because we'd say to ourselves `I'll stick
this or that in.' We just said whatever came into our minds.
``We were both from the same school - and it wasn't a terribly disciplined one,
I suppose. We still ad-lib all the time. It's a kind of challenge to each
other; a sort of `get out of that one' kind of thing. And a lot of the best
material we ever had came from that.''
Every time they did it, Rikki would go home and write all the ad-libs down.
``I'd write it properly, hone it and tidy it up, and then other ideas would
occur to me. And it all came from this ad-lib.''
We are sitting in the study of the actor's palatial West End home. He is in
relaxed mode, comfortably stretched out in a leather easy chair. Any time is a
good time to talk to the amiable Mr Fulton - but the festive season is more
appropriate than most.
After all, over many years we have come to associate him with Hogmanay. First,
through his Scotch and Wry series and, more recently, through our annual visit
to the manse of Scotland's cheeriest minister, that familiar bundle of Church
of Scotland laughs, the Rev I M Jolly.
But right now, barely a fortnight before his new show is due to be broadcast,
Fulton is musing about his life, about his career, and about the gift God gave
him - the abiding talent to crack a light and make us laugh. A profoundly
thoughtful and considerate man, he is an engaging conversationalist with an
endearing habit of wandering wonderfully off the point.
You very quickly realise that there are an awful lot of good things to be said
for Rikki Fulton. The first, and probably the most important, is the fact that
you couldn't meet a nicer man in a month's walking. The second is that, by
virtue of the fact that he is probably the finest comic actor of his (or any
other) generation, he makes us laugh. And the third is that, throughout a long
and distinguished career, he has steadfastly refused to desert his beloved
Glasgow.
Now comes the ``but''. But the thing about Fulton is that there are no buts
about him. It may be a cliche but he really is one of our ``best-loved'' actors.
He is show business's glorious exception. With him, what you see is what you
get. A proper gentleman. A happy and thoroughly contented human being with his
heart in the right place and his feet firmly on the ground. One of nature's
good guys. Was it ever thus? Probably. For, no matter who you talk to, you will
never hear a word said against him.
You mention his childhood - by all accounts a happy one in Dennistoun, brought
up the son of a newsagent and stationer - and you set off a fascinating train
of nostalgic thought. You quickly realise that here is a man, refreshingly
untainted by the vulgar excesses of the modern world, who treasures those
old-fashioned, benignly conservative values which disappeared, like snow off a
dyke, around the time the Corporation tram cars ceased to ply their trade in
Glasgow.
``I was born in 1924 so we are talking about a totally different set of rules,
regulations, customs, and views. It was a different country altogether. I mean
sex was a word you didn't use. Homosexuality was something you never heard
about. Anyone living together out of marriage would not be visited by either
family. If someone committed some terrible murder then they would be hanged.
``It was a happier and safer world to live in because it had all to do with the
fact that you knew exactly where you were. Policemen were respected, ministers
were respected. You wouldn't dream of arguing with your mother or father. They
were obeyed. Drugs were not around; the worst thing you could do was smoke too
early,'' he recalls.
This almost quaint sense of morality, which is both rare and unfashionable in
this day and age, is reflected in his work. As a regular churchgoer, dirty
jokes are anathema to him. Which is why there's nothing remotely crude or
smutty about Francie and Josie. It's all good clean fun. Likewise the Rev
Jolly. What Fulton delivers is a strength of characters, great comic roles
which don't need the crutch of bad taste to hold them up.
Rikki Fulton took his first tentative step into the world of showbiz shortly
after he was demobbed from the Navy. It was the mid forties and he was working
in a mundane job in a Glasgow shipping office. For some reason he found himself
drawn to the theatre, joining the local amateur Pantheon Club. After an
audition with the BBC he made his first radio broadcast in 1947. The engagement
led to more regular work, hosting the BBC Show Band Show from London (to this
day his only lengthy absence from Scotland).
It was not until 1954 that he first appeared on the stage as a comedian - in an
Edinburgh Festival revue. Shortly after that Howard and Wynham, famous
impressarios of the day, signed Fulton up on a long-term contract and teamed
him with legendary Scots comic Alec Finlay.
More than 40 years later, Rikki Fulton can look back with no small measure of
pride and satisfaction on a rich and diverse stage career. There was his
inspired performance in the celebrated Scots version of the Moliere plays for
Bill bryden at Edinburgh's Royal Lyceum. Then there was his big-screen role as
the sinister, steely-eyed, KGB villain in Michael Apted's Gorky Park. More
recently, of course, he's been back on familiar territory with BBC Scotland's
re-working of The Vital Spark.
But Rikki Fulton's kindest words are reserved for his theatrical partnership
with Jack Milroy. Of all the things he has done, it's Francie and Josie which
he has enjoyed the most.
He explains it this way: ``You know how people go to the theatre, watch a show,
and on the way home in the car they'll chuckle away and say `That was helluva
funny when they did this or that.' Well, that's exactly what Jack and I do too
after a show. We talk about it all the way home!
``There is something very rewarding and particularly satisfying about working
with someone where you get this great togetherness and understanding with each
finding the other funny.
``There are other things I have done which have put me under tremendous
pressure or have perhaps been greater challenges. I am very proud of them but,
in the end, it's Francie and Josie which gives me the most fun.''
Mind you, there was a time not so long ago when it appeared that the characters
were fast approaching the end of the road. But, at 67 and 71 respectively,
Milroy and Fulton seem prepared to soldier on for a while yet. Indeed, Fulton
is currently slaving over a hot computer screen, writing an entire new show for
the gruesome twosome which will be unleashed upon an unsuspecting Glasgow
public some time next year.
``It is a lot of work and I often complain that I'm stuck in front of a word
processor and all I get from Jack is the odd postcard from Tenerife or Majorca
saying `Keep going, China,''' he quips. ``To be honest it's not the happiest
way of spending the day or night. And there's something about writing. At the
back of your mind there's always this great block of anxiety about a joke which
you might find helluva funny but that no-one else will.''
The truth is that Rikki Fulton, at 71, will not allow himself to be put under
pressure from work. A serious heart attack a few years back served to
concentrate his mind and slow him down. Nevertheless, the offers of work are
still there if he wants them.
``I have to tell you, the things I have turned down only this year in film and
television parts you would not believe. And I turned them down because it would
have meant me being away from home for too long. If I cannot have my wife
(Kate, to whom he is utterly devoted) along with me then I don't want to know.
In any case, I am much more at home in the theatre in Scotland,'' he explains.
</TEXT>
