<HEADLINE>In this story of four women and a wimp, was the oldest the most meddlesome? Dowagers v ditherer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anne Simpson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<FLAG>Features</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph </GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766231</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The Queen Mother encouraged a meek and biddable Diana to pass through the
portals of protocol, says Anne Simpson
NOT many chuckles at the Buck House Happy Hour tonight. Those letters from the
Queen, so obviously intended to draw the messy tale of Splitsville to a close,
are having precisely the opposite effect. In terms of drama, The Public Fall of
the House of Windsor might yet outrun The Mousetrap. One thing is certain: next
Monday, the Sovereign's seasonal broadcast to an increasingly truculent nation
will notch up its biggest audience for years. The question is: will she, or
won't she?
The notion of an idealised royal family began in the same era that Christmas
itself became an elaborate family festival. Now Elizabeth II, the only one of
the tribe still actively holding regality and worthiness together, must enter
our living rooms as the beleaguered figurehead of ramshackle mythologies.
Apart from, maybe, one reference, couched in Latin, to another horrible year,
it is doubtful that Her Majesty will unburden her heart to the country. She was
born to adhere to a system that imposes emotional denial upon its members. Her
siblings might openly challenge it but look what happens - her siblings become
humiliatingly unstuck.
In fact, this is the very British story of four women and a wimp. It began with
a hyper-sensitive child who sought more ready affection than a royal mother
seemed able to give. So he sought and found pampering approval from a figure
one generation removed; that make-believe granny of the people, the Good Queen
Mum.
On reflection, the early travails of Charles's love life were the first
elements to threaten his public reputation. He was hopeless, and hopelessly, in
love with numerous society women, all too independent and intelligent to settle
for the stifling grandeur of marriage to the throne's heir and its long
practiced moral deceits. As a result, Charles the Misunderstood sought release
from misery in the company of a high-caste country woman whose gumboots-style
and impressive plainness are, interestingly, not unlike those of her lover's
mother, the Queen.
According to Lord Charteris, permanent Lord-in-Waiting at Buckingham Palace,
Camilla Parker Bowles is the love of Charles's life. Yet his very dependence on
the affection and guidance of a married woman (as she was then), did not
prevent him submitting to the marriage instructed by his family. So, by taking
Diana as his wife, Charles the Misunderstood became increasingly Charles the
Wretched.
Here, the cruellest irony pierces the tale, for it was with the Queen Mother's
encouragement that the meek and biddable Lady Diana Spencer passed through the
portals of insufferable protocol as consort to the prince. Diana is the
grandchild of one of the dowager Queen's closest friends, the late Ruth, Lady
Fermoy, and popular belief has it that the two old ladies set about their
disastrous match-making when it became obvious that Charles could no longer
delay choosing a wife.
From the start, some say, Lady Fermoy had worries about a misalliance. However,
in Diana, the Crown had found not just the required sexual innocent but a
symbol of modernity. What it eventually got, to maybe its greatest cost, was a
virgin who refused to be sacrificial. The Wales's doomed marriage is perhaps
the Queen Mother's only public mistake.
She was 82 at the time of the wedding and no doubt possessed an elderly
incomprehension about the very fundamental shifts in British life. Infidelity
would not have shocked her, since that has always been a sophisticated,
upper-crust deceit, but the candid independence of contemporary women was
something completely alien to her generation.
All those years before, it had been the Queen Mother's insistence on duty that
had been paramount in Princess Margaret's decision not to marry the handsome
and gallant divorcee, Peter Townsend. As things worsened in her favourite
grandchild's marriage, she might have thought her influence would be equally
effective in taming Diana. It wasn't, with the result that an old Queen and a
``future Queen'' allegedly came to detest each other.
Howvever, having been told to marry by his mother, and now finally instructed
by her to divorce, Charles seeks to shake off the ditherer image by announcing
he will never marry again, and possibly this is one way to pre-empt any further
scorn or outrage in his direction.
The desanctifying of Diana began with James Hewitt's caddish revelations and
continued with Julia Carling's silky catfight over her foolish husband's roving
eye. Yet in both instances Diana has emerged triumphant. Hewitt has been
black-balled from society and Will Carling has not only lost his wife, he has
been snubbed and dumped by a princess for being too crass in his infatuation.
And still Diana's popularity rating far outstrips her husband's.
Of course, Prince Charles has no need to marry Camilla for, as things are, her
own divorce, earlier this year, tidies and elevates her status as his closest
confidante. The couple could simply reinforce the contemporary trend and
co-habit, with the hearty and efficient Princess Anne acting as consort when
required. Yet Charles's ruling out of Camilla as a wife raises still more
questions than it answers. If she is to be seen accompanying him in official
life, will the citizenry wear it? Camilla has no public following and the
palace must consider how her appearance would go down in places such as
Bermondsey or Crathie.
Certainly Diana will never be queen, and she has long known that. Skittish in
Klosters, some years ago, she alerted photographers to an outsize medal on her
ski jacket, explaining: ``I have awarded it to myself for services to my
country because nobody else will.''
Graceful, hardworking, wilful, this noblewoman demonstrates repeatedly how an
instinctively manipulative and beautiful creature can hold her own against any
men.
In the past, women who owed their royal station to their marriages were shunted
out to the country when they fell from favour, or they had their heads chopped
off. But the broad, muscular back and full-blown figure which the princess now
reveals in those low-cut, shapely gowns seems to symbolise her metamorphosis
from Shy Di to powerful and self-possessed womanhood. She has also added a
feminist agenda to her armoury, reflecting the demands of twentieth-century
women to be defined not by men but as themselves.
Curiosity about her fate will remain fervent. Her loving attentiveness as a
mother is not doubted but what might stymie her chances of some sort of
ambassadorial existence, or establishing an alternative but influential
commoners' court, will be any indication of vindictive behaviour over the
divorce. Or any more predatory meddling with other people's marriages.
Diana says she wishes to use the media interest in her to her country's
advantage, and not be ``battered by it'', but fame and celebrity are fickle
allies in establishing a long-term career. As she ages and the glamour becomes
less immediately photogenic, she will find the cameras moving on to other
targets. In seven years' time, Prince William will be 20 and his hunt for a
royal bride will be the magnet for all the gossip hacks.
So, what advice would this clever but damaged mother-in-law give to a woman who
will be judged just as much as she was by the man she marries, rather than as
the person she is? Would she tell William's bride to seek affection from an
adoring public rather than from her husband? To reconcile herself to public
duty and private loneliness? To walk out before her face is on the souvenir
T-shirts? Or to find consolation in being the world's Number One cover girl?
Would she tell the royal bride to take a lover, or take fate on the chin? Or
even suggest that, given her own eventual divorce settlement, the marriage of a
twenty-first century woman to a future king could be a worthwhile life choice,
of sorts?
Nothing more illustrates the gulf in regal and emotional understanding between
Diana and the Queen than a comment in another royal TV expose earlier this
week. The divorce letters had not yet been made public but, in the programme,
certain persons were heard to discuss the imminent departure of a beautiful
lady from the royal family. Only they were talking about Britannia.
</TEXT>
