<HEADLINE>Labour candidate back in spotlight Sarwar faces city planning investigation</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766232</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
MOHAMMED Sarwar, one of the candidates at the centre of the Labour racism row
in Govan, has been pitched into a new controversy - this time over his business
affairs.
The Herald can reveal that the millionaire Pakistani businessman, who is the
Labour councillor for Pollokshields, is to be reported to the next district
council planning meeting over a breach of planning regulations.
Acting on information also passed to The Herald, planning and building control
officers visited Mr Sarwar's United Cash &amp; Carry business in West Street, on
the south side of the city.
The planning officer found that Mr Sarwar's business had expanded into an
adjoining building and was selling goods to the public.
The retailing is in direct contradiction to the full planning permission
granted for the building to a Mr Muhammed Akram by the district council in June
this year.
This permission had been granted on condition that ``the premises shall be used
for a storage and distribution warehouse as described by the applicant in his
letter dated March 20, and for no other purpose''.
Last night, a district council spokesman said: ``There are all sorts of things
on display to the general public in Mr Akram's depot and the effect of this is
that the planning department is to go to the next council planning committee
meeting to seek authority to serve on Mr Akram and Mr Sarwar breach of
condition notices which would require them to stop immediately.
``There is no right of appeal against this. The first available planning
committee meeting is on January 5 and the department will seek authority to
serve the notice then. If they did not stop, we could go to the fiscal.''
United is also apparently trading as a retail warehouse with members of the
public able to walk in off the street and buy goods. However, the district
council spokesman said that no-one in the area had been given retail consent.
``United has only wholesale consent,'' the spokesman said.
He added: ``If it is brought to our attention that there is an operation which
is carried out which is in breach of planning conditions, we have to
investigate and take steps to regularise it.''
The Herald understands that no-one has so far complained about this.
The district council spokesman also said there appeared to be no building
warrant for the two connecting entrances between Mr Sarwar's business and Mr
Akram's warehouse.
He said that fire exits could also be an issue. What had been set up to
safeguard a small number of warehousemen would not not necessarily be
satisfactory for the public.
Last night, Mr Sarwar's brother, Mohammad Ramzam, who deals with commercial
operations, said they were letting the building from Mr Akram, who was their
landlord. ``He assured us there was no problem as a cash and carry. A deal has
not been finalised. We are hoping to get a deal by the end of the month.
``I am not sure what it says on the lease. I don't know the complications. My
solicitor is looking into it. We can easily stop people going into Mr Akram's
depot or we can apply for change of use.''
Mr Ramzam said he believed his manager had knocked two entrances through to Mr
Akram's depot as a temporary measure. ``I'm not sure about building warrants.''
Mr Ramzam also said they were operating as a wholesaler and not a retailer.
``Our stock is sold at wholesale prices. Some people can say they are the
public but we say they are small business people.''
On the question of fire safety, he said: ``I think we have enough fire exits in
the building. It is well covered.''
It is the second time Mr Sarwar, who is a member of the Scottish Labour Party's
NEC and who has been elected to Pollokshields East on the new unitary
authority, has found himself the centre of controversy.
Last week, Mr Sarwar, who is bidding to become the first Asian MP in the UK,
was embroiled in a furious row after he lost his bid to become Labour
prospective parliamentary candidate for Glasgow Govan by one vote to Mike
Watson MP.
It emerged then that about 52 ballot papers - many of them Sarwar supporters -
had been disallowed, leading to the claim that they had been victims of racism.
Loud cries were raised for an inquiry while Mr Sarwar contemplated a legal
action. That threat was withdrawn pending a meeting of Labour's national
executive committee which will decide whether to investigate Mr Sarwar's
complaint when it meets on January 24.
</TEXT>
