<HEADLINE>Soldiers fail in murder appeal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766233</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO Scots Guards who shot dead an unarmed teenager on the streets of Belfast
were sent back to jail yesterday after a court rejected their appeals against
conviction for murder.
James Fisher, 27, from Ayr, and Mark Wright, 22, of Arbroath, who were given
life sentences, heard the judgment at the Northern Ireland Court of Appeal.
The youth's father, Mr Peter McBride, 46, said he was satisfied but hoped there
would not be another Lee Clegg-style campaign to free the two men.
``There is no point in judges passing sentences if there is somebody else
coming behind with his magic pen and then rubbing them out,'' he said, adding
that ``life should mean life''.
His 18-year-old son, also Peter, was shot dead in the republican New Lodge Road
area of north Belfast in September, l992.
Fisher and Wright denied murder, claiming they opened fire because they
believed the boy, who was running away at the time, was carrying a ``coffee
jar'' bomb and they feared for their lives. He was unarmed.
Defence lawyers claimed crucial witnesses lied at the original trial because
they were hostile to the presence of the British Army.
The Northern Ireland Lord Chief Justice, Sir Brian Hutton, dismissing the
appeals, said there had been no justifiable reason for the shooting.
However, at the end of his judgment, he declared: ``This court shares the hope
of the trial judge that Parliament will give consideration to the substitution
of a single crime of culpable homicide for the present distinct crimes of
murder and manslaughter, so that in a case of this nature a trial judge will
have power to impose a sentence for the term of years he considers just . . .
rather than be compelled to impose a sentence of life imprisonment.''
Fisher, of Glendale Place, Belmont, Ayr, and Wright, of Glebe Road, Arbroath,
were taken back to Maghaberry Prison, near Lisburn, County Antrim, to resume
their sentences.
Fisher's wife Julie left the court without making any comment but the soldiers'
former commanding officer, who did not wish to be named, said: ``These soldiers
found themselves operating in a difficult and dangerous environment. They had
to make a judgment quickly and decisively and that is what they did. I consider
they acted in good faith.''
</TEXT>
