<HEADLINE>A mug's game in royal souvenirs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By LESLEY DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766234</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DID people really buy souvenirs of the newly spliced couple back in 1981?
Apparently, yes. So what would the Charles and Di mugs, plates, wedding photos,
and suchlike be worth today in the wake of the Queen's divorce ultimatum?
Inquiries themselves turned into something of a mug's game. At Sotheby's of
London, a spokeswoman said severely: ``We wouldn't actually sell them, they'd
be too contemporary.''
The message was similar from the Glasgow branch of Phillips. ``We don't deal
with that kind of thing at all. They are not antiques but collectors' items.''
There was an equally negative reaction from Christie's of London. ``We don't
actually deal with royal memorabilia,'' said a spokeswoman.
Mr Sam Chalmers of the Scottish Auction House, Glasgow, confirmed that they
would classify photographs of the royal wedding and commemorative china as
collectors' items, would sell them, but that their auction price was
unpredictable. Would the couple's split make such items more or less valuable?
``Everyone's talking about it,'' Mr Chalmers replied, ``and probably will be
for years to come. But you just don't know the effect of these things.''
The owner of the Kilmarnock firm of Oliver's Antique and Bricabrac Store was
equally forthright: ``We do get stuff like this from house sales, it does sell,
but for a very small price.'' She also pointed out that there was a ``lot of it
made''.
She didn't think that the latest turn of events in the marriage saga would make
any difference: ``I don't see any market for this monetary-wise for quite a
long time.''
So there's little point in rushing to the loft and dusting down images of the
smiling couple. You might as well let the cobwebs gather.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
