<HEADLINE>Tabloids facing contempt charges over Knights case</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766236</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEWSPAPERS which printed articles before the trial of Mr Geoffrey Knights -
boyfriend of EastEnders actress Gillian Taylforth - face contempt proceedings
after a High Court decision yesterday.
Two judges gave the Attorney-General permission to take action against the
Daily Mail, Daily Mirror, the now-defunct Today, the Sun, and the Daily Star
for publishing the articles before Mr Knights was tried on a charge of wounding
with intent Miss Taylforth's driver Martin Davies.
Mr Knights' trial was halted at Harrow Crown Court in October on the grounds
that the ``unfair, outrageous, and oppressive'' publicity meant he would not
get a fair trial.
Mr Justice Popplewell, sitting with Mr Justice Dyson, said after a brief
hearing yesterday - at which the newspapers were not represented - that
Attorney-General Sir Nicholas Lyell could seek fines against the newspapers'
editors and publishers.
Mr Knights, a 41-year-old businessman, was arrested in April for allegedly
assaulting both Miss Taylforth, 39, and her driver. She withdrew her
allegations but the prosecution had intended to obtain a witness summons
against her.
In the days following the arrest and into the following month, a series of
articles appeared about the alleged attack.
The Attorney-General will argue when the case is heard early in the New Year
that the newspapers covered issues which would have gone before a trial jury,
including whether Mr Knights or Mr Davies was the aggressor, or whether Mr
Knights had acted in self-defence, as well as the nature of the relationship
between Miss Taylforth and her driver and the nature and extent of Mr Davies's
injuries.
</TEXT>
