<HEADLINE>Trust reduces job losses to 30</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974766238</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Highland Communities NHS Trust last night announced it would be shedding
the equivalent of 30 full-time jobs in an attempt to deal with a projected
deficit of #1.8m. It plans to save #2.4m.
The trust board, which in October accepted the resignation of chief executive
St John Hattersley having accepted his proposal to shed up to 45 jobs,
yesterday decided to revise its development plan and financial strategy.
It will now be based on three divisions rather than five, giving ``a leaner and
flatter structure.''
In a statement issued last night, the trust said: ``The plan proposes a
reduction in staffing of approximately 28.5 whole time equivalent (WTE) posts.
Eighteen of these are in senior management or administrative posts, with the
balance including ancillary and works posts.
``These changes will take place between now and March 31, 1996, by the
non-filling of vacancies, redeployment, early retirement, or voluntary or
compulsory redundancy.''
Mr Gary Maclennan, Highland regional officer for Unison, said last night: ``We
don't have the detail yet but . . . we will be involved in detailed
consultation which will begin in January.''
Meanwhile, Highland Health Board and Raigmore Hospital NHS Trust yesterday
denied reports it was closing eight surgical beds because of a cash shortage
and denied people were having to wait for vital operations as a result.
Mr Derek Leslie, service standards manager issued a statement on behalf of both
the board and the trust saying: ``There is no question of the Raigmore trust
running out of money and, indeed, the action has been taken in an effort to
best manage resources . . . ''
</TEXT>
