<HEADLINE>Under-age sales</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974766239</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR report regarding Nigel Griffiths's comments on the difficulties
encountered in attempts to use children to purchase alcohol as a means of
identifying retailers who break the law is somewhat misleading (December 13).
It distinguishes alcohol sales to under-age buyers from similar sales of
tobacco, fireworks, videos, etc, on the basis that the child purchaser, as well
as the retailer, commits an offence and implies that the ``test purchase'' by a
supervised child is a successful enforcement method in those other areas.
In relation to tobacco sales to young people, the Scottish Office Home and
Health Department in its guidance to enforcement agencies specifically ruled
out such methods, even where a child and parents were both in agreement with
the exercise.
In all areas of sales to under-age children the problems are further
complicated by Section 428(2) of the Criminal Procedure (Scotland) Act, 1975,
which provides that those who aid, abet, counsel, procure, or incite the
commission of an offence by another are guilty of that same offence.
Trading standards officers would therefore be open to prosecution themselves.
Readers may be further interested to know that the Government, via its
De-regulation Task Force, recently scrapped the legislation that gave local
authorities (ie, trading standards officers) power to exercise control over
firework sales to under-16s, leaving the police as the only enforcement agency.
Inevitably, other more pressing priorities will take precedence, letting
unscrupulous traders off the hook.
If certain areas of the criminal justice system were reformed - not confined to
alcohol sales as Nigel Griffiths appears to suggest - trading standards
officers could effectively enforce legal controls in the retail sector leaving
the police free to deal with ``real'' crime.
Gavin Kenny,
39 Heron Place,
Johnstone.
</TEXT>
