<DATE>951222</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A king without a queen Charles's vow keeps Camilla on the sidelines</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Willam Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974766350</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prince of Wales yesterday ruled out remarriage after his divorce. He will
be a king alone.
His decision, announced by his press secretary, Mr Alan Percival, was coupled
with his decision to obey the Queen's request, given in letters sent on Monday
to him and the Princess of Wales, that they should divorce.
It brings to an end speculation about the future of his relationship with Mrs
Camilla Parker-Bowles, removes the spectre of a future Queen Camilla, and ought
to ensure his eventual accession to the throne.
It also ends talk about his standing down, when the time comes, in favour of
his son, Prince William.
Mrs Parker-Bowles will remain, as she has been for many years, the royal
mistress and she and the prince will be able to be seen in public on private
occasions without comment. Although divorce is no barrier to Prince Charles
becoming king, marrying a divorcee would have met with bitter opposition from
many sections of the Church of England, of which he would then be head, as well
as from many other sections of society.
The Princess of Wales, apparently taken by surprise when the Queen's letters
became public knowledge, indicated she would not be replying until the New
Year. Although she said in her Panorama interview that she did not wish a
divorce, she has no alternative but to do as the Queen wishes.
It will be divorce by consent and, since the Queen's letters have removed the
barrier about her consent being required to the ending of a royal marriage, it
could become effective within a matter of weeks.
The task now is for the couple's lawyers to proceed with the complicated
divorce settlement ensuring adequate financial provision for the princess. This
could take the form of a lump sum of some 15m invested to bring her an annual
income of about 500,000.
The problem is where to find the cash. The prince's wealth comes mainly from
the Duchy of Cornwall's revenues and he has no access to the capital.
The princess will also want the details about her access to their two sons,
William and Harry, clarified, and, while not part of the settlement, there is
the matter of her desire to be a queen of hearts, a roving royal angel of
mercy, to be resolved.
Meanwhile, the prince's decision was applauded by constitutional expert and
former Conservative Cabinet Minister Lord St John of Fawsley as putting duty
and the nation before personal desires.
One leading churchman, the Archdeacon of York, however, warned the prince
against having a relationship with Mrs Parker-Bowles outside marriage. Mrs
Parker-Bowles's brother-in-law, Mr Simon Elliot said she would not be
commenting.
There could be some delay over a decree nisi as the principal lawyers
concerned were away on holiday.
Lord Blake, the constitutional historian and royal adviser, said the prince's
announcement made no difference to constitutional and legal claims to the
throne. "It may affect public opinion. I would have thought it would not damage
his position at all." He added he did not think the princess could stand in the
way of a divorce, "having admitted to 21 million viewers adultery with that
ghastly man".
"The Prince of Wales would have a cast-iron case for bringing a petition
against her. I don't think he would like to do it but I don't think she can
block it indefinitely."
The Dean of St Paul's, the Very Reverend Eric Evans, said many would have
found Mrs Parker-Bowles unsuitable to be Queen because of her role as "the
other woman".
The Archbishop of Canterbury and the Church of England refused to make any
comment on the prince's decision, as did Cardinal Basil Hume and the Roman
Catholic Church.
Deputy Prime Minister Michael Heseltine commented: "Obviously it's a very sad
announcement but I think it had become inevitable..."
Labour Leader Tony Blair said there would have to be discussions about the
future public role the princess would play. "I think most people, myself
included, would want to see, should a divorce take place, some role for
Princess Diana..." Should the princess agree to a divorce by consent it is
expected that she could retain the title, Her Royal Highness, and be known as
Diana, Princess of Wales. Her trump card remains the children. Whatever else
happens, as the mother of William and Harry she will be provided for.
</TEXT>
